<title>USIA: The United States and the WTO</title>
</head><a name="top">
<body>
<p>

<b>TEXT:  U.S. IMPROVES OFFER IN WTO BASIC TELECOM TALKS
<br>(Restrictions on submarine cable landing licenses lifted)</b>

<p> Washington -- The United States has improved its offer to open its market to foreign telecommunications firms in an effort to help bring to conclusion an international accord on basic telecommunications services, says Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Jeffrey Lang.

<p> In a press release issued November 13 by the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative (USTR) in Geneva, Lang said he hopes the new U.S. offer and one from the European Union will provide a basis for other countries to improve their offers on market access to their telecommunications sectors so that an agreement can be reached by the February 1997 deadline.

<p>The new U.S. offer would remove restrictions limiting foreign access to submarine cable landing licenses, he said.  It is the third improvement of U.S. offers in these talks.

<p>Following is the text of the USTR statement:

<p> (begin text)

<p> The United States has again improved its market access commitments in the WTO negotiations on basic telecommunications.

<p> Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Ambassador Jeff Lang announced in Geneva that the United States had removed the restriction limiting access to submarine cable landing licenses.  "As a result," Ambassador Lang stated, "if the negotiations succeed, the U.S. will provide national treatment to WTO members with regard to access to licenses to land submarine cables in accordance with its laws and regulations."

<p> This is the third time the U.S. has improved its offer -- previous improvements included market access and national treatment in the local Telecom services market and adoption of a set of agreed regulatory principles to govern the telecom sector.

<p>The United States also revised its offer so that it is technology neutral and includes all market segments of basic telecommunications services.  These changes do not reflect any substantive change but are in line with a growing consensus among negotiators that schedules should be standardized and should be technology neutral, especially to clarify which members intend to open their satellite-based services markets.

<p>Ambassador Lang noted that "there is not much time left to conclude these negotiations and significant progress must be made by the Singapore Ministerial Conference if we are to succeed by February."  In this connection, Ambassador Lang welcomed the improvements in the offer of the European Union.  "The revised US and European offers provide a solid basis for the United States and the European Union to obtain more and better offers from other WTO members at Singapore," said Ambassador Lang.



<p>(end text)

