<html><head>
<title>USIA: The United States and the WTO</title>
</head><a name="top">
<body>
<p>

<b>TEXT:  GARDNER ON HELMS-BURTON LAW BEFORE WTO DISPUTE PANEL<br>
(Issue poses risks for the new World Trade Organization)</b>

<p>Washington -- Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Booth Gardner says that the European Union's request for a dispute resolution panel within the World Trade Organization (WTO) to discuss the U.S. LIBERTAD Act (Helms-Burton law) concerning Cuba could pose a threat to the organization.

<p>"We do not believe that recourse to a WTO trade panel will lead to a resolution of this dispute," Gardner said in a statement in Geneva before the WTO Dispute Settlement Body November 20.  "On the other hand, we do believe that proceeding further with this matter would pose serious risks for this new and invaluable organization, which is only in the early stages of its development."

<p>Following is the text of the statement:

<p>(begin text)

<p>This matter is on the agenda today as a result of a second request by the European Communities, acting for itself and its Member States, for a dispute settlement panel regarding certain provisions of the LIBERTAD Act and other U.S. measures governing U.S. economic relations with Cuba.  When this matter came before this body a little over a month ago, the United States explained that the measures the EC included in its request for a panel reflect longstanding U.S. foreign policy and security concerns with regard to Cuba.

<p>The LIBERTAD Act, in particular, was enacted in the immediate aftermath of the shootdown by Cuba of two unarmed civil aircraft in broad daylight and without justification, in blatant violation of international law.  The Act is designed to promote a swift transition to democracy in Cuba, a goal that we, the EC, the Member States and many other governments share.

<p>Moreover, certain of the other measures included in the EC's panel request have been in force for some years -- or decades -- and have been expressly justified by the United States under the GATT 1947 as measures taken in pursuit of essential U.S. security interests.

<p>As we said in October, given the foreign and security policy concerns underpinning decades of U.S. relations with Cuba, and in the light of the common interests we share with our European friends in regard to Cuba, the United States is surprised and concerned to find our differences over Cuba raised before a multilateral trade forum.

<p>The United States very much regrets that the Community and the Member States today have seen fit to move those differences one step further in the direction of a WTO panel.

<p>The United States reiterates that our dispute with the Community is not fundamentally a trade matter and thus is not of a nature that we should ask a trade panel to decide.  There is no suggestion that any of the measures raised by the Community reflect trade protectionism.

<p>We do not believe that recourse to a WTO trade panel will lead to a resolution of this dispute.  On the other hand, we do believe that proceeding further with this matter would pose serious risks for this new and invaluable organization, which is only in the early stages of its development.

<p>In closing, the United States would strongly urge the Community to explore other, more appropriate and fruitful avenues for pursuing its interests in this controversy.

<p>(end text)



<p>

