<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SoftQuad//DTD draft HTML 3.2 + extensions for HoTMetaL PRO 3.0 19960923//EN"
 "hmpro3.dtd">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>THE INTERGOVERNMENTAL UNITED STATES - SOUTH AFRICA
BUSINESS DEVELOPMENT COMMITTEE</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">
<H3>TERMS OF REFERENCE  THE INTERGOVERNMENTAL UNITED STATES -
SOUTH AFRICA BUSINESS DEVELOPMENT COMMITTEE
</H3>
<P>I.  	The United States - South Africa Business Development
Committee (the &quot;Committee&quot;) is hereby established by
the Governments of the United States of America and the Republic
of South Africa (the &quot;Parties&quot;) as a bilateral
intergovernment committee to facilitate the development of
commercial relations and related economic matters between the
Parties.  These Terms of Reference are Intended to provide a
general framework to guide cooperation between the Parties.</P> 
<P>II.	The committee will provide advice and guidance to the
Parties, exchange information, and encourage bilateral discus-
sions in the following areas:</P>  
<P>A. Resolving obstacles to trade and investment, identifying
problems and implementing solutions;</P> 
<P>B. Adoption of a project-oriented approach, solving
individual problems where government action or inaction is
affecting a commercial project;
</P>
<P>C. Improving conditions for commercial activity in both
countries;</P> 
<P>D.  Implementation of promotion programs to assist the
respective business communities in their work in the Parties,
markets, including trade missions, exhibits, seminars, and other
events; and,</P> 
<P>E. Consideration of other steps which may be taken to
facilitate and encourage the growth and development of commercial
relations and related economic matters between the Parties.</P>
<P>III.	The Committee will be comprised of two sections, a
United States section and a South African section.  Each section
will be composed of a Chairman and twenty members chosen from
appropriate private trade sectors to represent the views and
interests of particular segments of the business community.  The
members shall be drawn from leading large, medium and small
manufacturing and service companies, trade associations, and
private sector associations involved in the areas of finance and
investments, market access, technical assistance, infrastructure
development, and corporate social responsibility.  Membership
will be balanced across these industry sectors to the maximum
extent possible.  Each Party will appoint the members to its
respective section, and will advise each other of the persons so
designated by each Party in advance of their participation in any
meeting of the Committee.  Each section will formulate and adopt
appropriate procedural rules to govern their respective meetings
outside the Committee.
</P>
<P>IV.     In addition to the twenty private sector members, the
Chairman of a section may at any time, choose, appoint, or invite
any number of government employees or officials from other 
departments, agencies or ministries of the respective
governments, or representatives of other economic actors, to
participate in or advise the section during Committee meetings.</P>
<P>V.      The Committee will work on the basis of mutual
agreement,and will, as necessary, adopt rules of procedure and 
work programs.  The Committee will meet at least annually as
mutually agreed by the Parties, alternately in the United States
and South Africa.  Any measures or recommendations resulting from
the committee or its working groups will specify whether
subsequent approval of the Parties is required.  Any document
mutually agreed upon during the work of the committee will be in
the English language.
</P>
<P>VI.     The Committee will be co-chaired by the Chairman of
each section, who will be, on the United States sides the U.S.
secretary of commerce, and on the South Africa side, the South
African Minister Of Trade and Industry.  Each Chairman will be
responsible for ensuring the views of each section are fully
conveyed within the committee, and will take a leading role in
Committee discussions.   
</P>
<P>VII.	Each chairman will be principally assisted by an
Executive Secretary, named by the chairman, who will arrange the
organizational and other matters in connection with the meetings
of the Council and its working groups.  The Executive Secretaries
may take part in the discussions within their respective
sections, but have no formal vote on matters before the section. 
Unless otherwise appointed by a chairman, the Executive
Secretaries for each section will be, on the United States side,
the Deputy Assistant Secretary of Commerce for Africa, the Near
East and South Asia, and on the South Africa side, the 	. In
addition to their administrative duties within their respective
sections, the Executive Secretaries also will communicate with
each other as necessary to arrange Committee meetings and to
ensure the smooth functioning of work between meetings.  Agendas
for Committee meetings will be agreed upon not later than one
month prior to a scheduled Committee meeting.</P> 
<P>VIII. 	The committee will have an Executive Committee, also
co- chaired by the Chairman of each section.  In addition to the
chairmen, membership of the Executive Committee will consist of
the Executive Secretaries of the Committee, co-chairs of working
groups, and representatives of government agencies, U.S.
Government departments or South African Government ministries, as
appropriate, when invited by the Chairman of a section.  The
Executive Committee's functions will include:</P> 
<P>A. Identification of, and removal strategies for, obstacles
to bilateral trade and investment;</P> 
<P>B. Organization and coordination of the committees work
between Committee meetings;
</P>
<P>C. Planning and organizing the annual meetings of the
Committee; and
</P>
<P>D. Consideration of proposals for amending the structure of
the Committee.</P>  
<P>IX.   The Co-chairman of the Committee will, as mutually
agreed, establish joint working groups to consider and report on
specific matters.  The Committee will determine the assignments
of such working groups,  which will conduct their work in
accordance with the instructions of the Committee.  Working
groups will be staffed by interested members from each section of
the committee to provide advice and information in the specific
areas including:</P>   
<P>A.  Finance and Investment --strategies for resolving
problems where government action or inaction is  affecting
company proposals;
</P>
<P>B.  Bilateral Market Access --recommendations for   fostering
understanding of the trade regulations of  the Parties'
respective trading systems as well as identification of the trade
barriers in the respective             systems and proposals for
removal of such barriers from each system as necessary to create
a freer flow of two- way trade;</P>  
<P>C.  Technical Assistance -- proposals for developing means of
assisting the commercial expansion of the South African economy
and the growth of the business sectors relating to disadvantages
communities;
</P> 
<P>D.   Infrastructure Development -- proposals to assist the
delivery of essential services beyond traditional urban areas;
and
</P>
<P>E.   Role of the Private Sector in the New South Africa --
proposals to advance the dialogue on the subject of corporate
social responsibility, within the context of a sovereign South
Africa developing it's domestic laws.	 At the first meeting of
each working group, co-chairs will be named by the respective
section chairmen, one from each section.  The co-chairs will be
responsible for arranging working group meetings, agendas, and
final reports.
</P>
<P>X.    Expenses incidental to the meetings of the Committee,
the Executive Committee, and any working group established by the
committee will be borne by the government of the host country.
Members will serve on the Committee without compensation for
their participation in Committee activities.  Travel expenses
from one country to the other, as well as living and other
personal expenses of representatives participating in meetings of
the Committee and any working group will be borne by the
committee	members.
</P>
<P>XI.   These Terms of Reference may be amended by mutual
agreement	of the Parties at any Committee meeting or during the
periods between the meetings of the Committee.
</P>
<P>DONE in duplicate at Atlanta, Georgia, June 4, 1994.
</P>
<P>FOR THE GOVERNMENT OF THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA: <BR>Ronald
H. Brown <BR>Secretary of Commerce	  </P>           
<P>FOR THE GOVERNMENT OF THE REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA: <BR>Trevor
Manuel <BR>Minister of Trade and Industry</P>    	              
                                 
