<html><head>
<title>USIA: The United States and the WTO</title>
</head><a name="top">
<body>
<p>

<b>TEXT: U.S. AGRICULTURE SECRETARY GLICKMAN ON WTO MINISTERIAL<br>
(Praises reconfirmed commitment on agriculture)</b><br>

<p>Washington -- Secretary of Agriculture Dan Glickman has praised trade ministers meeting in Singapore for reaffirming their commitment to conduct negotiations on agricultural trade starting in 1999.

<p>Glickman made the statement December 13 upon conclusion of the World Trade Organization (WTO) ministerial meeting.  He said the Singapore Declaration from that meeting assures that momentum continues in reducing barriers in agriculture trade.

<p>Following is the text of Glickman's statement:

<p>(begin text)

<p>A major step was taken today in Singapore that will enable American agriculture to count on more open world markets in the future.  The first Ministerial Conference of the World Trade Organization endorsed a continuation of trade reforms in agriculture, initiated in the Uruguay Round two years ago, through a preparatory process that will lead to a new market-opening negotiations in 1999.
I am pleased that the world trading community recognized the importance of a strong reaffirmation of the agreement reached by trade ministers in Marrakesh in 1994 to begin discussions on further liberalization of agriculture trade even before implementation of the Uruguay Round agreement is finished in the year 2000.
This process will enable us to continue our efforts to further reduce import barriers, establish disciplines on state trading enterprises, eliminate export subsidies and remove unjustifiable sanitary and phytosanitary regulations.  With the growing importance of world markets to U.S. agriculture, it is vital that momentum to expand opportunities be maintained.  The Singapore Declaration will ensure that this happens.
While we gear up to move this effort forward next year in Geneva, we will also continue our efforts to ensure full implementation of commitments in existing agreements, whether multilateral, regional, or bilateral.  We will continue our efforts, using all the tools available to us, to respond to exorbitantly high tariffs, such as those maintained by Canada in a number of commodities, unjustified sanitary and phytosanitary regulations, and other trade-distorting measures around the world.
I would like to express my appreciation to Acting U.S. Trade Representative, Charlene Barshefsky, who headed the U.S. delegation in Singapore, for her successful efforts in ensuring that agriculture remains a top priority in the WTO process.  I would also like to thank the members of the U.S. private sector who participated in the Ministerial process.  Their contribution clearly had a major positive impact on the outcome of the talks.
(end text)


<p>

<p>Return to <A HREF = "singpg.htm"> The WTO Singapore Meeting</A>.</ul>
<p>Return to <A HREF = "wto.htm">Return to U.S.-WTO Home Page</A>.</ul>
</body>
</html>
