<title>New York Universities - Environment</title>
</head><P>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#006633"VLINK="#990033">
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><P>

<B><center><h1>New York</h1></center><p><P>
<P>
<IMG SRC =
"blkrule.gif"><P>
<a href="http://www.alfred.edu">Alfred
University</A><P>

Alfred University, Environmental Studies Program,<BR>
Saxon Drive, Alfred, NY 14802<BR>
(607, 871-2205; Fax: 607, 871-2342; E-mail:
ens@bigvax.alfred.edu)<P>
Founded: 1971.<P>
The program
offers undergraduate degree in multidisciplinary
environmental studies in a liberal arts setting.  Students can
focus on either natural or social sciences, and many take a
second major in biology, geology, political science, economics,
etc. The program is supervised by fifteen faculty members from
different disciplines.<P>
Director: DR. GORDON L.
GODSHALK<P>
Publication: Newsletter<P>
<P>
<IMG SRC =
"blkrule.gif"><P>
<a
href="http://www.bard.edu/info/areainfo/index.htm">Bard
College</A><P>

Bard College, Graduate School in Environmental Studies, Bard
College, Annandale-on-Hudson, NY 12504-5000<P>
An
interdisciplinary graduate program that combines training in
the natural and social sciences. Students receive a masters in
science in environmental studies after two summers of intensive
course work and a third season completing a research thesis. 
Recent thesis projects have included multinational corporations
and environmental responsibility; habitat utilization of a local
endangered species; population growth rates of marine fishes; and
sociological analysis of a small rural town.<P>
Director: JANE L.
WOLFSON, Ph.D. (914, 758-7483)<P>
Administrative Assistant: ELIZABETH SIMONSON (914, 758-7483)<P>

<P>
<IMG SRC = "blkrule.gif"><P>
<a
href="http://www.library.csi.cuny.edu/">College of Staten
Island</A><P>

Environmental Science Masters Program and Center for
Environmental Science, 65-308, College of Staten Island, City
University of New York, 2800 Victory Blvd., Staten Island, NY
10314 (718, 982-3921; Fax: 718, 982-3852)<P>
An interdisciplinary
program including ecology, geology,
chemistry, environmental engineering, and computer modeling. The
objective of the masters program is to expose the students to the
scientific principles underlying environmental problems.  The
Center carries out research on wetlands, park planning, air
pollution, waste disposal, environmental epidemiology, and risk
analysis.  The masters program was started in 1972 and the Center
in 1987.  Five full-time faculty are involved.<P>
Director,
