<html><head>
<title>USIA: The United States and the WTO</title>
</head><a name="top">
<body>
<p>

<b>TEXT:  USTR'S STOLER ON TRADE AND LABOR STANDARDS
<br>(Calls for fundamental human rights in the workplace)</b><br>

<p>Singapore -- The United States is aiming to help the World Trade Organization (WTO) recognize the intrinsic relationship between trade and international labor standards so that the WTO can gain the confidence of workers, a U.S. trade official says.

<p>Andrew Stoler, the deputy chief of mission in the U.S. Trade Representative's Office in Geneva, said December 8 that "only trade bureaucrats can make a distinction between trade liberalization and the concerns of people in the workplace."

<p>Speaking to the International Confederation of Free Trade Unions (ICFTU) the day before the opening of the WTO's first ministerial meeting December 9-13 here, Stoler said "If we cannot mobilize support for more global trade, at risk is the ability to increase trade further, and at some point, the globalization that trade bureaucrats take for granted will become threatened."

<p>Stoler was speaking for Acting U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky, who had to cancel because of trade negotiations in Tokyo.

<p>In Singapore, the Clinton administration is seeking the creation of a WTO working group to examine the issue of trade and labor standards, as mandated by U.S. trade legislation.  They have encountered resistance from several nations, who fear that such a working group could result in the creation of new multilateral rules that would erode the competitive edge gained by low labor costs.

<p>Stoler stressed that the United States is not seeking a global minimum wage or protectionism.  Rather, he said, when the U.S. talks about core labor standards, it is referring to fundamental human rights in the workplace: freedom of association, the right to collective bargaining, the prohibition on forced labor, the prohibition of exploitative child labor and the prohibition on discrimination.

<p>"The issue will not go away, and refusal to recognize it could, over time, truncate and distort the ability of the WTO to accomplish its mission," Stoler said.

<p>The following is the text of Stoler's statement as delivered:

<p>(begin text)

<p>Ambassador Barshefsky asked me to convey her regrets that she cannot be here this morning because she was forced to stay in Tokyo for negotiations yesterday.  Regrettably, her plane landed just a few hours ago but she asked me to assure you that she is fighting your fight.  Ambassador Barshefsky asked me to thank Mr. Jordan (the Secretary General ICFTU) for inviting her to be here today.  We share an important objective here.  And that is to help the WTO and all those interested in more and freer trade understand the importance of the intrinsic relationship between trade and the issue of improving labor standards internationally.

<p>We are making some progress.  In the next few days we will work with our trading partners to achieve an outcome that reflects the importance of this issue.  What's at stake?  Ultimately, the confidence of the very constituencies who must come to support trade agreements and market-opening initiatives.  What we are looking for here is a basic expression of values and a commitment to address the common concerns of workers around the world, whether they make computers or cars, work in mines, serve meals, clean buildings or load ships.

<p>We have no illusion that our efforts to achieve recognition of the importance of labor standards and trade will come easily.  There is resistance within the WTO.  Regrettably, there are a number of nations that are unwilling to provide a rightful role for the WTO on this issue.

<p>A few months ago Ambassador Barshefsky enlisted John Sweeney, the newly elected leader of the AFL-CIO, to work with her and use every forum to outline the importance of this effort.  With his efforts and others, there is a broader understanding about the importance of core labor standards but we have more work to do.

<p>It is worth making the distinction of what we re not talking about:  We are not talking about seeking a global minimum wage.  We are not talking about protectionism.  We all recognize that global trade is a necessary catalyst to improve wages and working conditions, and enhance wealth.

<p>When we talk about core labor standards, what we are talking about are fundamental human rights in the workplace:
-- Freedom of association,
-- The right to collective bargaining,
-- The prohibition on forced labor,
-- The prohibition of exploitative child labor, and
-- The prohibition on discrimination.

<p>What we are seeking is not revolutionary, but a simple recognition in the WTO of the responsibilities all WTO member nations have committed to in the International Labor Organization and other fora.  Why isn't that enough?  Because only trade bureaucrats can make a distinction between trade liberalization and the concerns of people in the workplace.  I know because I've been trying to explain this now practically every day since April.  The WTO has a responsibility to work with other international institutions, principally the ILO, to improve the lives of workers.

<p>Ambassador Barshefsky has been very clear.  Our trading partners must recognize these concerns because they are not going to go away.  We cannot hide from our basic moral responsibility here.

<p>The Problem

<p>What we are talking about in acknowledging our responsibilities to address core labor rights is not a hypothetical political battle.  This is a very real and immediate concern as studies by the OECD and ILO have concluded.

<p>In the last 20 years, by many indices, we are actually losing ground in this effort.  The ILO study indicates, for example, that 250 million children are working in developing countries.  Some 120 million are working full-time.  Most are in agriculture or domestic service, but many are working in deplorable manufacturing conditions with severe consequences.

<p>In some countries, death rates caused by exposure to poison chemicals and compounds among children actually exceeds death rates from childhood illnesses.

<p>Problems in labor standards do not simply fall upon children.  We know through our investigations that worker rights in Asian countries and in our own hemisphere are not what they should be.  I do want to assure you however that the Clinton administration through our GSP program has contributed to progress on working conditions in a number of countries.

<p>To be sure our work is just beginning.  The United States cannot do this job alone which is precisely why we brought this issue to the WTO.  The ILO has established a working party on the social dimensions of the liberalization of international trade.  The formal involvement of the WTO would add significantly to the commitment of the ILO.

<p>What the reports and our own experience tell us are as follows:

<p>First, observance and protection of core labor rights will enhance economic development around the world, and that is an objective in which all of us have an interest.

<p>Second, trade liberalization and effective implementation of core labor standards are mutually enforcing.

<p>The American Experience

<p>At the risk of sounding a bit chauvinistic, let me outline why I feel so strongly about this issue.  Increased trade is good for America.  We have only in the past year seen the first substantial wage and standard of living gains after two decades of relative stagnation.

<p>Trade is a big part of that equation.  In just the past five years, trade has moved from 25 percent to more than 30 percent of our GDP.  Jobs related to trade pay 15 percent more than jobs in the rest of the economy.  We now have 11 million jobs dependent upon trade.

<p>Yet Americans do not believe that they are seeing economic benefits from trade.  They support more exports, but do not believe that trade agreements -- which are necessary to open markets for exports -- are good for them.

<p>This disconnect is not just an American phenomenon.  It is a global problem.  If we cannot mobilize support for more global trade, at risk is the ability to increase trade further, and at some point, the globalization that trade bureaucrats take for granted will become threatened.  Here again the WTO could be part of the solution.

<p>Toward a Solution

<p>Labor conditions are determined by both political and economic factors.  Just as global market-opening initiatives should be multilateral in nature, so should initiatives to improve labor conditions.

<p>We believe it is in the long-term interests of the WTO to acknowledge the relationship between trade and labor conditions, much as it has begun a dialogue to explore the relationship between trade and the environment.  This initiative will be good for the global trading system, it will be good for workers.  Let me quote the director of the ILO in saying, what we are seeking is "to bring back into focus the objectives of fundamental labor standards and social progress... we should reject a single-minded insistence on trade sanctions or an inflexible resistance to any link between labor standards and trade."

<p>What we are really looking for here is common ground.  This issue will not go away, and refusal to recognize it could, over time, truncate and distort the ability of the WTO to accomplish its own mission.

<p>Conferences such as this one the ICFTU has organized are immensely helpful to these efforts.  Be assured, we will continue to work with you to advance concerns about worker rights in the context of global trade at the WTO and wherever we might more this issue forward.

<p>Speaking for Ambassador Barshefsky, I very much appreciate the contributions you are making here.  Thank you.

<p>(End text)


<p>

