<body>
<p>

<b>TEXT:  DEPUTY USTR LANG 10/7 PRESS STATEMENT IN BANGKOK<br>
(Open telecom markets depend on Asian WTO members)</b>

<p>Bangkok -- The World Trade Organization (WTO) telecommunications services negotiations cannot succeed without market-opening commitments from the high-growth countries of Asia, according to Jeffrey Lang, deputy U.S. Trade Representative.

<p>In an October 7 statement in Bangkok, Lang pointed out that WTO members from Eastern Europe and Latin America have already offered to provide market access across all basic telecommunications service sectors without significant limits on foreign investment.  He added that 31 countries have adopted "a common set of enforceable regulatory commitments that will be crucial to assure real market access."

<p>"We are looking for offers from the powerful economies of Southeast Asia that build on the progress each country has made to date in opening telecom services markets," he said.

<p>In addition to the telecommunications services talks, the United States would like to see discussion of labor standards, transparency in government procurement, and an Information Technology Agreement (ITA) at the December 9-13 WTO Singapore Ministerial Conference, Lang said.

<p>According to Lang, the ITA would reduce tariffs to zero by the year 2000 for semiconductors computers, telecommunications equipment and other components of the Global Information Infrastructure.

<p>Following is the official text of Lang's statement, as prepared for delivery:

<p>(begin official text)

<p>OCTOBER 7, 1996

<p>PRESS STATEMENT BY AMBASSADOR JEFFREY M.  LANG

<p>DEPUTY UNITED STATES TRADE REPRESENTATIVE

<p>BANGKOK, THAILAND

<p>I have just completed a visit to four ASEAN countries -- Singapore, Malaysia, Indonesia and Thailand -- to brief Ministers and my colleagues in trade, telecom and foreign ministries on the results of the latest meeting of the Quadrilateral Trade Ministers, which took place in Seattle on September 26 to 28.  The Quad is composed of the trade ministers of the United States, the European Union, Japan and Canada.  My ASEAN colleagues and I discussed the details of several initiatives that are crucial to the success of the Singapore Ministerial Conference of the World Trade Organization.  The Singapore Ministerial will take place on December 9 to 13.

<p>Assistant U.S. Trade Representative Bob Cassidy will travel to the Philippines in a few days on a similar mission.

<p>At Seattle, the Quad ministers broke two "log-jams" among the industrialized countries.

<p>-- First, Acting United States Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky, Sir Leon Brittan of the European Union, and MITI Minister Tsukahara of Japan agreed on terms whereby the European Union will join in multilateral negotiations at the WTO to commit to zero tariffs for semiconductors and other information technology products.  This is the proposed Information Technology Agreement, which would reduce tariffs to zero, by the year 2000, not only for semiconductors, but also for computers, telecom equipment and other components of the Global Information Infrastructure.  In return for the E.U.'s commitment to negotiate an ITA, the Semiconductor Council meeting scheduled for January will be postponed until March.

<p>-- Second, Ambassador Barshefsky and Sir Leon announced their intention to respond positively, in advance of the Singapore Ministerial, to each other's requests for improvement of their respective offers in WTO negotiations on basic telecommunications services.  These negotiations have a deadline of February 15, 1997.  Japan and Canada also confirmed in Seattle their intentions to review their telecom services offers and to make their best efforts to improve those offers before the Singapore Ministerial.  The Quad partners agreed to take these market-opening steps in telecom goods and services on a MFN, or Most Favored Nation basis, conditional on successful multilateral talks among all the members of the WTO.

<p>The focus of the global trade community therefore shifts next to Asia, the fastest-growing region in the world, and a region where the importance of expanding and improving telecommunications infrastructure is widely recognized.  Our chances for successful multilateral agreements to open global markets for telecom goods and services will depend, to a great extent, on how the WTO members of Asia will approach these issues as we prepare for the Singapore Ministerial.

<p>I had detailed discussions today with senior officials of the Commerce Ministry, the Foreign Ministry, and the Ministry of Transport and Communications.  We discussed our mutual objectives for the Singapore Ministerial, including

<p>-- the Information Technology Agreement;

<p>-- the WTO telecom services talks;

<p>-- transparency in government procurement; and,

<p>-- providing an opportunity for a discussion of labor standards at the WTO.

<p>We also discussed a variety of other issues, including intellectual property, insurance and the APEC meetings scheduled for next month in Manila.

<p>Let me review the main points.

<p>First, on government procurement, the United States is proposing negotiations on an interim agreement among all WTO members that would provide for greater transparency.  In many countries, the largest purchaser is the government.  Transparency in procurement is a first step to opening this huge market.

<p>Second, on labor standards, the Quad proposals are modest, but necessary.  The WTO increasingly is seen as a forum for resolution of industry's economic interests, but in isolation from the interests of ordinary working people.  The United States is suggesting that the members agree to discuss labor standards at the WTO, without preconditions as to further steps beyond a discussion.  We aim for a discussion that would not prejudice to the primary role of the International Labor Organization in the field of labor standards, and that would explicitly bar issues of wage rates and any pretexts for protectionism.

<p>Third, I have found receptivity in this part of the world to the proposed Information Technology Agreement, because most countries in the region are exporters of these products, as is the United States.  But the ITA opportunity has to be grasped quickly, or it could be lost.  Experts from ASEAN and other countries have been invited to a meeting in Geneva on Friday, October 10, to begin what we hope will be a speedy process to agree on the crucial details of product coverage and tariff phase-out.  The Quad countries explicitly left the door open to contributions from other countries on these details.

<p>Finally, the WTO telecom services negotiations cannot succeed without market-opening commitments from the high-growth countries of Asia.  The telecom services offers made so far by WTO members in Eastern Europe and Latin America are superior to the offers that have been made by WTO members in Asia.  Those other offers -- for example, by Argentina, Hungary, Brazil, and others in those regions -- provide market access across all basic telecom services sectors at an early date, without significant limits on foreign investment.  Moreover, thirty-one countries have adopted a common set of enforceable regulatory commitments that will be crucial to assure real market access.

<p>We are looking for offers from the powerful economies of Southeast Asia that build on the progress each country has made to date in opening telecom services markets.

<p>(end official text)



<p>

