<html><head>
<title>USIA: The United States and the WTO</title>
</head><a name="top">
<body>
<p>

<b>TRANSCRIPT: HILLS ON WTO MINISTERIAL IN SINGAPORE
<br>(Former USTR predicts ITA negotiations will succeed)</b><br>

<p>Washington -- Carla Hills, who was U.S. trade representative in the Bush administration, predicts that trade ministers meeting in Singapore in days ahead will approve some sort of information technology agreement, a top U.S. objective.

<p>Hills made the prediction December 6 at the National Press Club in remarks setting the background for the World Trade Organization (WTO) ministerial-level meeting in Singapore December 9-13.

<p>She also expects the ministers at Singapore to approve some weak statement on the controversial issue of labor standards.  She predicted negotiators will conclude in early 1997 an agreement on basic telecommunications services, an agreement that has so far proved elusive.  And she suggested that a few European and Asian countries would likely block preparatory work on WTO agricultural negotiations that are scheduled to start in 1999.

<p>Following is a transcript of Hills' remarks:

<p>(begin transcript)

<p>HILLS:  I've been asked to talk about and give you a framework for the World Trade Organization's meeting in Singapore.  As Peter Hickman said, it's going to be a crowded affair.  Over 160 nations will be represented there: 127 members of the World Trade Organization, or the WTO, plus 34 observer nations.  In addition, there will be some 49 observer international organizations, including 14 international organizations from the IMF to the World Bank, various regional development banks, and the United Nations and its various agencies.  So it's not a small meeting.

<p>I think with this audience, you know what the WTO is: basically, an extension of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, which is nearing its 50th anniversary.  Under the GATT, the trading nations of the world slashed their tariffs from an average of 40 percent down to below 5 percent today.  And that has caused world trade to mushroom, and with it, it has raised standards of living for people all around the world and has created economic opportunity.

<p>In the early '80s, led by the United States, the GATT members decided that the GATT needed to be modernized and strengthened, as it only covered goods and there were rapidly growing sectors, such as services and agriculture, high technology, which needed the protection of intellectual property, and investment, where there were no internationally agreed norms.

<p>And so we started the Uruguay Round of multilateral trade talks in 1986, and that resulted in 1994 in dozens of new agreements containing thousands of tariff cuts and new obligations covering services, intellectual property right protections, protections for investment, and that was fine.  A number of legal texts were signed by over 100 nations.  And one of the agreements created the World Trade Organization as a successor of the GATT, but kept the GATT to cover trade and goods.  And the question before you is, at two years what has the WTO clearly accomplished?

<p>Well, two years is probably too short a period to have a conclusive evaluation of the accomplishments of the WTO, particularly as many of its commitments are ongoing and are being phased in.  Still, let me give you a half a dozen examples of where I think the WTO has made substantial improvement over its predecessor organization.

<p>First, it has far broader coverage.  Its 29 legal texts cover things like services.  That was important to the United States, as we're the largest provider of services worldwide, selling some $200 billion per year in services.  The World Trade Organization for the first time has agreed to cut agricultural subsidies and to convert quantitative barriers to tariffs and then proceed to cut them.  And the WTO members for the first time agreed to rules to protect patents, trademarks, copyrights, and trade secrets.  And it agreed to strengthen the GATT trading rules by requiring the WTO members to sign all of the legal texts.  No picking and choosing as was done under the GATT.  And so if you signed one, you signed all.  And that is a rule that has applied save for one area, namely procurement.  And when the agreement is finally implemented, the old area of goods will have further benefit because the tariff in the area of goods has been cut by an additional 45 -- probably about an additional third.  And in 45 percent of the area of industrial goods they have eliminated tariffs altogether, including important sectors like pharmaceuticals, paper, and furniture, all important areas to the United States.

<p>Dispute settlement under the WTO mechanism is much clearer and much faster, and I think is generally recognized as an area of extraordinary success.  As of early November worldwide there had been 62 consultations over trade differences.

<p>The United States has been a plaintiff in 21 and a respondent in nine.  We've won or settled four.  There are 16 pending.  We've lost two cases, and I think those who studied them thought that they were legitimate outcomes.  And we have had some settlements outside the system as a result of the filing.  So that this is a success story, I think, for reducing trade friction.

<p>And finally, the WTO, unlike the GATT, creates a permanent institutional structure so that a trade minister could bring to the over 100 trading nations a new idea for an international norm and without having to start a whole massive round of trade talks.  That is the door through which the newer issues have come -- labor, environment and competition policy.  And they will continue to come.  And the fact that they're contentious at the outset and the secretary- general is having difficulty getting a consensus is not surprising.  After all, the United States wanted to start the Uruguay Round in 1982, and it wasn't till 1986 that it was launched.  So it takes a while to develop a consensus.

<p>Now, what will the ministers discuss at Singapore?  Well, I think the focus will be on implementation of these various WTO commitments, including the unfinished business that was left over from the Uruguay Round and the so-called built-in agenda where the WTO members agreed to negotiate in the future in a number of areas.  And here let me mention a few.

<p>Basic telecommunications.  This negotiation covers a $500 billion global market.  They're scheduled to conclude in February of '97.  The original deadline of April of 1996 was extended because only 11 nations were willing to match the U.S. offer.  Latin America and Eastern Europe would have agreed to our offer, but they wanted somewhere between one and five years.  There were no comparable offers from the Asia nations.  And the current reports are the negotiations are going very well.  Were I a betting person, I would think that you would reach in early '97 a resolution.

<p>Secondly, financial services: Negotiations are expected to resume in financial services next year.  Negotiations reached an interim agreement that was signed in August and -- May -- the interim agreement went into force in August of this year.  And it is subject to review and withdrawal at the end of next year.  The United States complained that the agreement failed to lock in rights that currently exist in many of the developing countries, particularly the right to maintain majority ownership of financial institutions.  Companies that had bought 80 percent of a company were told that under the accord, the host government could have reduced that percentage down to below 50 percent, and so, in effect, it would be a closure of the market.  I think that there will be an enormous effort this year to persuade particularly the nations in Latin America and Asia to make better offers for the financial services sector.

<p>In maritime services, the United States walked away from the negotiations this past June.  Only 36 nations made commitments, and they did agree to suspend negotiations until the year 2000.

<p>On services generally, there will be a round of services negotiation covering all sorts of services, to begin in the year 2000, in hopes that nations will put on the table services beyond tourism, information, health, which are already covered.

<p>And agriculture, always a contentious area:  Another round is scheduled, under the terms of the agreement, to begin in 1999.  The OECD estimates that farm subsidies and supports still cost the consumer about $350 billion a year.  The United States and the 14 members of the Cairns group, which includes the seven ASEAN nations and several Latin American nations, and Australia, want work to start in anticipation of the negotiations in 1999.  They'd like that work to begin in 1997.  Korea, Japan, and the European Union resist.  So if I were a betting person I would say there'd be very little likelihood that much work is going to be done before the deadline of 1999.

<p>The major addition to this built-in agenda and the unfinished agenda has already been mentioned, and that's the information technology agreement.  This is a high priority for the United States.  We are seeking staged reductions in tariffs, hopefully down to zero, on a variety of items -- computers, LAN equipment, supercomputers, semiconductors -- by the year 2000.  The Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum endorsed the concept.  Certain of the APEC nations felt that the coverage was not in line with what they had hoped, and some had some difficulty with the timetable.  But I think that there will be a discussion of this, a hearty discussion of this at Singapore, and I would expect that they would be able to reach some agreement.

<p>Then accession has already been mentioned.  You know, another one of the big successes of the WTO is the desire of so many of these nations that have transitory economies that have come from statism into a market concept want to get into the WTO.  And there are currently 34 applications pending for admission, including applications from China, Taiwan, Vietnam, Saudi Arabia, and Russia.  And each one of these applications presents challenging issues.

<p>Then finally the ministers are going to have to deal with the so-called newer issues, which are contentious.  And let me mention three or four in a descending level of contention.

<p>First, labor standards.  The secretary general, Renato Ruggiero, had proposed in his draft declaration that he would mention labor standards.  The ASEAN nations, Brazil and Egypt strongly oppose.  The United States says it's not going to sign this declaration unless there is some mention to core labor standards.  And sources say that the European Union, Japan and Australia are willing to have a mention but -- and are not insisting on any particular wording.  So the question is, will there be a mention.  And I would suspect that they could resolve that with some mention.  The draft language already is just very, very gentle.  It talks in terms of the International Labor Organization having primary jurisdiction in this area and more should be done.

<p>Secondly is investments.  Good progress is being made in the OECD on a multilateral agreement on investment.  Secretary General Ruggiero has proposed that the WTO also take up work on investment.  The U.S.  would like the OECD to conclude its work before the WTO does anything in depth, and you've got a split among the developing nations.  Some developing nations don't want the WTO to touch the subject, investment.  They would like unilaterally to make the rules for their own dealings with foreign investors.  Others would like to have some discussion in the WTO, fearing that if the Organization of Economic Cooperation and Development, which is the rich man's club, comes to a resolution on an investment agreement and without their input, that it may not serve their interests.  So you've got a dichotomy there in the developing world, some preferring that the WTO step up to it and have an investment arrangement, others not wanting any organization to have an investment agreement that would deal with their interests.

<p>The environment was thought to be a contentious issue and has turned out not to be so contentious.  The declaration will mention the report of the Committee on Trade and the Environment, and probably the ministers will ask the WTO to continue its work.  Basically, the committee's report, which was filed in early November, calls for cooperation between the WTO and institutions that enforce multilateral environmental agreements.  The report sidestepped the most controversial area, such as the use of trade sanctions to enforce environmental norms.  The report suggests that disputes among the parties to a multilateral environmental accord be handled under that accord although the parties would retain their WTO rights, which raises the question of what happens when there's an inconsistency.  And language was dropped which would have called upon the WTO members to ensure that the trade measures enacted in any multilateral environmental accord be consistent with the WTO.

<p>(end transcript)



<p>

