<html><head>
<title>USIA: The United States and the WTO</title>
</head><a name="top">
<body>
<p>

<b>TEXT: USTR POSITION PAPER ON THE BANANA ISSUE
<br>(Urges equitable handling of U.S., Latin American banana exports)</b><br>

<p>
WASHINGTON -- The following is the text of a U.S. Trade Representative (USTR) position paper on the question of the international banana trade:

<p>
Office of the United States Trade Representative

<p>The Banana Issue

<p>There are many misconceptions about U.S. policy, about what this case is about and about what a WTO case means.  To briefly summarize this very complex issue: The United States, Mexico, Ecuador, Honduras and Guatemala are engaged in a WTO dispute settlement to try to end the trade-distorting method the EU uses to discriminate against U.S. and Latin American distribution companies and banana exports from Latin American countries.  Chiquita, Dole Foods and Delmonte support an end to the EU banana regime.

<p>-- The United States has major interests in the Caribbean, as well as in Latin America.  We and the Caribbean share important goals: security, orderly movement of people and control of migration, protection of the environment, the expansion of trade and investment and improved living standards.  These interests are best served by long-term and broad-based economic growth and political stability in the Caribbean.

<p>-- USG goals with respect to EC banana regulations are to: promote economic growth in the region, remove illegal discrimination, keep international commitments, reform the existing banana regime, and encourage continued diversification of Caribbean economies.

<p>-- The EU regime has deprived Latin American countries of market share and export growth in the EU and has taken business away from U.S. and Latin American banana marketing firms.

<p>-- The WTO banana case will not require the EU to end all types of trade preferences or financial assistance to the Caribbean and is not a threat to Caribbean banana production.

<p>-- A reformed EU banana regime could maintain tariff preferences for Caribbean producers, encourage diversification and help these producers become competitive without imposing gratuitous discrimination against non-European marketing firms.

<p>-- Before the new EU regulations went into effect in 1993, only three EU member states -- France, the U.K. and Spain -- sharply limited the supply of Latin American bananas; now the entire 15 countries of the EU do.

<p>-- A WTO panel that found the EU's banana regulations to be inconsistent with WTO agreements would not require the EU to end all assistance for the Caribbean, but would call upon the EU to bring its banana regulations into conformity with agreed rules of international trade.

<p>-- The five countries that brought the WTO action have expressed their commitment to a healthy Caribbean banana presence in the EU.  There are ways to accomplish this objective without impeding the exports and distribution services of other Western Hemisphere producers and marketing companies.

<p>-- The United States is ready to work with the EU to help the Caribbean producers in a way that does not hurt U.S. companies and Latin American producers.  There are better ways to accomplish this objective than the EU's regulations, as our alternatives paper points out.

<p>
Banana Alternatives Summary

<p>-- We believe that it is in the best interest of the Caribbean, Latin America, the United States and the international trading system for the EU to pursue WTO-consistent policies that focus on the needs and capabilities of banana-producing countries.

<p>-- Given the ability of most African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) countries to compete, EU assistance should be focused on those countries that need it.  The Caribbean nations of the Windward Islands (St. Vincent and the Grenadines, Dominica, Grenada, and St. Lucia) are not near being competitive, in part because of their special circumstances and in part because EU regulations have stifled incentives to become competitive.

<p>-- EU regulations have also been a disincentive to diversification.  It is likely that the preference system itself has discouraged investment in alternative crops.

<p>-- While Windward Island producers must continue to work toward dramatically improving efficiency and quality of production, the EU banana regulation must be reformed to help to prepare the Windward producers for competitiveness when the current Lome banana protocol expires.

<p>-- The U.S. respects the EU commitment undertaken in its Lome agreements to promote development of ACP countries through access to its market.  We do not object to a continuation of tariff preferences for the Windward Islands and other ACP banana producers.

<p>-- However, we do object to EU banana regulations that are inconsistent with the agreed rules of international trade and are not consistent with the terms of the WTO waiver for the banana tariff preferences.

<p>-- There are many WTO-consistent paths to reach the objective of economic growth for Windward Island banana producers through WTO-consistent tariff preferences, technical assistance or financial aid.  Other ways:

<p>-- Develop human resources in the Windward Islands through education.

<p>-- Explore alternatives such as information technologies.

<p>-- Finance pilot projects and starter-plots for alternative crops.

<p>-- Provide a WTO-consistent income support subsidy.

<p>-- Introduce a buy-out scheme calculated to encourage inefficient producers to look for alternatives.

<p>-- The EU collects $300 million annually in tariff revenue from Latin American bananas.  The EU could consider expanding its diversification program and use some of the banana tariff proceeds to finance such programs.

<p>-- It is important to begin work now on implementing such measures and reforming the current regime to benefit all affected countries in the region.  The United States stands ready, as it always has, to work with the EU, the Caribbean, and Latin America in developing a WTO-consistent approach toward this end.


<p>

<p>Return to <A HREF = "wtotxtpg.htm"> Texts and Remarks</A>.</ul>
<p>Return to <A HREF = "wto.htm">Return to U.S.-WTO Home Page</A>.</ul>
</body>
