<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SoftQuad//DTD draft HTML 3.2 + extensions for HoTMetaL PRO 3.0 19960802//EN" "hmpro3.dtd">
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>THE U.S.-SOUTH AFRICA BINATIONAL COMMISSION</TITLE></HEAD><BODY
BGCOLOR="#FDFFFF" TEXT="#000000">
      <P ALIGN="CENTER"><H3 ALIGN="CENTER"><B> THE U.S.-SOUTH AFRICA BINATIONAL COMMISSION</B></H3></P>

<P ALIGN="LEFT">The U.S.-South Africa Binational Commission was announced during President Mandela's October 1994 visit to Washington.  The Commission was created to oversee, coordinate, and promote the development of relations between the United States and South Africa.  Vice President Gore and Executive Deputy President Mbeki launched the U.S.-S.A. Binational Commission at its inaugural meeting on March 1, 1995.  The Commission is co-chaired by the Vice President of the United States and the Deputy President of the Republic of South Africa.  The Commission was originally comprised of five committees for the purpose of facilitating bilateral cooperation in key issues of mutual concern: 1) Trade and Investment (formerly called business development); 2) Environment.  Conservation and Sustainable Development; 3) Sustainable Energy Development; 4) Human Resource Development and Education; and 5) science and Technology.  Each Committee is chaired at the Ministerial/Secretarial level.</P>

<P ALIGN="LEFT">The Commission is scheduled to meet approximately every six months with the venue alternating between the two countries.  During the meetings, the Commission will review activities of the six committees, resolve any outstanding difficulties and establish an agenda for future undertakings of the Commission.  The committee co-chairpersons are responsible for their committees' completing assigned tasks prior to the next Commission meeting.</P>

<P ALIGN="LEFT">The first full meeting of the BNC with its initial five committees occurred in Pretoria in December 1995.  A sixth committee on Agriculture was added to the BNC following that session.  The BNC met with all six committees in July 1996 in Washington.</P>

<P>The third full meeting of the U.S.-South Africa Binational Commission (BNC) is scheduled to take place in Cape Town, South Africa on February 14 - 17, 1997.</P>

<P DIR="LTR">The BNC has become the capstone of the Clinton Administration's efforts to reestablish and elevate to a priority position the U.S. relationship with the new South Afiica.</P>


<P ALIGN="LEFT"><B DIR="LTR">Trade and Investment Committee</B></P>

<P ALIGN="LEFT">The Secretary of Commerce co-chairs the BNC's Trade and Investinent Committee (TIC) with his counterpart, South Afiica's Minister of Trade and Industry Alec Erwin.  Ruth Harkin, President of OPIC, is the Vice Chair on the U.S. side.  There is no South African Vice Chair.  The February meeting will be the second BNC/TIC session for Minister Erwin.  He assumed his position as Minister of the Department of Trade and Industry on April 3, 1996.  He had formerly served as the Deputy Minister of Finance.
The TIC has played a key role as the United States and South Africa seek to reestablish the many facets of their commercial relationship which had been cut off during the apartheid/sanctions era.  USDOC/ITA's Office of Africa is the TIC point of contact for the Department.  Commerce coordinates the TIC interagency working group representing 13 USG agencies in the trade and investment area to identify issues to be addressed and delivarables to be announced at the TIC meetings.  The following agencies make up the TIC: Commerce, State, USTR, Treasury, OPIC, AID, Energy, TDA, Labor, EXIM Bank, USIA, the NSC and the White House.  This group has been meeting periodically since the fall of 1993, as the USDOC Interagency Task Force on South Africa, and has been largely responsible for crafting the commercial component of the USG's relationship with the new South Africa.</P>


</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
