<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>USIA: U.S. Policy in the Gulf -- Ambassador
David C. Litt's statement before the Senate Committee on Foreign
Relations </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff><IMG SRC="usis2.jpg">
<CENTER><B><H2>Ambassador David C. Litt's statement<br>
before the Senate Committee on Foreign Relations<br>
at his nomination hearing for Ambassador<br>
to the United Arab Emirates<br>
June 20, 1995</H2></B><P>
<IMG SRC="footer.gif"></CENTER> 
<P>
Mr. Chairman and members of the Committee, I am honored to appear
before you today to discuss my nomination to become the U.S.
Ambassador to the United Arab Emirates.  I wish to express my
deepest appreciation to President Clinton and Secretary
Christopher
for their confidence in my abilities to represent the United
States
in the UAE.
<P>
Mr. Chairman, for decades the Persian Gulf has occupied a
strategic
place in United States foreign policy.  The Gulf has all too
often
been a flashpoint threatening vital U.S. interests, but it also
has
been a source of opportunities for American commerce.  In both
cases, effective diplomacy is the front line weapon of choice in
defending U.S. interests. have had the privilege throughout much
of
my career to be part of our diplomatic team that has focussed on
that region.
<P>
It is a further privilege to be nominated to serve in a country
that offers promise to be of substantial support for America's
policies in the Middle East.  If confirmed, it is my intention to
promote to the fullest extent of my abilities our key interests:
building and maintaining an effective security relationship with
the UAE government, maintaining open access for American
corporations to the business opportunities that are blossoming in
the UAE as well as promoting American products over those of our
competitors, and seeking effective support from the UAE
government
for our policies in the Gulf region and toward the Middle East
peace process.
<P>
With these ambitions in mind, I am ready to meet the challenge
that
lies ahead.  I do not accept this commitment lightly, nor do I
undervalue the difficulties that may arise.  The threats to peace
and stability are many, and I have been actively involved in
combatting some of them from Washington.  With your support I
look
forward to contributing to our joint efforts to strengthen
American
policy in the Gulf region.
<P>
<HR>
