<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SoftQuad//DTD draft HTML 3.2 + extensions for HoTMetaL PRO 3.0 19960923//EN"
 "hmpro3.dtd">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>inaugural press release</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="000000">
<PRE>                             THE WHITE HOUSE
                      OFFICE OF THE VICE PRESIDENT
                    FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE            

CONTACT: 202-456-7036
Wednesday, March 1, 1995


     Deputy President Thabo Mbeki and I have just signed a Statement of Intent to form
the U.S.-South Africa Binational Commission.  By doing so, we launch a new era in
partnership between our two democracies.  This Commission will facilitate cooperation so we
can move together in important areas of cooperation: business development, conservation and
environment, energy development, human resources development and education,  science and
technology.  The agreement calls for semi-annual Commission meetings to ensure bilateral
efforts in these key areas moving ahead expeditiously throughout the year.  The next
Commission meeting will be held in South Africa to assess progress made over the next six
months and to set the agenda for future undertakings of the Commission.  Some of the
initiatives include:

     -    Business Development Committee, co-chaired by Commerce Secretary Ron
          Brown, held its inaugural meeting last September.  The Committee reviewed
          plans for its next full meeting in May in Cape Town, South Africa.

     -    Secretary Brown also announced plans for a commercial law seminar scheduled
          also scheduled for May in South Africa.

     -    Conservation and Environment Committee, co-chaired by Interior Secretary
          Babbitt, will support South Africa's successful wildlife management as a model
          of sustainable development of wildlife resources for the rest of Africa.  South
          Africa will also be brought into the GLOBE initiative.

     -    Energy Development Committee, co-chaired by Energy Secretary Hazel
          O'Leary, will be looking at some initiative already under discussion with the
          South African Government, such as a Renewable Energy Rural Electrification
          Pilot Program, construction of a U.S. photovoltaic cell manufacturing plant in
          South Africa, and a program of scientific and technical exchange between U.S.
          and South African universities.

     -    Human Resources Development and Education Committee, co-chaired by U.S.
          Agency for International Development Administrator Brian Atwood is looking
          forward to discussing a number of initiatives with his South African
          counterpart, including: a Youth Employment Skills Program, the Mantelet
          Scholars Program for post-graduate economic studies, a Fulbright Program, and
          a Labor-Management Relations Program.

     -    The Science and Technology Committee, co-chaired by the President's Advisor
          for Science and Technology Policy John Gibbons and Dr. Ngubane, who is
          here today with Deputy President Mbeki will focus on completing negotiations
          for the Framework Agreement on Environment, Science and Technology
          Cooperation, cooperative programs in fields where South Africa has conducted
          world-class scientific research, and the creation of mentoring program using
          U.S. scientist and engineers.

     All the U.S. co-chairs are anxious to get to work with their South African counterparts
and they will be making plans for their committees to meet between now and the next full
Commission meeting in the fall.

     The importance of PVO's and the private sector can not be over emphasized and the
Commissions is a good vehicle to bring together the efforts of public, private sector and NGO
organizations.

Thank you all for coming.
</PRE></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
