<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release July 23, 1996</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">THE WHITE HOUSE<BR>  Office of the Vice
President</H3>
<P>

______________________________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
For Immediate Release	July 23, 1996 
</P>
<P>
United States-South Africa Binational Commission 
</P>
<P>
THE U.S. OVERSEAS PRIVATE INVESTMENT CORPORATION BACKS NEW FUND
TO PROMOTE ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT IN SOUTH AFRICA 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore today announced that the federal Overseas
Private Investment Corporation (OPIC) is backing a new, $120
million fund that will make equity investments in South Africa
and other nations in the continent_s southern region. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vice President made the announcement at a press conference
following the second full session of the United States-South
Africa Binational Commission that he co-chairs with South African
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki.  
</P>
<P>
 	</P>
<P>
&quot;This OPIC-backed fund is a critical vehicle that will help
move needed investment capital into South Africa and other
southern African nations,&quot; said Ruth R. Harkin, President of
OPIC. &quot;Through agencies like OPIC, this Administration is
creating public-private partnerships that promote economic
development and opportunities around the world.&quot; 
</P>
<P>
	OPIC is an independent agency of the U.S. government that sells
financial services to American companies making long-term
investments in South Africa and other developing nations.
</P>
<P>
 	The $120 million fund, called the New Africa Opportunity Fund,
L.P., is backed with an OPIC investment guaranty and is being
privately managed by New Africa Advisors (NAA), a subsidiary of
the Durham, North Carolina-based Sloan Financial Group.  With
managed assets of more than $3.5 billion, Sloan is the largest
African-American owned investment firm in America. 
</P>
<P>
	The management team of NAA includes experienced investment
professionals located in Johannesburg, South Africa supported by
the Sloan organization in North Carolina.  NAA was the first U.S.
investment firm to locate an office in Johannesburg in 1992,
providing American investors access to African securities
markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fund, one of 23 OPIC-backed investment funds, will focus on
the development of businesses which are owned by the region_s
majority population.  It is expected to increase the level of
U.S. goods and services flowing to southern Africa and to
generate significant regional economic development.  In addition,
the Fund will support the return to South Africa those American
companies that left during the boycott period.  
</P>
<P>
	In addition to South Africa, the Fund will pursue investments in
ten other southern African countries including: Angola; Botswana;
Lesotho; Malawi; Mauritius; Mozambique; Namibia; Swaziland;
Zambia; and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
<P>
	All investments made by OPIC-backed funds are reviewed to ensure
a positive impact on the U.S. economy and that the projects take
steps to protect the host country_s environment and respect
worker rights.  Supporting American business for 25 years, OPIC
is a self-sustaining federal agency that encourages private, U.S.
investment in some 140 developing nations worldwide. Since 1971,
OPIC has supported $84 billion worth of investments that will
generate $43 billion in U.S. exports and help to create and
support 200,000 jobs.   
</P></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
