<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>USIA: U.S. Policy in Iraq -- State Dept.
Announcement On Operation Provide Comfort</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff><IMG SRC="usis2.jpg">
<CENTER><B><H2>State Dept. Announcement<br>
On Operation Provide Comfort<br>
December 26, 1996</H2></B><P>
<IMG SRC="footer.gif"></CENTER> 
<P>
Washington -- Turkey announced December 25 that it will extend
Coalition Air Operations over northern Iraq beginning January 1,
the State Department said December 25.
<P>
In a written statement, the State Department said that coalition
aircraft have been flying these operations since 1991 under
"Operation Provide Comfort," but the designation "Provide
Comfort" is being dropped because of changes in its mission due
to the closing of the Military Command Center in Zakho and the
shift of humanitarian assistance in the north under United
Nations Security Council Resolution 986 to international
organizations.
<P>
Following is the State Department text:
<P>
<center>U.S. DEPARTMENT OF STATE<br>
OFFICE OF THE SPOKESMAN<br>
DECEMBER 25, 1996
<P>
STATEMENT BY JOHN DINGER, SPOKESMAN<br>
EXTENSION OF COALITION AIR OPERATIONS OVER NORTHERN IRAQ</center>
<P>
The United States welcomes Turkey's December 25 announcement that
it will extend Coalition Air Operations over northern Iraq
beginning January 1. Coalition aircraft will continue to fly
these operations as they have since 1991 in the framework of
Operation Provide Comfort. Because of changes in its mission as a
result of the closing last fall of the Military Command Center in
Zakho and the shift of humanitarian assistance in the north under
UNSCR 986 to international organizations, the designation
"Provide Comfort" will no longer will be used.
<P>
Operation Provide Comfort has made an important contribution to
the well being of the people of northern Iraq and to the peace
and stability of the region. The ongoing air operation
underscores the firm commitment of coalition partners to bringing
about Iraq's full compliance with all its UN obligations.
<P>
