<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>USIA: U.S. Policy in the Gulf -- Export Import
Bank Announces Deal With Qatar</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff><IMG SRC="usis2.jpg">
<CENTER><B><H2>Export Import Bank Announces Deal With
Qatar</H2></B><P>
<IMG SRC="footer.gif"></CENTER> 
<P>
Washington -- The following news release from the Export Import
Bank of the United States was released January 17 to announce the
"Middle East Deal of the Year," a half-billion dollar export to
Qatar that will also benefit Virginia, Texas, Pennsylvania, and
Oklahoma firms.
<P>
(Begin text)
<P>
The Export-Import Bank of the United States (Ex-Im Bank) has
approved its first project financings in Qatar -- $526 million to
support U.S. exports for two gas field development projects. The
sale of U.S. equipment and services for the Ras Laffan and
Qatargas projects, sponsored by subsidiaries of Mobil Corp.,
Fairfax, VA, will sustain thousands of high-quality American
jobs.
<P>
The projects will tap the largest gas field in the world, the
North Field located offshore Qatar, and use exports from U.S.
companies around the country including primary contractors M.W.
Kellogg and McDermott Engineering both of Houston, TX.
<P>
The Ras Laffan project financing was named "Middle East Deal of
the Year" by Project Finance International Magazine, and the
Qatargas project financing was selected to be one of the
magazine's top five Middle East deals for 1996.
<P>
"The Ras Laffan project expects to purchase in excess of $500
million of goods and services from suppliers in the United
States, which would not have been possible without Ex-Im Bank's
participation," said Dale Stein, Director, Project Finance,
Mobil. "Ex-Im Bank played a leadership role in the financing
which was critical to its success."
<P>
Dianne Rudo, Vice President of Ex-Im Bank's project Finance
Division, said: "With the approval of these cases in the first
quarter of fiscal 1997, our division's business so far this year
equals 80 percent of all the financing we did in fiscal 1996.
These transactions are the first of what we hope will be many
large project financing commitments in the Middle East by Ex-Im
Bank."
<P>
Ex-Im Bank's Board of Directors approved $464 million in
financing supporting U.S. exports to Ras Laffan Liquefied Natural
Gas Co. Ltd. to build, own and operate offshore and onshore
facilities at the North Field. Ras Laffan will extract gas and
process it to form liquefied natural gas (LNG).
<P>
Project sponsors and owners of Ras Laffan are the Qatar General
Petroleum Corp. (QGPC), owned by the government of Qatar, and
Mobil QM Gas Inc., a wholly owned subsidiary of Mobil Corp. M.W.
Kellogg is a primary contractor for the onshore portion of the
project, and McDermott International for the offshore platform.
Subcontractors on the project include companies based in
Pennsylvania, Oklahoma and Texas. Firms based in Florida, Nevada,
California and Massachusetts are under consideration as potential
subcontractors.
<P>
Ex-Im Bank also approved up to $62 million in financing in
support of the sale of U.S. equipment and services for the
upstream part of the Qatargas Liquefied Natural Gas Project.
Qatargas will develop a gas and condensate concession in the
North Field, build a pipeline to transport the wet gas, extract
and sell condensates, and deliver the resulting feedstock gas to
an LNG plant. The Qatargas upstream project is a joint venture
owned by subsidiaries of Mobil, U.S.A.; QGPC, Qatar; Total,
France; and Marubeni and Mitsui, Japan.
<P>
The financers of the two projects will be repaid from project
revenues, rather than relying on a guarantee of the debt by the
host country government. "Financing on a limited recourse basis
is relatively new for major international projects," Mobil's
Stein said. "Ex-Im Bank's Project Finance Division used its
expertise in the area to the benefit of the Ras Laffan and
Qatargas financing and ultimately to the benefit of U.S.
business."
<P>
Ex-Im Bank is an independent government agency that creates and
sustains good high-wage jobs for American workers by financing
U.S. export sales into key emerging markets where private sources
of credit are still developing.
<P>
<HR>
<center>This Web site was produced and is maintained by the
United States Information Agency.<P><A HREF="gulfmain.htm">
