<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEW Explanation of U.S. Operations</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY
BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#602B1A" VLINK="#C95A36" ALINK="#7C0418">
<H2>Explanation of the U.S. Operations of the Committee</H2>
<PRE> 
This Committee uses five Working Groups, based on U.S. and S.A. environmental agency
responsibilities, to organize its activities.  The Department of the Interior (DOI) staff sought
to involve as many Federal environmental agencies as possible in the work of the Committee.

Since DOI agencies, EPA and NOAA, all intend to develop strong professional relationships
with their counterparts in South Africa, it was decided each agency should have as much
autonomy to develop its activities and contacts as possible.  Each agency is providing its own
funding for its activities and operates under its own legal authorities. [Each Working Group
coordinates with other agencies, for example USFWS includes Smithsonian and Bureau of
Land Management in its Working Group.]

A.  U.S. Participants in the Working Groups: 

Nature Conservation and Ecotourism  
U.S. Co-Chair: Marshall Jones, Assistant Director, Fish and Wildlife Service
Staff: David Ferguson, International Program Officer, Fish and Wildlife Service

Environmental Management
U.S. Co-Chair: William Nitze, Assistant Administrator, International Activities, EPA
Staff: Marsha Coleman-Adebayo, Program Officer, International Activities, EPA

Water Conservation
U.S. Co-Chair: Eluid Martinez, Commissioner, Bureau of Reclamation
Staff: Richard Ives, Acting Chief, International Activities, Bureau of Reclamation

Oceans and Atmosphere
U.S. Co-Chair: Elbert Friday, Director, National Weather Service, National Oce- anic and
Atmospheric Administration
Staff: Martin Yerg, Chief, International Activities Office, NWS/NOAA

Fisheries 
U.S. Co-Chair: Will Martin, Deputy Assistant Secretary, International Affairs, NOAA
Staff: Jacqueline Rousseau, Program Officer, International Affairs, NOAA
     Brad Brown, NOAA, Director of Southeast Fisheries Science Center
                                                                           
B.  Functions of Each Working Group:

Nature Conservation and Ecotourism
This Working Group supports efforts to maintain South Africa's wildlife and parks
management as a model for sustainable development of wildlife resources and protection of
biodiversity for the rest of Africa.  It facilitates exchange of information and skills between
South Africa and the United States and between South Africa and other African countries. 
The members discuss policies related to international environmental conventions such as
CITES, World Heritage, Ramsar, and the Biodiversity Convention.  The group develops
techniques to bring to public attention the economic importance of sustainable development,
national parks and wildlife tourism.

Environmental Management and Pollution Prevention
This Working Group focuses on major environmental issues of both countries.  It explores
avenues to support environmental management capacity building, including environmental
laws, policies and practices that encourage sound environmental management and sustainable
development with special attention to promoting pollution prevention.  The working group
establishes a mechanism for systematic exchange of information between and among
counterpart government agencies, such as through INFOTERRA.  Members seek to promote
increased interaction between environmental organizations, academic and research institutions
and private environmental technology and services companies.

Water Conservation
This Working Group shares common problems and lessons in dealing with the lack of water
in certain parts of the country, a problem faced by both nations.  The focus is on capacity
building, water conservation, and water utility exchanges.  Project activities strive to provide
equitable allocation and efficient use of water.  The U.S. has been impressed with the
innovative ideas and breadth of the Working Group s activities to address difficult water
allocation problems.

Oceans and Atmosphere
This Working Group focuses on applied research and operations in the field of meteorology,
climatology, hydrology and oceanography with an emphasis on short-term and long-term
rainfall forecasting and cloud seeding.  The Working Group will cooperate in the areas of
education and training, exchange of experts and information, joint scientific studies, and
upgrading of equipment and observations.

Fisheries
This Working Group shares expertise in a number of fisheries-related areas including the
following: a) the role of marine reserves in conservation and sustainable development; b)
stock assessment methodologies; and c) cooperation in areas of joint research interests,
particularly dealing with comparative ecosystems research on highly-migratory fish species
and pelagic and groundfish resources.  Comparisons of ecosystems might focus on the
Agulhas Current and the Gulf Stream and the Benguela and California Currents.  In addition,
the working group is exploring the possibility of cooperative educational and research efforts
between traditionally black colleges in both the United States and South Africa.

</PRE></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
