<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>USIA: U.S. Policy in the Gulf -- Iraq
Sanctions Chronology</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff><IMG SRC="usis2.jpg"><CENTER>
<B><H2>CHRONOLOGY OF IRAQ SANCTIONS</H2></B><P>
<IMG SRC="footer.gif"></CENTER> 

<center><b><h2>1996</H2></b></center>
<P>
<center><b> September </b></center>
<p>
September 1, 1996 -- Responding to Iraqi attacks in northern Iraq
and Iraqi efforts to renegotiate the accord, UN Secretary-General
Boutros Boutros-Ghali freezes implementation of Iraqi
"oil-for-food "accord.
<P>
September 3-4, 1996 -- U.S. military forces in the Persian Gulf
region launch two missile attacks on Iraqi military and command
positions in southern Iraq.  Iraqi forces withdraw from Erbil.
<P>
<center><b> August </b></center>
<p>
August 2, 1996 -- Raed Ahmad, an Iraqi weight lifter who carried
his country's flag at the 1996 Summer Olympics in Atlanta,
requests political asylum in the United States.
<P>
August 31, 1996 -- Iraqi military forces capture town of Erbil in
northern Iraq in a show of military support for one of two main
rival Kurdish movements in northern Iraq.
<P>
<center><b> June </b></center>
<p>
June 22-23, 1996 -- First Arab Summit since 1990 is held.  Iraq
is sole Arab nation not invited to attend.
<P>
<center><b> May </b></center>
<p>
May 20, 1996 -- Iraq and the United Nations sign an
"oil-for-food" deal which would allow Iraq to sell $2 billion
worth of oil for food and medical supplies to be supplied to
Iraqi civilians under UN supervision.
<p>
<center><b> February </b></center>
<p>
February 20, 1996 -- Hussein and Saddam Kamel, Saddam's two
sons-in-law who requested asylum in Jordan in August 1995, return
to Baghdad after receiving Iraqi government "pardons."
<P>
February 23, 1996 -- Hussein and Saddam Kamel killed in Baghdad,
allegedly at the hands of family members.
<P>
<hr>
<P>
<center><b><h2>1995</h2></b></center>
<P>
<center><b> October </b></center>
<p>
October 15, 1995 -- Saddam Hussein is "re-elected" to another
seven-year term as President of Iraq in a referendum in which he
was the sole candidate.  Saddam reportedly won 99.96% of the
vote.  Foreign observers noted that voters were required to sign
their ballots.  Jordan's King Hussein described the vote as a
"farce."
<P>
<center><b> August </b></center>
<p>
August 8, 1995 -- Jordan grants asylum to two sons-in-law of
Saddam Hussein, Lt. Gen. Hussein Kamel Hassan al-Majid, who had
supervised Iraq's weapons of mass destruction development
programs since 1987, and his brother, Lt. Col. Saddam Kamel
Hassan al-Majid, who formerly headed the presidential security
forces.  The two men were married to the two eldest daughters of
Saddam Hussein.
<P>
August 17-20, 1995 -- During a visit to Baghdad, Iraq provides
new information to UN arms inspector Rolf Ekeus, admitting inter
alia that it began a crash nuclear weapons programs in April 1990
that sought to produce a nuclear weapon by April 1991.  Observers
speculated that Iraq's new candor was prompted by the defection
of Hussein Kamel who the Iraqi government believed would
cooperate with UN inspectors and Western governments to provide
previously undisclosed information on Iraqi
weapons programs.  
<P>

<center><b> July </b></center>
<p>
July 11, 1995 -- UN votes to renew trade sanctions on Iraq. 
Observers described the extension as a "foregone conclusion"
after UN arms inspector Rolf Ekeus reported that, after four
years of denials, Iraq had admitted that it produced biological
weapons in 1989 and 1990. 
<P>
<center><b> June </b></center>
<p>
June 14, 1995 -- Iraqi troops loyal to Saddam Hussein reportedly
put down an uprising led by elite Republican guard troops.  The
Iraqi government denied the report.
<P>
<center><b> April </b></center>
<p>
April 10, 1995 -- Rolf Ekeus stated that the Iraqi government had
withheld information from the United Nations that suggested that
Iraq planned and perhaps began a biological weapons
program
in the 1980s.
<P>
April 16, 1995 -- Iraqi Cabinet formally turns down a UNSC offer
to allow Iraq to sell up to $2 billion worth of oil to purchase
food and medicines which would have contributed to alleviating
supply shortages harming Iraqi citizens.
<P>
<center><b> February </b></center>
<p>
February 27, 1995 -- Max Van der Stoel, the former Dutch Foreign
Minister who has been charged by the UN with monitoring human
rights abuses in Iraq, characterized Iraq as among "the worst
offenders of human rights since the Second World War." 

<P><center><b> January </b></center>
<p>
January 10, 1995 -- Rolf Ekeus, Head of the UN special commission
monitoring Iraqi disarmament, reported to the Security Council
that Iraq had recently turned over information on its chemical
weapons programs that it had failed to disclose for four years.
<P>
<hr>
<P>
<center><b><h2>1994</h2></b></center>
<P>
<center><b> November </b></center>
<p>
November 10, 1994 -- Iraq issues a statement declaring that it
"recognizes the sovereignty of the State of Kuwait, its
territorial integrity and political independence."  (Renunciation
of the claim that Kuwait was a "province" of Iraq was one of
several UNSC conditions to end economic sanctions on Iraq.
<P>
<center><b> October </b></center>
<p>
October 7, 1994 -- Iraq begins to mass troops at a location near
Basra, twenty miles north of the Kuwaiti border.
<P>
October 8, 1994 -- U.S. orders the deployment of 4,000 additional
troops to Kuwait.
<P>
October 9, 1994 -- U.S. deployment expands to 36,000 troops.
<P>
October 15, 1994 -- UN Security council votes unanimously to
condemn the movement of Iraqi troops towards the Kuwaiti border
and to refrain from threatening military movements.
<P>
<center><b> April </b></center>
<p> 
April 24, 1994 -- Iraq announces completion of a 65-mile canal
through southern Iraq that would divert river waters away from
marshlands inhabited primarily by Shiite Iraqis to desert lands. 
The project has long been the object of concern to human rights
groups who charge that the primary reason for the project is to
punish the Shiite population in this region for their support of
anti-government rebels and to make rebel bases more accessible to
government attack.
<P>
<hr>
<P>
<center><b><h2>1993</h2></b></center>
<center><b> November </b></center>
<p> 
November 12, 1993 -- The New York Times reports that the Iraqi
government forces have stepped up military pressure against
Shiite villages in southern Iraq forcing thousands to flee deeper
into the marshes or across the border into Iran.
<P>
<center><b> July </b></center>
<p>
July 19, 1993 -- UN Special Commissioner for Iraqi Disarmament
Rolf Ekeus and Iraqi government reach agreement on renewing UN
inspections of Iraqi weapons programs amid mounting fears that
military reprisals will be taken by coalition forces if a new
inspections agreement is not reached.
<P>
<center><b> June </b></center>
<p>
June 26, 1993 -- US forces launch a missile attack on Iraqi
intelligence headquarters in Baghdad in retaliation for evidence
linking the Iraqi government to the assassination plot against
former President Bush.
<P>
June 10-July 17, 1993 -- A lengthy stand-off takes place between
the Iraqi government and UN inspectors over Iraq's refusal to
allow inspectors to monitor two missile test sites south of
Baghdad.  UN monitors are withdrawn.
<P><center><b> May </b></center>
<p>
May 19, 1993 -- US officials state that an FBI investigation had
substantiated charges that the Iraqi government plotted the
assassination of former President Bush while visiting Kuwait in
April 1993.
<P><center><b> April </b></center>
<p>
April 9, 1993 -- Iraqi anti-aircraft fires at four U.S. airplanes
in the no-fly zone; the planes respond by bombing Iraqi
anti-aircraft positions.
<P>
April 16-18, 1993 -- Former U.S. President Bush visits Kuwait.
<P>
April 16, 1993 -- Several relief agencies withdraw personnel from
northern Iraq after a series of attacks on their personnel
attributed to Iraqi intelligence services.
<P>
April 29, 1993 -- Kuwait announces the arrest of a group of
Iraqis who were charged with planning to assassinate former U.S.
President Bush during his visit to Kuwait.  The arrests
reportedly took place prior to Bush's April visit.
<P>
<center><b> February </b></center>
<p>
February 3, 1993 -- Iraqi anti-aircraft batteries fire on two
French Mirages in no-fly zone.  French aircraft are not damaged.
<P>
<center><b> January </b></center>
<p>
January 4-5, 1993 -- Iraq moves anti-aircraft missiles into
southern no-fly zone.
<P>
January 6, 1993 -- U.S., Britain, France, and Russia give Iraq a
48 hour ultimatum to remove anti-aircraft batteries from the
no-fly zones.
<P>
January 8, 1993 -- Iraq announces again that it will not allow UN
inspectors to use UN aircraft to conduct inspections of Iraqi
military installations.
<P>
January 10, 1993 -- Iraq denies a request by UN inspectors to
enter Iraq on a UN plane.
<P>
January 10-13, 1993 -- Iraqi workers make several trips to an
Iraqi naval base in the demilitarized zone between Iraq and
Kuwait and recover military equipment, including Silkworm
missiles, abandoned during 1991 war.
<P>
January 11, 1993 -- Iraq moves additional missiles into northern
no-fly zone.
<P>
January 13, 1993 -- More than 100 US, British, and French planes
strike missile batteries and radar stations in Iraq.  President 
Bush orders an additional 1,250 troops to Kuwait.
<P>
January 17, 1993 -- U.S. missiles strike industrial complex near
Baghdad believed to be manufacturing parts for Iraqi nuclear
program.
<P>
January 18, 1993 -- U.S. planes mount an air strike against Iraqi
air defenses in southern Iraq.
<P>
January 21 & 22 , 1993 -- U.S. planes hit an Iraqi radar
installations in northern Iraq two times after Iraqi gunners lock
radars on U.S. aircraft.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<center><b><h2>1992</h2></b></center>
<center><b> December </b></center>
<p>
December 27, 1992 -- U.S. fighter planes shoot down an Iraqi
aircraft violating southern "no fly zone."
<p>
<center><b> August </b></center>
<p>
August 2&3, 1992 -- Iraqi media run several articles and carry
broadcasts reasserting that Kuwait is a province of Iraq.
<P>
August 26, 1992 -- US, Britain, and France announce the
establishment of a southern "no fly zone" to protect Iraqi
dissidents in southern Iraq from regime air attacks.  (A northern
"no fly zone" has been in place since the 1991 cease-fire).
<P>
August 26, 1992 -- UNSC votes to accept a UN-sponsored
demarcation of the Iraqi-Kuwaiti border and declares this border
"inviolable."
<P>
<center><b> July </b></center>
<p>
July 2-8, 1992 -- Reports circulate in international media
regarding a possible failed coup and subsequent army purge in
Iraq.
<P>
July 5-22, 1992 -- Iraq refuses to allow a UN inspection team to
enter a building in Baghdad believed to contain documents related
to Iraq's nuclear program.  On July 22, inspectors withdrew
without gaining access.
<P>
July 25, 1992 -- Iraq agrees to allow UN monitors into the
building to which access was previously refused.
<P>
<center><b> March </b></center>
<p>
March 13, 1992 -- UNSC formally informs Iraq that it is in
violation of the 1991 cease-fire agreement.
<P>
March 19, 1992 -- Iraq forwards letter to the UNSC stating that
it will cooperate with UN weapons inspection efforts.
<P>
<center><b>February</b></center>
<p>
February 26-28, 1992 -- Iraq refuses to allow UN inspectors to
begin dismantling Scud missile production plants and other
Scud-related equipment.
<P>
February 28, 1992 -- UNSC condemns Iraq for refusing to allow UN
inspectors to destroy its weapons of mass destruction and
ballistic missiles as agreed in 1991 cease-fire terms.
<P>
<hr>
<P>
<center><b><h2>1991</h2></b></center>
<P>
<center><b>September</b></center>
<p>
September 8, 1991 -- Iraq announces its will not allow UN
inspectors to use UN aircraft to inspect Iraqi military
facilities, a violation of the cease-fire agreement.
<P>
September 18, 1991 -- President Bush authorizes US Air Force
planes to escort UN aircraft engaged in weapons inspection in
Iraq.
<P>
September 23 and 24, 1991 -- Iraqi troops detain UN weapons
inspectors in Baghdad on two separate occasions.
<P>
September 24, 1991 -- UN receives a vaguely worded Iraqi
statement interpreted as withdrawing Iraq's objections to the use
of UN aircraft in monitoring the destruction of Iraq's weapons of
mass destruction.
<P>
September 28, 1991 -- Iraq ends the multi-day detention of UN
inspectors who discovered
documents that confirmed Iraq was conducting a clandestine
nuclear program.
<P>
<center><b>July</b></center>
<p>
July 15, 1991-- The last coalition troops leave Iraq.
<P>
July 30, 1991 -- UN weapons inspectors report to the UNSC that
Iraq has attempted to conceal aspects of its nuclear weapons
program by destroying or burying essential equipment.  The
inspectors also reported identifying four times as many chemical
weapons as Iraq had reported to be in its possession.
<p>
<center><b>June</b></center>
<p>
June 23-28, 1991 -- Iraqi soldiers obstructed and, in one case
fired warning shots at, UN inspectors attempting to oversee the
destruction of Iraqi nuclear
armaments parts.
<p>
<center><b>April</b></center>
<p>
April 6, 1991 -- Iraq formally accepts the terms of a permanent
cease-fire as stipulated in UN 687.  Also included in the
agreement is UN supervised destruction of Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction, ballistic missiles, and Iraq's agreement to
contribute to a reparations fund.
<P>
April 11, 1991 -- UNSC declares a formal end to the war after
reviewing Iraq's message to ensure that Iraq's acceptance of UN
terms was unconditional.
<P>
<center><b>March</b></center>
<p>
March 2, 1991 -- United Nations Security Council passes <A
HREF="unsc686.htm">UNSC 686</A> establishing cease-fire terms. 
The United Nations requires Iraq to rescind its annexation of
Kuwait, to accept in principle liability for damages and injuries
caused by the invasion and occupation of Kuwait, to release
coalition POWs immediately, to release all Kuwaitis, third
country nationals, and remains in Iraqi government possession, to
return all stolen Kuwaiti property, to end all military action,
to identify mines and booby traps (and disclose information on
any chemical or biological weapons stored) in areas of Iraq
occupied by coalition forces.  In addition, all twelve UN
resolutions passed before the war remain in effect.
<P>
March 3, 1991 -- A meeting takes place near Safwan, Iraq between
coalition and Iraqi military commanders to arrange the
military-to-military details of a formal cease-fire.
<P>
March 3, 1991 -- Iraqi Foreign minister Tariq Aziz sends the UNSC
a letter stating that Iraq will "fulfill its obligations" under
UN 686.
<P>
March 3-13, 1991 -- Many reports of unrest and uprisings in Iraq,
all ultimately put down by Iraqi military forces.  Iraqi forces
use helicopters in putting down these insurgencies.
<P>
March 13, 1991 -- President Bush notes that the use of
helicopters against the insurgents violates the cease-fire
agreement and the military-to-military agreement reached at
Safwan.
<P>
<center><b>February</b></center>
<p>
February 15, 1991 -- Iraq offers to withdraw from Kuwait. 
Coalition forces reject the offer due to numerous conditions
attached to it.
<P>
February 23, 1991 -- Coalition forces begin ground attack against
Iraqi forces.
<P>
February 27, 1991 -- Coalition forces announce that Kuwait has
been liberated.  President Bush announces a suspension of
military operations at midnight on February 27.
<P>
February 27-28, 1991 -- Iraq observes the cease-fire and accepts
most coalition terms for a formal cease-fire.
<P>
<center><b>January</B></center>
<p>
January 9, 1991 -- Secretary of State James Baker and Iraqi
Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz meet in
Geneva in a final U.S. diplomatic effort to avert war.  Iraqi
officials refuse to comply
unconditionally with UN resolutions by the UN-imposed January 15
deadline.
<P>
January 12, 1991 -- U.S. Congress authorizes President Bush to
use "all necessary means" to
force Iraqi withdrawal from Kuwait.
<P>
January 13, 1991 -- UN Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
departs Baghdad after the failure of "eleventh hour" talks to
avoid
conflict.
<P>    
January 16, 1991 -- International coalition begins air attacks on
Iraqi targets.
<P>
January 23, 1991 -- Iraqi military forces deliberately create a
huge oil spill in the Persian Gulf, the largest oil spill on
record.  U.S. officials term the spill an act of "environmental
terrorism."
<P>
<center><b><h2>1990</h2></b></center>
<p>
November 28, 1990 -- UN 677 condemns Iraqi efforts to change
demography of Kuwait and the alteration and destruction of
Kuwaiti
civil records.
<P>
November 29, 1990 -- United Nations Security Council approves a
resolution, <A HREF="unsc678.htm">UNSC 678</A>, authorizing use
of "all necessary means" to force Iraq from Kuwait if Iraq does
not withdraw by January 15, 1991.<P>
<P>
<center><b>October</b></center>
<p>
October 29, 1990 -- United Nations Security Council passes a
resolution making Iraq liable for damages, injuries, and
financial losses resulting from the invasion and occupation of
Kuwait. 
<p>
<center><b>September</b></center>
<p>
September 16, 1990 -- UNSC passes UNSC 667 condemning Iraqi
efforts to force nations to close their embassies in Kuwait and
move them to Baghdad.
<P>
September 25, 1990 -- UNSC passes UNSC 670 which extends land and
sea blockade of Iraq to air traffic.
<P>
<center><b>August</b></center>
<p>
August 2, 1990 -- Iraqi forces invade Kuwait in the early morning
hours and quickly establish military control of Kuwait. 
President Bush harshly condemns the invasion, orders economic
sanctions on Iraq and occupied Kuwait, and freezes Iraqi and
Kuwaiti assets in the U.S.  The United Nations Security Council
passes resolution <A HREF="unsc660.htm">UNSC 660</A> condemning
the
invasion and demanding the immediate and unconditional withdrawal
of Iraqi troops from Kuwait.  The UNSC threatens to impose
mandatory sanctions against Iraq unless it complies with the
resolution. 
<P>
August 4, 1990 -- EC and Japan cut trade ties with Iraq.
<P>
August 6, 1990 -- UNSC passes UNSC 661 imposing a broad trade
embargo on Iraq and occupied Kuwait.
 <P>
August 6-7, 1990 -- President Bush sends U.S. troops to Saudi
Arabia to assist in the defense of
the Kingdom against possible Iraqi aggression.
<P>
August 8, 1990 -- Iraq announces its annexation of Kuwait.
<P>
August 9, 1990 -- UNSC unanimously declares Iraq's annexation of
Kuwait "null and void."
<P>
August 10, 1990 -- Emergency Arab Summit meeting in Cairo votes
to send Arab troops to Saudi
Arabia and other Persian Gulf states to assist in defending them
against possible Iraqi attack.
<P>
August 11, 1990 -- Egyptian and Moroccan troops begin arriving in
Saudi Arabia.
<P>
August 13, 1990 -- Pakistan announces it has agreed to send
troops to Saudi Arabia.
<P>
August 14, 1990 -- Syrian forces arrive in Saudi Arabia.
<P>
August 17, 1990 -- Iraq announces that it will "play host" to
citizens of countries in the
international coalition using them as "human shields" against
possible coalition attacks.
<P>
August 18, 1990 -- United Nations Security Council passes UNSC
664 calling on Iraq to release all foreign citizens and warns
Iraq against harming them.
<P>
August 25, 1990-- UNSC authorizes naval forces in and around the
Persian Gulf to use force to prevent violations of UN economic
sanctions on Iraq.
<HR>
