<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Statement of Conclusion</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">
<H2 ALIGN="center">THE WHITE HOUSE OFFICE OF THE VICE PRESIDENT</H2>
<P>
For Immediate Release							  July 23, 1996 
</P>
<P>
U.S.- South Africa Binational Commission 
</P>
<P>
Science and Technology Committee 
</P>
<P>
	The Science and Technology (S&amp;T) Committee of the U.S.-South
Africa Binational Commission, headed by Vice President Al Gore
and South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, will help South
Africa meet the goals of its Reconstruction and Development
Program by applying science and technology to basic human needs. 
To meet this goal, the Vice President and the Deputy President
have focused the Committee's work on three objectives:  capacity
building and science education; food and environmental security;
and health care.     
</P>
<P>
	The S&amp;T Committee co-chairs, John H. Gibbons, Assistant to
the President for Science and Technology, and Ben Ngubane, South
African Minister for Arts, Culture, Science and Technology, have
made science education and capacity building a cornerstone of the
new bilateral relationship.  Specific projects aimed at math and
science education for South Africa's black majority include:
</P>
<P>
 -	Global Learning and Observations to Benefit the Environment
(GLOBE) program, in which South Africa will join the Vice
President's initiative to give students hands-on experience in
taking environmental measurements and using computers;  -	Faculty
Enrichment Program at South African historically black colleges
and universities (HBCU's), in which the U.S. Department of Energy
and Florida A&amp;M University will train South African faculty
from the Technikon of the Northern Transvaal in science and
engineering.  The South African teachers will improve their
teaching skills and develop an advanced math and science
curriculum for schools in South Africa.  -	SUNSAT student
microsatellite program, in which NASA has agreed to launch a
South African student-built satellite in early 1997.  Younger
students will interact with the satellite through a radio
communications system.  In exchange for the launch, SUNSAT will
carry two NASA instruments that will give the satellite unique
capabilities in monitoring sea level rise, melting of polar ice
caps, and other important indicators of global change.       
</P>
<P>
Under the auspices of the S&amp;T Committee, the Department of
Commerce's National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA)
and the South African Weather Bureau (SAWB) announced progress in
environmental monitoring and climate prediction.  
</P>
<P>
-	NOAA and SAWB have joined forces to better understand the
oceanographic phenomena known as El Nino and its effects in
southern Africa.  The project is already producing valuable data,
which can be used to predict drought, heavy rains, and warmer
temperatures.  The ability to predict drought up to one year in
advance could have a tremendous impact on agricultural
production.  Our new predictive capabilities will also help us
understand the climate conditions that are directly related to
outbreaks of vector-borne diseases like malaria. 
</P>
<P>
-	The S&amp;T Committee's Precipitation Enhancement Project is an
excellent example of the mutual benefits of this Commission.  In
the U.S., we use more water than we recover; in South Africa,
cyclical droughts have devastating results.  By taking advantage
of cloud-seeding technologies developed in South Africa and
computer models developed in the United States, we can improve
our ability to make best use of limited water resources.  	</P>
<P>
The U.S. and South Africa also agreed to join forces to combat
the threat of emerging infectious diseases.  Under the auspices
of the S&amp;T Committee, South Africa will become a regional
surveillance and response center in a global network called for
by the Clinton Administration last month.  The two sides will
also work together in the areas of telemedicine and biomedical
research, under a newly created subgroup on health. 	 	</P>
<P>
As a result of the S&amp;T Committee's meeting, the two sides
will also share information on science policy and technology
commercialization.  As a first step, the U.S. and South Africa
signed an agreement between the Department of Commerce's National
Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) and the South
African Council for Scientific and Industrial Research (CSIR),
which will pave the way for cooperation in the development of new
technologies, advanced materials for building and construction.
</P></BODY></HTML>
