<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>USIA: U.S. Policy in the Gulf -- Remarks by
Robert Pelletreau, Assistant Secretary of State for Near Eastern
Affairs</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff><IMG SRC="usis2.jpg">
<CENTER><B><H2>Remarks by Robert Pelletreau,<br>
Assistant Secretary of State for Near Eastern Affairs<br>
Washington D.C., June 26, 1995
</H2></B><P>
<IMG SRC="footer.gif"></CENTER> 
<P>
Washington --  Although the United States still faces challenges
in
the Middle East, opportunities exist through the ongoing peace
process to ensure security and stability in the area, Robert H.
Pelletreau, Assistant Secretary of State for Near Eastern
Affairs,
said in Washington June 26.
<P>
In a speech before members of the American-Bahrain Friendship
Society, Pelletreau expressed hope that with Syrian-Israel
military
talks now underway in Washington, "a real opportunity exists for
progress in these talks.  At the same time, he admitted, "we
recognize that these opportunities are not going to be simple
negotiations and that there are real gaps between the parties on
several key issues."
<P>
The Assistant Secretary also praised efforts by friendly states
in
the Gulf, particularly Bharain, and cited the "strong bonds of
cooperation and friendship between Bahrain and the United States
that "reflects the special relationship that has long existed
between our two countries."
<P>
He praised diplomatic efforts in the Gulf by Ambassador Abdul
Ghaffar, Bahrain's Ambassador to the United States and David
Ransom, President Clinton's representative in Bahrain, along with
Bahrain's Shaikh Issa, to build on the Middle East peace process.
<P>
Following is the text of Pelletreau's remarks: (Begin text) Thank
you, Mr. Ambassador.  Good evening friends, colleagues and
distinguished guests.  It is a pleasure to be with you this
evening
to pay tribute to the strong bonds of cooperation and friendship
between Bahrain and the United States.  This is a date we have
had
for some time.  I am sorry that unexpected travel forced
postponement of earlier dates for this get-together.  Let me
thank
Ambassador Abdul Ghaffar for hosting this event and recognize Tom
Bigley for his leadership of the Society and for the time, energy
and creativity he brings to your activities.
<P>
The American-Bahraini Friendship Society reflects the special
relationship that has long existed between our two countries and
peoples, a relationship founded initially on private humanitarian
contacts but which today has developed into a rich and
multifaceted
interaction involving business, academic and governmental
dimensions.  The U.S. Navy has had a particularly long and
fruitful
relationship with Bahrain.  When I first visited the Pearl of the
Gulf twenty-five years ago, I sought out U.S. naval officers for
briefings.  In preparation for my assignment as Ambassador to
Bahrain in the late 70s, I made sure to consult with Admiral
Bigley
and others at the Pentagon.  Recently at dinner with Bill and
Shirley Crowe in London, we spent much of the evening exchanging
reminiscences of our respective tours in Bahrain.
<P>
This Society's membership includes many of us who have a
professional interest in keeping relations between the U.S. and
Bahrain healthy and strong, but who also have joined to savor
fond
memories and to keep up with good friends.  We also share in
admiration and respect for His Highness, Shaikh Issa, whose
hospitality and kindness so many of us have enjoyed, and whose
wise
leadership has kept Bahrain safe and prospering in perilous
times.
<P>
The day-to-day management of our relations is in excellent hands.
Ambassador Abdul Ghaffar has played a large role in nurturing the
U.S.-Bahraini relationship since he arrived, and for that we are
grateful. His work here in Washington and at the UN has helped
extend and deepen our good relations.
<P>
President Clinton's representative in Bahrain, Ambassador David
Ransom, is likewise a distinguished diplomat who combines a rich
background of experience in the region with solid
political-military expertise.  He is joined by Rear Admiral Scott
Redd, a talented and worthy successor of several former
commanders
of the Middle East Force here tonight.
<P>
Let me say a few words about the challenges and opportunities
facing the United States today in the Middle East: opportunities
to
make further progress in the peace process; and challenges to
security and stability in the Gulf, including the pressures that
friendly states like Bahrain are facing.
<P>
Earlier this month I accompanied Secretary Christopher to the
region on a visit that helped create a new sense of optimism
among
the negotiating parties.  As you know, Syrian-Israel military
talks
begin here in Washington tomorrow.  We believe a real opportunity
exists for progress in these talks.  At the same time, we
recognize
that these are not going to be simple negotiations and that there
are real gaps between the parties on several key issues.  But
they
have narrowed their differences, and it is important that both
have
agreed to direct talks between their Chiefs of Staff.  We are
working closely with both parties to help move these negotiations
forward.
<P>
The Palestinians and Israelis have also taken important steps
forward recently, and are working diligently toward a July 1
target
date for an agreement on implementing the second phase of the
Declaration of Principles.  Even if they miss this target a bit,
we
are encouraged by the prospects for continued progress on this
track.  The holding of Palestinian elections in the period ahead
would be a real breakthrough.
<P>
Jordan and Israel are following up their historic peace accord
signed last October by moving forward on joint development
projects
and cooperative undertakings in a number of spheres, as called
for
in the treaty.  Jordan is also preparing to host the Amman
Economic
and Business Summit this fall whose purpose is to engage the
private sector in new opportunities that are opening in the
region
as a result of progress in the peace process.
<P>
Additionally, the less-publicized multilateral negotiations,
which
bring together Israel, the Palestinians, and over a dozen Arab
countries as well as others, have continued to steadily expand
the
scope of their activities.  Bahrain has been among the countries
supporting these negotiations, agreeing to host the multilateral
working group on the environment last fall which produced a draft
Code of Conduct for the Environment, the first time that has been
done for the Middle East.  We believe work in the multilateral
track is of particular long-term importance to the region, in
that
such collective activities are forging mechanisms of interaction
that buttress peaceful relations.  The United States, in
encouraging the development of productive working relations
between
professionals with similar interests, the elimination of trade
and
travel barriers, reconciliation between countries of the Gulf and
Jordan and the Palestinian Authority, is not seeking to promote
domination of any nation or group of nations over others, but
rather mutual acceptance, tolerance, respect for religious and
cultural diversity, fair economic interaction and the peaceful
resolution of disputes.
<P>
Gulf Security Even as the region inclines toward peace, however,
we
cannot relax our vigilance against threats to security and
stability.  The Gulf in modern times has been inherently unstable
as Iran and Iraq have each sought hegemony.  The fall of the Shah
and the Iranian revolution were followed by eight years of
conflict
between Iran and Iraq.  It would have been preferable to see that
war conclude in mutual exhaustion, without victor or vanquished,
for when Iraq gained the upper hand, Saddam Hussein lost no time
in
seeking domination of the region and its resources.  We are still
living today with the consequences of his naked aggression
against
Kuwait.
<P>
Our policy toward Iraq remains unambiguous: we insist that it
comply fully with all relevant Security Council resolutions
passed
in response to its 1990 invasion.
<P>
Iraq still seeks to resist and evade the will of the
international
community.  Last October it once again mobilized military forces
on
Kuwait's border.  This past week UNSCOM Chairman Rolf Ekeus
reported to the Security Council that Iraq continues to withhold
information on its past biological weapons programs.  This is not
unexpected news.  It is consistent with the Baghdad regime's
failure to cooperate in accounting for Kuwaiti citizens and
others
missing in action in the 1990 conflict, its arrogant and
repressive
violation of minimal human rights standards for Iraq's citizens
in
the north, south, and even central parts of the country, and its
ludicrous claim that it is returning Kuwait military equipment
when
the junk it is turning over has clear Iranian markings and our
satellites can readily identify Kuwaiti equipment being used in
Republican Guard units.
<P>
The regime's stubborn defiance unfortunately exacerbates the
hardships faced by the Iraqi people.  In April, we and other
states
formulated a new Security Council resolution to facilitate and
simplify Iraqi oil sales to finance the purchase of food,
medicines, and other humanitarian items. Although Iraq's dictator
has rejected this gesture in a knee-jerk reaction, it remains on
the table as a way of relieving the suffering of innocent people
who are not our enemies.
<P>
Regarding Iran, U.S. policy is focused on Iran's actions; not on
the nature of its government.  We remain concerned about Iranian
support for international terrorism, its support for groups
violently opposed to the peace process, its threats toward
neighboring states and support for subversive movements, and its
pursuit of weapons of mass destruction and high-tech rearmament.
<P>
We have been working to focus additional international pressure
on
Iran to change this behavior.  On April 30, the President
announced
a ban on U.S. trade with and investment in Iran.  We invite
others
to refrain from actions that would provide benefits to Iran, such
as extending credits or investment guarantees or
opportunistically
filling in behind cancelled American contracts.  This will
further
tighten the economic constraints on the regime.  Our aim is to
convince the Iranian leadership that a change in Tehran's
policies
would be in Iran's own interest and that there are costs to not
doing so.
<P>
Iran's intentions toward shipping in the Straits of Hormuz have
also provoked concern.  Iran's military reinforcement appears
designed to enforce its territorial claims over Abu Musa and the
Tunbs islands, over which the UAE also claims sovereignty.  The
lack of Iranian response to UAE invitations over the past year to
settle this difference peacefully is unjustified.  Although there
has been some cutback in the alert-status of those Iranian
forces,
we continue to monitor them carefully in line with our concern
for
the freedom of navigation in this vital waterway.
<P>
Gulf Collective Security Our efforts to counter the threatening
potential of Iran and Iraq are complemented by bolstering the
defensive capabilities of our friends in the Gulf region.  We are
encouraging Bahrain and the other members of the GCC to continue
to
work together on collective defense and security.  We have
strengthened our own ability to act quickly in the region by
maintaining strong forces, by prepositioning equipment and
material, and by providing defense articles to friendly states.
<P>
Our goal is to complement, not replace the Gulf states'
collective
security efforts.  We do not intend to station troops permanently
anywhere in the region.  Our objective is to support our friends,
to deter threats, and to reduce the likelihood that we and our
allies would have to resort again to warfare to repel aggression.
<P>
As friends of Bahrain, we are concerned not only with external
threats to its security.  We are also troubled by the unrest that
Bahrain has recently experienced.  We recognize the government's
responsibility to guarantee public safety and security.  We also
appreciate the Government's efforts to find ways to address the
economic and political concerns that have fuelled dissatisfaction
among groups of Bahraini youth.  While the worst of this wave of
unrest seems to have passed, without posing a serious threat to
the
government or the country's stability, its underlying causes
remain
an ongoing challenge to be addressed.
<P>
As Bahrain in the past has demonstrated ingenuity and
farsightedness in developing its banking sector, its
communications
and transportation infrastructure and even its tourism industry,
and as it has invested heavily in education and health services,
its capable leaders must continue their efforts to give every
Bahraini a stake in the country's future, to provide employment
openings and social justice, and the opportunity for the
country's
youth to lead productive lives in dignity.  We are confident the
Government will meet this challenge as it has all others in the
past.  The announcement of a new cabinet June 25th is an
indication
of the Government's seriousness in bringing fresh energy and
initiative to this task.
<P>
America's ties and friendship with Bahrain reach back over many
decades and have grown with the passage of time.  We are all
proud
of Bahrain's accomplishments and have watched in admiration as
Manama has developed into a vibrant capital and international
center of economic and financial activity.  The U.S.-Bahraini
relationship has many facets: it contributes to regional peace
and
stability in an unsettled region, it generates a healthy trade
and
commercial interchange for our businesses, and it brings our
peoples closer together.  We look forward to many more decades of
close cooperation.  So let me take this opportunity to
acknowledge
these accomplishments, to express our continuing support for
Bahrain in the future, and to celebrate the special U.S.-Bahraini
friendship that has brought us together this evening.
<P>
<HR>
