<HEAD>
<TITLE>U.S. - S.A. Business Development Committee</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">
<CENTER>
<H3>U.S. - S.A. Business Development Committe  
</H3></CENTER>
<P>The U.S. - S.A. Business Development Committee (BDC) was
established in 1994 as a high level means to facilitate the
reestablishment of commercial relations between the two
countries.  The Terms of Reference establishing the BDC were
signed by the late Commerce Secretary Ron Brown and then Minister
of Trade and Industry Trevor Manuel in Atlanta on June , 1994.
The inaugural meeting of the BDC was held in Washington, D.C. in
September, 1994.
</P>
<P>The BDC consists of 21 private sector representatives from
each country, selected by their respective governments.  The
committee has as its focus four principal areas: removing
obstacles to two-way trade and investment; improving conditions
for commercial activity in both countries; implementing
promotional programs to assist their respective business
communities enter the other's markets; and articulating
additional steps which may or ought to be taken to facilitate and
encourage the growth and development of commercial relations
between the parties.  Over the past two years, the BDC has
focused its activities in the areas of: finance and investment,
market access, technology transfer and business development.
</P>
<P>The BDC's  accomplishments over the past two years have
included: a soon to be launched Technical Assistance Center to
expand business opportunities for black South Africans, a legal
clerkship program to expand non-traditional access to the
commercial law field in South Africa, Intellectual property law
seminars in South Africa, financial services trade missions to
South Africa; and enhanced market access for S.A. products into
the United States.
</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
