<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>2nd Meeting: Gore Press Conference Remarks</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY
BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#602B1A" VLINK="#C95A36" ALINK="#7C0418">
<PRE>
                        THE WHITE HOUSE
                  Office of the Vice President
______________________________________________________________________________

For Immediate Release
July 23, 1996


         United States-South Africa Binational Commission


    REMARKS PREPARED FOR DELIVERY BY VICE PRESIDENT AL GORE
                            AT THE 
 US-SOUTH AFRICAN BINATIONAL COMMISSION JOINT PRESS CONFERENCE

     Good  afternoon.   I would like to begin by thanking all the dedicated men and women
who have worked so hard these past months to make this meeting of the U.S.-South Africa
Binational Commission a true success.  My special thanks, though, go to South Africa's Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki for the commitment and leadership he has shown throughout the BNC
process which we began here in Washington in March of 1995 and continued in Pretoria late last
year.

     Created by the clear vision and very good sense of Presidents Mandela and Clinton, our
Binational Commission exists to support one very simple, but fundamental idea that our nations
can grow stronger, wiser, more free and prosperous when our citizens join together in common
cause to confront common challenges, and to take advantage of shared opportunities.   

     We have accomplished a great deal since our last meeting.   Together, we have explored
ways to reduce pollution, conserve water, manage waste, empower and educate our young
people, protect our environment, improve agricultural practices, build free markets and free
minds, and help open the door to real economic opportunity for all our citizens.  
     
     By sharing experience and know-how, we also have been enriching both our nations. 
Since our Commission's first meeting, over 100 South African leaders have participated in
professional exchanges with their American counterparts. We also have launched the Mandela
scholars program which is providing graduate-level economics training for historically
disadvantaged South Africans.  

     These young people truly are the best hope for our future.  I would like to ask those
Mandela scholars who are here today to stand up and be recognized....  

     Each of you should know we are all very, very proud of you.

     If I may, I would like briefly to review some of the important new steps we've taken in
the past few days across the full range of our Commission's efforts, from promoting trade and
investment, to cooperation on agriculture, sustainable energy, science and technology, human
resources development and education, and our environment.    

     -- First, I am pleased to announce that earlier today, Ruth Harkin, the President of the
U.S. Overseas Private Investment Corporation, signed an Investment Fund Protocol to support a
120 million dollar private equity fund that will invest in businesses in South Africa owned by the
country's  majority population.  This new fund represents a major step towards spurring
investment, trade, job creation and growth in a new, robust and prosperous South Africa.  I am
proud that our Commission has played and important role in making this new fund a reality.  

    --  The civil aviation agreement we just signed also is emblematic of the many other
accomplishments of the BNC.  This agreement will restore formal aviation relations between the
U.S. and South Africa for the first time since they were broken in protest over apartheid more
than nine years ago.   The agreement is borne of mutual need and will serve our mutual self-interest.  
The flow of trade, investment and tourism between our two countries has grown
enormously in the last two years.  By recent count, one new American business per week has set
up shop in South Africa.  American tourism to South Africa has doubled in that same period. 
This new agreement will meet the existing need for more passenger and cargo flights between
our countries and provides for increasing scheduled and charter flights to meet the further growth
that is sure to come.  

     --  We also have agreed during this session to expand our cooperative efforts to combat
crime.  The U.S. will contribute substantially to South Africa's request for assistance to help
realize the full potential of its law enforcement forces. 

     Working together, sharing ideas and expertise, I know we can improve the quality of law
enforcement in both countries and can help each other ensure the safety and security our citizens
deserve.

     -- We also signed a Declaration of Intent to help bring South Africa into the growing
community of schoolchildren, teachers,  and scientists around the world that participate in a
program which we call &quot;GLOBE&quot;;  or &quot;Global Learning and Observation to Benefit the
Environment.&quot;  This is a hands-on science education program we formed at the beginning of the
Administration that links students, educators and scientist around the world through the Internet
to study our environment, and share data about our planet with scientists and each other. 
Already, some 37 nations and tens of thousands of  students participate in this important effort.  I
am glad that South Africa soon will become a GLOBE partner as well.  

     -- We also pledged today to proceed with a partnership to create a Fulbright Commission
which will improve and expand the ways in which Americans and South Africans study and
conduct research together.

     --  We are working with our partners in South Africa to build energy efficient housing,
and to promote the use of renewable and clean fuels, both by industry and in homes. 
     
     --  Our Peace Corps also will soon provide talented young Americans with the chance to
work with South Africans where they live to help improve education and foster good-will.  

     Through these, and many other initiatives of our Binational Commission,  the U.S. and
South Africa are building a matrix of mutually beneficial connections, programs, exchanges and
business ventures.  

     Some of those, like the civil aviation agreement, are bearing fruit today.  Others, like the
Mandela Scholars program and the Fulbright Commission, will pay dividends in the future.  But
these are all part of the same critical effort -- to establish a healthy give and take across all
aspects of our societies, and to nurture the possibilities of peace, justice, and prosperity for all
our citizens.  I am deeply proud of our work together.  And Mr. Deputy President, may I say that
I look forward to our next meeting in South Africa.   Thank you very much......  Mr. Deputy
President?



                              ###

</PRE></BODY></HTML>
