<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release July 23, 1996</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY
BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#993300" VLINK="#666600" ALINK="#cccccc">
<H3 ALIGN="center">THE WHITE HOUSE<BR>  Office of the Vice
President</H3>
<P>_________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>For Immediate Release	July 23, 1996
</P>
<P> United States-South Africa Binational Commission Agriculture
Committee  	</P>
<P>Vice President Al Gore and South African Deputy President
Thabo Mbeki today announced the signing of the Joint Terms of
Reference that outline the functions and organizational structure
of the Agriculture Committee of the U.S.-South Africa Binational
Commission. 
</P>
<P>	&quot;Our interests lay far beyond respective trade between
our countries.  We believe work by this Committee can result in
rural development and agribusiness development for South Africa.&quot;
Vice President Gore said.  &quot;Agriculture joins five other
committees -- Human Resources and Development; Trade and
Investment; Science and Technology; Conservation, Environment and
Water; and Energy -- that provide a mechanism for high-level
discussions on mutual interests between our two countries.&quot; 
  	</P>
<P>The groundwork for the Agriculture Committee was done in
December 1995 during a visit by the Vice President to South
Africa for the second meeting of the U.S.-South Africa Binational
Commission.  The Committee, which is co-chaired by U.S.
Department of Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman and Republic of
South Africa Minister of Land and Agriculture, Derek Andre
Hanekom, held its first meeting March 26, 1996.  Four working
groups were formed to address agricultural issues related to
market access, institutional development, agricultural technology
development for income generation, and sustainable agricultural
and rural development.  	</P>
<P>The Agriculture Committee also sponsored an agribusiness
forum in March that attracted more than 70 U.S. and South African
agribusiness representatives. The forum gave participants the
opportunity to exchange information on doing business in South
Africa.  	</P>
<P></P>
<P>Other major deliverables of the Agriculture Committee include
the following:  --	By the end of  FY 1996, 45 South Africans will
have completed short-term, individualized training in
agribusiness trade and investment in the United States under the
Cochran Fellowship Program;  --	 	USDA placed an agribusiness
advisor in Capetown in March 1996.   This advisor will act as a
liaison between the U.S. and South African Agribusiness
communities; 
</P>
<P>	A USDA Nutrition Advisor provided technical assistance on
policy formulation of a national school feeding program to the
South African Department of Health which began in mid-November
1995.  The Nutrition Advisor returned to the United States in
mid-February, 1996; 
</P>
<P>	 	Advanced research training fellowships will give promising
young scientists from South Africa an opportunity to obtain
advanced degrees in the United States;  	 </P>
<P>	More than 300,000 children's books and text books will be
provided to supply libraries in rural schools and communities of
South Africa;  	</P>
<P> 	USDA authorized $50 million in credit guarantees for sales
of U.S. agricultural commodities to South Africa under the
Commodity Credit Corporation's Intermediate Export Credit
Guarantee Program (GSM-103).  This is the first such program in a
Sub-Saharan African country; 
</P>
<P>	*	The Promotion of Village Banks (Rural Cooperatives) USDA
will provide technical assistance to the South African government
in the facilitation of the creation of locally-based financial
institutions to service the lower end of the South African market
due to the inability of existing public and private financial
institutions to fill the market gap; and  	 </P>
<P>	Seminars, workshops, and food shows will be sponsored by
USDA.  The programs will include discussions of Sanitary and
Phyto-Sanitary issues, use of U.S. wood products, food marketing
seminars, collaborative research workshops on advanced farming
techniques, early warning climate systems, and plant and animal
disease research. 				 	</P>
<P>USDA has in the pipeline numerous additional joint projects
with the South African Department of Agricutlure.  The South
African Department of Agriculture officials have indicated that
they have additional programs and projects they would like to see
jointly 	 implemented and will provide some funding for these
initiatives.
</P></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
