<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>USIA: U.S. Policy in the Gulf-- Dept. of State
Official Discusses U.S.-Kuwait Relations</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff><IMG SRC="usis2.jpg">
<CENTER><B><H2>Dept. of State Official<br>
Discusses U.S.-Kuwait Relations<br>
May 4, 1996</H2></B><P>
<IMG SRC="footer.gif"></CENTER> 
<P>
(Kuwait Assured on Sanctions Against Iraq) 
<p>
Washington -- A State Department official emphasized April 4 that
"there can be no discussions of an easing of the international
sanctions" until Iraq fulfills the obligations established by the
Security Council in the wake of the Gulf War.
<P>
John Craig, director of the Office of Arabian Peninsula Affairs
at
the State Department, gave this assurance at a seminar here
titled,
"A Partnership for Stability and Prosperity: Kuwait and the
U.S.-Kuwait Relationship."
<P>
The State Department official added that Iraq "must dismantle its
programs of weapons of mass destruction, account for the over 600
Kuwaiti prisoners and missing persons and return Kuwaiti property
and put a stop to the human rights abuses of the Iraqi people." 
The seminar, sponsored by the U.S.-GCC Corporate Cooperation
Committee, is the first in a year-long series examining the
United
States' "special relationship" with the six-member countries of
the
Gulf Cooperation Council.
<P>
Other speakers at the seminar included Kuwait Deputy Chief of
Mission Abdul-al S. al-Qenaei, who has been named his country's
ambassador to India; David A. Hamod, Washington representative of
the American Business Council of the Gulf Countries, and Col.
Edward D. Bishop, director of the U.S. Central Command Liaison
Office at the Department of Defense.  Dr. John Duke Anthony,
president of the National Council on U.S.-Arab Relations,
moderated
the event.
<P>
Following is the official text of his remarks, as delivered:
(Begin
text) Mr. Ambassador, and distinguished guests, this past month
and
a half we have witnessed a series of important events that
highlight the very close friendship that characterizes U.S.
relations with Kuwait.  On February 28, His Highness Amir Jaber
al-Sabah paid an official visit to Washington, meeting with the
President and receiving calls from the Vice President and four
other Cabinet officers.  On March 13, First Deputy Prime Minister
and Foreign Minister Sheikh Sabah al-Ahmad al-Sabah participated
in
the Summit of the Peacemakers in Sharm el-Sheikh, Egypt, where he
carried the Kuwaiti Government's message strongly condemning
terrorism.  Just two weeks ago, former President Bush and His
Highness Crown Prince Saad presided at the official opening of
the
beautiful new U.S. Embassy building in Kuwait, a gift of the
Kuwaiti people to the American people.  As you can imagine, it
would be an understatement to say that former President Bush was
warmly welcomed in Kuwait.
<P>
I would like to describe some of the government-to-government
cooperation that is the basis of this relationship.  Starting
with
security cooperation and, foreshadowing the more detailed
presentation of Colonel Bishop, allow me to note what has been
achieved.  In September 1991 the United States and Kuwait signed
a
Defense Cooperation Agreement which has become a model for
similar
agreements that we later entered into with other Gulf states.
Under
this agreement, Kuwaiti and U.S. troops engage in one of the
heaviest combined exercise schedules in the world.  The U.S. and
Kuwaiti militaries are working closely to modernize and upgrade
the
Kuwaiti forces, to make them a powerful deterrent to threats of
aggression aimed at Kuwait.  We saw some early results of this
effort in October 1994 when Saddam once again deployed his
armored
divisions on Kuwait's border.  Kuwait's forces deployed quickly
to
the border in response and, together with a U.S. infantry
division,
thwarted Saddam's planned invasion.  We share the same view of
the
threats to the region and are working together to deter such
threats.  Our security cooperation could not be better.
<P>
We likewise are working very successfully in the diplomatic arena
to keep the sanctions on Iraq firmly in place.  In the UN and in
the capitals of Security Council members, our diplomats carry the
same message -- there can be no discussions of an easing of the
international sanctions until Iraq fulfills the obligations
established by the Security Council, that, among others, Iraq
must
dismantle its programs of weapons of mass destruction, account
for
the over 600 Kuwaiti prisoners and missing persons, return
Kuwaiti
property and put a stop to the human rights abuses of the Iraqi
people.  Kuwait is a full partner in our sanctions enforcement
efforts in the Gulf, which will become even more important if
Iraq
accepts the UN Security Council Resolution 986 allowing it to
sell
oil for food and medicine under tightly monitored conditions.  We
will work closely to ensure that this humanitarian relief
provision
does not allow Iraq to evade the sanctions and its Security
Council
obligations.
<P>
The issue of Kuwaiti prisoners and missing persons from the Gulf
War is intimately tied to Iraq sanctions.  The International Red
Cross maintains files on over 603 Kuwaitis and residents of
Kuwait
that the Iraqi occupation authorities took prisoner or were last
seen in Iraqi custody. These are civilians.  We in the U.S. know
the anguish caused by unaccounted for POWs and we are resolved
that
Iraq must tell the international community where these people are
and what has happened to them.  This requirement is one of the
UN's
cease-fire conditions for ending the Gulf War.  The Red
Cross-sponsored talks on this issue between Iraq and the Gulf War
Coalition allies provides the only regular face-to-face forum
where
we meet with the Iraqis.  The U.S. takes this issue very
seriously
-- we send high-level delegations to these meetings that include,
in addition to ambassadors, POW experts from the Pentagon.
<P>
U.S.-Kuwait cooperation extends to other key diplomatic
initiatives
as well. Kuwait is a strong supporter of the U.S.-led effort to
bring about peace between Israel and its Arab neighbors.  Kuwait
was the first country in the Gulf to renounce the Arab League
boycott on American firms that do business with Israel -- Kuwait
first announced this policy in June 1993 and then led the other
GCC
members to take this step in September 1994.  Kuwait has
generously
supported the establishment of the Palestinian Authority in the
West Bank and Gaza with funding for start-up costs.  This funding
came despite the fact that Kuwait does not maintain relations
with
the PLO. Rather, Kuwait felt obliged to help the Palestinian
people
on their road to autonomy and self-reliance and also to help an
important initiative of their American friends.  In addition, we
have the extremely strong condemnation by the Government of
Kuwait
of the recent bombings in Israel. Kuwaitis abhor this violence
and
are joining us in the struggle against terrorism.
<P>
This cooperation extends beyond the boundaries of the Middle East
as well. When the Amir came to Washington, he heard from the
President and others the importance we attach to securing the
fragile peace in the Balkans and specifically to helping the
Bosnians acquire the means and ability to defend themselves in
the
future.  Kuwait is already providing humanitarian relief to the
Bosnians through private organizations, but we are consulting
closely on Kuwaiti involvement in the international effort to
implement the Dayton Accords as well.
<P>
One growth area for U.S.-Kuwait relations is in the commercial
field.  Since the Gulf War, the U.S. has consistently been the
largest exporter to, and investor in, Kuwait.  In 1994, the U.S.
exported $1.18 billion worth of goods to Kuwait; in 1995, U.S.
exports to Kuwait rose more than 20 percent to $1.4 billion. 
While
our exports to Kuwait in the first years after Desert Storm were
weighted towards the military sector (Kuwait has purchased a
total
of $4.5 billion in U.S. defense goods), now military goods
represent less than one half of our export total to Kuwait.  On
the
investment side, the biggest event to date came in 1994 when
Kuwait's state petrochemical industry signed a $2 billion joint
venture with Union Carbide, which will be the largest
petrochemical
facility in the Gulf.
<P>
The future of our commercial relations, as with our traditional
government-to- government contacts, is indeed bright.  We are
working together in the security field, cooperating to maintain
sanctions on Iraq and support Middle East peace and seeking
greater
joint commercial projects.  Our embassy tells us that Kuwaitis
like
America's quality products and are growing used to American
institutions like Kentucky Fried Chicken.  Kuwaitis welcome the
American presence in Kuwait and they in turn are visiting America
in record numbers as tourists but also as students in American
high
schools, colleges and graduate schools.
<P>
I would like to close by stealing one of the favorite themes of
our
host John Duke Anthony -- that this growth in non-governmental,
people-to-people relations is crucial.  Yes, we share common
national interests in the Gulf, in the Middle East and indeed
throughout the world.  But for our two countries to reach full
understanding, our peoples must get to know each other better.  I
am happy to say that with the help of U.S.-GCC Corporate
Cooperation Committee and other groups, we are getting to know
each
other better.  This greater knowledge and understanding will help
me and my colleagues in the Government to do our jobs better.
<P>
<HR>
<center>This Web site was produced and is maintained by the
United States Information Agency.<P><A HREF="gulfmain.htm">
Return</A> to the Gulf Security Homepage <IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE
SRC="usisflag.gif"> <A HREF="http://www.usia.gov/usis.html">
Return</A> to the USIS homepage 
</CENTER></body></html>
  
