</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>USIA: U.S. Policy in the Gulf-- Remarks by
USIA Director Joseph Duffey to the Bahraini American Friendship
Society</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff><IMG SRC="usis2.jpg">
<CENTER><B><H2>Remarks by USIA Director Joseph Duffey<br> 
to the Bahraini American Friendship Society<br>
November 8, 1995</H2></B><P>
<IMG SRC="footer.gif"></CENTER> 
<P>
Washington -- "Bahrain is well-suited to enter into the new
economic arena that is developing in the Middle East.  Over the
years, Bahrain has wisely invested in developing its banking
sector, and has worked hard to develop its health,
communications, and transportation infrastructure," Dr. Joseph
Duffey said November 8.
<P>
In an address before members of the Bahraini American Friendship
Society, Duffey, Director of the United States Information Agency
(USIA), praised Bahrain for "many years of wise economic
decision-making and forethought. A large number of American
companies have recognized Bahrain's positive economic climate by
locating their regional headquarters on the island," he said.
<P>
"Bahrain also deserves special recognition as a staunch supporter
of the Middle East Peace Process," Duffey said.  "The U.S. has
valued highly Bahrain's participation in the
"MDBO""MDNM"multi-lateral track of (Middle East Peace)
negotiations."
<P>
Duffey admitted that "the political climate in Washington often
forces us to think in the short term ... while overlooking those
states that have proven long-term friends."
<P>
He reminded the audience that "throughout this century, the U.S.
and Bahrain have cooperated, traded, and worked together on
political issues of major importance" and praised Bahrain as "a
vital partner in the goal of assuring a secure and stable Gulf
region."
<P>
Following is the text of Dr. Duffey's remarks, as prepared for
delivery: (Begin text) Thank you, Mr. Ambassador.  Good evening
ladies and gentlemen, friends, colleagues, and distinguished
guests.  It is an honor to be here tonight with all of you to
recognize the strong bonds of friendship between the United
States and Bahrain.  I would like to thank all of you for
attending tonight, and especially thank my friend Ambassador
Abdul Ghaffar for his energy and dedication in strengthening the
ties that exist between our two countries.  I would also like to
recognize Tom Bigley, former Commander of the Middle East Force
in Bahrain, for his active leadership of the Bahraini American
Friendship Society.
<P>
I would also like to acknowledge to all present our sincere
appreciation of His Highness Shaikh Issa and His Excellency the
Crown Prime and Prime Minister, Shaikh Hamad.  They have
demonstrated wise and courageous leadership over many years, and
shown continuing sincere friendship for the United States.
<P>
The political climate in Washington often forces us to think in
the short term and to focus on the burning issues of the day,
while overlooking those states that have proven long-term
friends.   Bahrain, an island nation with a history stretching
back thousands of years, has long been a reliable friend of the
United States, and it is heartening and proper that an
organization such as the Bahraini American Friendship Society
exists to help keep this relationship thriving.  The U.S.-Bahrain
naval relationship extends back decades, long before the Gulf War
brought it global attention, and our diplomatic and commercial
relations have grown steadily since the 1900s.  Throughout this
century, the U.S. and Bahrain have cooperated, traded, and worked
together on political issues of major importance.
<P>
U.S.-Bahraini relations today are in very capable hands.  I
already acknowledged my admiration for all of Ambassador Abdul
Ghaffar's hard work in cementing U.S.-Bahraini ties.  He is
joined in this endeavor by two excellent American officials
currently in Manama: U.S. Ambassador to Bahrain, David Ransom,
and Vice Admiral Scott Redd, Commander of USNAVCENT and the Fifth
Fleet.
<P>
The United States and Bahrain have worked closely for years in
bringing stability and peace to the Gulf region and the Middle
East.  The U.S. relies on Bahrain as a vital partner in the goal
of assuring a secure and stable Gulf region.  Bahrain has offered
more than just words of support. It has taken real action to
assist the U.S. in this important goal.  The U.S. and Bahrain
have worked hard on Gulf security for decades, and many in the
audience tonight have been important figures in building and
maintaining the Bahraini-U.S. commitment to achieving this goal.
<P>
Bahrain also deserves special recognition as a staunch supporter
of the Middle East Peace Process.  The U.S. has valued highly
Bahrain's participation in the multi-lateral track of the
negotiations, particularly Bahrain's hosting of the multilateral
working group on the environment last year.  We saw only last
month at the Amman Economic Summit more dramatic evidence of how
the Peace Process is creating a more dynamic and positive
regional and global economic reality.  Bahrain participated
actively in the Summit through its strong, high-level delegation,
once again proving Bahraini commitment to the peace process.
<P>
Bahrain is well-suited to enter into the new economic arena that
is developing in the Middle East.  Over the years, Bahrain has
wisely invested in developing its banking sector, and has worked
hard to develop its health, communications, and transportation
infrastructure.  Bahrain should feel very proud of the country's
ranking by the Heritage Foundation as third among 101 countries
in the world in terms of economic freedom.  Such a high ranking
can only have come about through many years of wise economic
decision-making and forethought.   A large number of American
companies have recognized Bahrain's positive economic climate by
locating their regional headquarters on the island.
<P>
Bahrain's past economic reforms and initiatives have rightly
earned it a high ranking from the Heritage Foundation.  These
initiatives have included the basic steps needed to institute
reforms in the field of intellectual property protection and
copyright protection.  Bahrain deserves our praise for joining
the World Trade Organization and the World Intellectual Property
Organization.  These positive steps will be even more significant
when Bahrain joins two more important international intellectual
property agreements, the Berne Convention (covering literary
works), and the Geneva Phonograms Convention (covering audio
recordings).  Participation in all these frameworks for the
protection of intellectual property will establish a solid
foundation for the protection of copyrights in Bahrain.
Buttressing these international agreements, reformed copyright
laws and strengthened effective enforcement of those laws within
Bahrain would benefit growing Bahraini companies and encourage
even more U.S. firms to seek cooperative ventures with Bahraini
businesses.
<P>
In addressing the intellectual property rights issue, both
countries benefit from dialogue and comparison of our experiences
and successes.  This can be illustrated by the successful
resolution of a General System of Preferences problem between the
U.S. and Bahrain two years ago.  I am proud to say that USIA had
some part in this, through organizing a visit to the U.S. for a
key Bahraini official involved in labor issues.  In a one-month
trip through the U.S., both Bahraini and American interlocutors
compared their labor systems, issues, and accomplishments,
forming a dialogue that helped to resolve the problem to the
mutual satisfaction of both nations.
<P>
Dialogue is an important aspect of our relationship with Bahrain,
whether the issue focuses on security, political goals, commerce,
or culture. People-to- people activities and exchanges have
helped to cement all aspects of U.S.-Bahraini relations, and
active public diplomacy is a crucial aspect of our relations with
Bahrain.  Our U.S. Information Service in Bahrain, and the
Bahraini Embassy's constant efforts in Washington, have helped to
build personal relationships that form the foundation of our two
nations' friendship.
<P>
The United States Information Service in Bahrain works closely
with all aspects of Bahraini government and society, focusing on
ways of increasing dialogue and cooperation between our two
peoples.  In September, I spoke here in Washington at a ceremony
marking the 55th Anniversary of the International Visitor
program, a USIA program which brings citizens of foreign
countries to the U.S. for month-long visits to acquaint them with
the U.S. and its society.  At the same time, Ambassador Ransom
and our USIS post in Bahrain hosted a similar celebration in
Manama for Bahraini alumni of this program.  This event was
attended by a wide range of Bahraini citizens who had traveled to
the U.S., many for the first time, on this program.  This
distinguished group included three ministers, two former
ministers, five under secretaries, numerous academics,
journalists, and government officials.
<P>
I should also mention an exchange program of note which occurred
two years ago involving the Bahrain Center for Studies and
Research, the director of which, Shaikh Salman bin Hamad
Al-Khalifa, is a good friend of mine.  The Center, working in
conjunction with our USIS office, selected 19 student leaders
from the University of Bahrain for a USIA-organized program on
policy-making in the U.S.  This group visited several American
cities, where the students saw how the U.S. comes to consensus in
foreign and domestic policies, the role of citizen groups, the
role of the  private and public sectors in this process, and the
ongoing debates and discussions that surround public policy in
the U.S.  The students left the U.S. after two weeks with a
greater understanding of the American politics, culture, and
society.  Such programs are vital for the future of the
U.S.-Bahrain relationship, for we need continued dialogue and
understanding between the peoples of our two nations to maintain
the strength of our close ties.  I should mention that the
exchange I have just described was not only closely coordinated
by USIS and the Bahrain Center, but that the Center shared the
cost of carrying out the visit.  In times of austere budgets for
both our governments, this cost-sharing shows the value that both
governments place on our relationship.
<P>
To promote this ongoing dialogue, USIA works closely with
Bahraini educational and cultural institutions.  At Bahrain
University, we have cooperated on exchanges of faculty and
students through the Fulbright Exchange and other programs.  USIA
has been fortunate to work with professionals at the University
in the field of libraries, accreditation, and academic
development.  The high priority that Bahrain places on exchange
with the U.S. can be seen in the history of the country's
participation in the prestigious Eisenhower Fellowship program. 
Bahrain has sent more citizens per capita as  participants in
this highly competitive program than any other nation in the
world.  Finally, Bahrain has always sent excellent participants
on the Humphrey Fellowship program; one Fellow in the U.S. this
year is Bahrain's highest-ranking woman military officer,
currently studying total quality management and hospital
administration in Seattle.
<P>
As a moderate Islamic country with a long history of positive
relations with the U.S. and the West, Bahrain has an important
voice and role in the ongoing dialogue to build understanding
between the Islamic World and the West.  Bahrain has provided a
valuable forum for this dialogue.  USIS Bahrain has arranged
programs in cooperation with Manama's beautiful Bait Al-Quran
Museum, sponsoring American speakers on Arabic poetry, and the
role of Islam in the United States and the Muslim tradition in
the U.S. Such dialogue is imperative to countering the false
notion that the U.S. perceives Islam as an enemy.  Activities
such as these, and such as our gathering here tonight, are
important to strengthen and reaffirm the fact that the
U.S.-Bahraini relationship is a friendship based on mutual
respect and understanding.  By continuing to engage each other in
the fields of security and political cooperation, commerce and
trade, and culture and education, we reaffirm the respect and
understanding that is the grounding of our countries'
relationship.
<P>
Bahrain is one of our oldest and best friends in the Middle East,
a stable and important commercial partner that has made and
continues to make important contributions to Gulf security and
the Middle East peace process.  I am confident that these strong
relations will continue for many more decades, especially when
these relations are founded on the solid ties between the people
of Bahrain and the people of the United States.  I commend the
Bahraini American Friendship Society for its work in
strengthening the relationship between our two nations, and again
thank you for attending this event tonight.
<P>
<HR>
<center>This Web site was produced and is maintained by the
United States Information Agency.<P><A HREF="gulfmain.htm">
