<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Inaugural Meeting Wireless File</TITLE></HEAD><BODY
BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000"><PRE><A NAME="goretext">VICE PRESIDENT GORE'S STATEMENT AT SIGNING
CEREMONY</A>

WASHINGTON -- Deputy President Thabo Mbeki and Vice-President Al Gore signed an
agreement March 1, launching a &quot;new era in partnership&quot; between both the United States and
South Africa.

In a statement released by the Office of the Vice President, Gore said the commission will
facilitate business development, conservation and the environment, energy and human
resources development, education, science and technology.

Following is the text of the Gore statement:

(BEGIN TEXT)

Deputy President Thabo Mbeki and I have just signed a Statement of Intent to form the U.S. -
South Africa Binational Commission.  By doing so, we launch a new era in partnership
between our two democracies.  This Commission will facilitate cooperation so we can move
together in important areas of cooperation: business development, conservation and
environment, energy development, human resources development and education, and science
and technology.  The agreement calls for semi-annual Commission meetings to ensure
bilateral efforts in these key [sic] are moving ahead expeditiously throughout the year.  The
next Commission meeting will be held in South Africa to assess progress made over the next
six months and to set the agenda for future undertakings of the Commission.  Some of the
initiatives include:

-- Business Development Committee, co-chaired by Commerce Secretary Ron Brown, held its
inaugural meeting last September.  The Committee reviewed plans for its next full meeting in
May in Cape Town, South Africa.

-- Secretary Brown also announced plans for a commercial law seminar also scheduled for
May in South Africa.

-- Conservation and Environment Committee, co-chaired by Interior Secretary Babbitt, will
support South Africa's successful wildlife management as a model of sustainable development
of wildlife resources for the rest of Africa.  South Africa will also be brought into the
GLOBE initiative.

-- Energy Development Committee, co-chaired by Energy Secretary Hazel O'Leary, will be
looking at some initiative already under discussion with the South African Government, such
as a Renewable Energy Rural Electrification Pilot Program, construction of a U.S.
photovoltaic cell manufacturing plant in South Africa, and a program of scientific and
technical exchange between U.S. and South African universities.

-- Human Resources Development and Education Committee, co-chaired by U.S. Agency for
International Development Administrator Brian Atwood is looking forward to discussing a
number of initiatives with his South African counterpart, including: a Youth Employment
Skills Program, the Mandela Scholars Program for post-graduate economic studies, a
Fulbright Program, and a Labor-Management Relations Program.

-- The Science and Technology Committee, co-chaired by the President's Adviser for Science
and Technology Policy John Gibbons and Dr. Ngubane, who is here today with Deputy
President Mbeki will focus on completing negotiations for the Framework agreement on
Environment, Science and Technology Cooperation, cooperative programs in fields where
South Africa has conducted world-class scientific research, and the creation of a mentoring
program using U.S. scientists and engineers.

All the U.S. co-chairs are anxious to get to work with their South African counterparts and
they will be making plans for their committees to meet between now and the next full
Commission meeting in the fail.

The importance of PVO's and the private sector can not be over emphasized and the
Commission is a good vehicle to bring together the efforts of public, private sector and NGO
organizations.

Thank you all for coming.
(END TEXT)
NNNN

<A NAME="story">MBEKI, GORE SIGN BUSINESS AGREEMENT AT WHITE HOUSE</A>

WASHINGTON -- Terming the United States bilateral relationship with South Africa &quot;critical
to the future of our world,&quot; Vice President Al Gore signed an agreement March 1 with
visiting South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki aimed at smoothing business relations
between their nations.

Gore said the agreement, which establishes the U.S.-South Africa Binational Commission,
&quot;will launch a new era in partnership between our two democracies.&quot;

The agreement calls for semiannual meetings of the commission to ensure that bilateral efforts
aimed at business cooperation operate smoothly.

Gore explained that the commission &quot;will facilitate cooperation so we can move [forward]
together in important areas of cooperation:  business development, conservation and
environment, energy development, human resources development and education, and science
and technology.&quot;

The vice president added, &quot;We have also agreed that this commission will reach out to
non-governmental organizations and other private sector groups and ask them to become fully
engaged&quot; with the commission's work.

[According to Commerce Department statistics, South Africa purchased $2,200 million worth
of U.S. goods in 1993, making it a larger market for America's exports than all the countries
of eastern Europe combined.]

Deputy President Mbeki noted that &quot;this is a very important day for South Africa&quot; because
the agreement moves forward &quot;relations that have existed between us and the United States
for very many years.  What it says is:  Having done the things we have done together that
gave birth to our non-racial democracy, what next do we do?

&quot;I think the next thing we are trying to do within the context of the U.S.-Africa Binational
Commission,&quot; Mbeki added, is to say:  &quot;There can be a non-racial world.  There can be a
manner of interaction such that those who have more...can share in a way that can produce a
better world for all.&quot;

</PRE></BODY></HTML>
