<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>USIA: U.S. Policy in the Gulf -- Jan Kalicki
Briefing on Bahrain Business Conferences</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff><IMG SRC="usis2.jpg">
<CENTER><B><H2>Jan Kalicki, Counselor of the Dept. of
Commerce<br>
Briefing on Bahrain Business Conferences<br>
February 22, 1996</H2></B><P>
<IMG SRC="footer.gif"></CENTER> 
<P>
(U.S.-GCC conferences will take place March 9-13)  
<P>
Washington -- Two back-to-back conferences aimed at forging a
"partnership" between the public and private sectors in the U.S.
and Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) will take place in Bahrain on
March 9-13.
<P>
Jan H. Kalicki, counselor of the Department of Commerce,
explained
at a Foreign Press Center briefing February 22 that the United
States would like this partnership "to make our economic and
commercial ties" with the six members of the Gulf states as
"prominent" as the security and political relationship.
<P>
The first conference, opening March 9, will be a
government-to-government meeting known as the U.S.-GCC Economic
Dialogue.  This will be followed the next day by the second
U.S.-GCC Business Conference, which is expected to be attended by
more than 200 American businesses.
<P>
The two other briefers at the Foreign Presss Center were Shaun E.
Donnelly, deputy assistant secretary in charge of trade policy
and
programs at the State Department's Bureau of Economic and
Business
Affairs, and Arthur H. Hughes, deputy assistant secretary of
State
for Near Eastern Affairs.
<P>
Following is the text of the "talking points" read by Kalicki at
the briefing:
<P>
(Begin text) 
<p>
IMPORTANCE OF THE CONFERENCE -- It is a pleasure to join with my
colleagues from the Department of State -- Deputy Assistant
Secretary for Near East, Art Hughes, and Deputy Assistant
Secretary
for Economics and Business, Shaun Donnelly, to tell you about the
importance of the second U.S.-GCC Business Conference to the U.S.
government, to the U.S. business community, and to the overall
relationship between the GCC and the United States.
<P>
<ul>
<li>In that relationship, security and political ties have always
been important.  We would like to see the public sectors and the
private sectors form a partnership to make our economic and our
commercial ties an equally prominent part of our relationship.
</ul>
<P>
PUBLIC-PRIVATE PARTNERSHIP -- To that end, for the first time, we
are holding the U.S.-GCC Business Conference in conjunction with
the government-to-government talks in the U.S.-GCC Economic
Dialogue.  We will hold the seventh meeting of the dialogue,
while
we are in Bahrain, as well as the second business conference.
<ul>
<li> The first business conference took place in 1993 in
Washington, DC.  It was highly successful, and we expect that the
second conference in Bahrain will be even more successful.  We
want
it to lead to specific deals, including joint ventures between
U.S.
companies and businesses in the GCC.

<li>In both the dialogue and the conference, we will be
discussing
ways to increase private investment in the GCC, and to strengthen
intellectual property protection, standards, technology transfer
and bilateral trade.

<li>We are addressing these issues in order to spur private
sector
development and to create a greater role for our private sectors
in
addressing the new economic challenges in the region.
</ul>
<P>
PRIVATE SECTOR ROLE -- These challenges include growing
populations
and rising expectations at a time when government resources to
address these challenges are increasingly limited.
<ul>
<li>But there is a growing private sector in the GCC and growing
interest on the part of the U.S. companies to look to the GCC as
a
place to do business.
<li>This conference comes at a time when the Middle East as a
whole
is not only open for business but actually doing more and more
business -- and when American companies are increasingly seeking
to
take advantage of the greater opportunity in the region, and
particularly in the countries of the Gulf Cooperation Council.
<li>We expect at least 200 U.S. business representatives to
attend
the conference, along with several U.S. government officials, and
we expect that there will be an equal or greater number of
business
representatives from the GCC.
<li>U.S.-GCC trade has reached around $21,000 million in recent
years, with annual U.S. exports to the region at $10,000-11,000
million and our imports $11,000-12,000 million.  We want the
trading relationship to expand, both in volume and in the
diversity
of the products traded.
<li>Health care, power generation, telecommunications,
information
systems, and consumer products are some of the areas where we
feel
U.S. companies could form profitable partnerships with their GCC
counterparts.
<li>U.S. investment in the GCC has climbed steadily to $3,800
million in 1994.  But there is potential for higher growth in
this
area as well.
<li>The conference will seek ways to make that growth happen and
to
make deals -- ways to develop stronger ties between our private
sectors in the United States and the GCC so that those ties
become
the underpinning of our overall relationship.
</ul>
<P>
REGIONAL INTEGRATION -- The conference will also reinforce the
common policy goal of greater regional integration.  GCC members
realize that in order to attract foreign investment, they must
create a market in which companies can operate easily in all Gulf
countries.  Companies see the Gulf market as a potentially very
large one once trade barriers are reduced and ultimately
eliminated
among the GCC states.
<ul>
<LI>This policy goal, in fact, is important for the entire Middle
East.  Less than seven percent of the area's total trade is
within
the region itself. We believe that the countries of the Middle
East
want to change this and become valuable trade partners with each
other, along with the rest of the world.

<li>So we look forward to the Bahrain meetings.  They will
reinforce our trade and investment ties.  They will contribute to
private sector development -- and private sector initiative in
the
region.  And they will encourage economic cooperation and
integration in the Gulf and the wider Middle East.
</ul>
<P> 
<HR>
