</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>USIA: U.S. Policy in the Gulf</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff><IMG SRC="usis2.jpg">
<CENTER><B><H2>Speech by Commerce Secretary Ron Brown<br>
to the American Business Council of Kuwait<br>
February, 8, 1995</H2></B><P>
<IMG SRC="footer.gif"></CENTER> 
<P>
Kuwait -- "The economies of all nations are more and more
dependent upon exports, upon competing in a very tough and
difficult global economic environment," U.S. Secretary of
Commerce Ronald H. Brown said on February 8.
<P>
In a speech to the American Business Council of Kuwait, Brown
said the United States desires to "reach out to our friends in
Kuwait and to help to build a strong commercial relationship to
enhance our trade and investment and economic and commercial
relationship."  He also stressed the importance of a strong and
effective public-private partnership in this commercial
enterprise.
<P>
"We hope and trust that all of you here will help us pursue those
goals, goals that will bring us closer together, goals that will
enhance our relationship, goals that will turn friendships that
were forged during times of war into friendships that will be
built upon during times of peace," Brown concluded.
<P>
Following is the text of the secretary's speech.
<P>
It is my honor and pleasure to be in Kuwait.  This is my first
visit here. It is an important visit, because once again it
demonstrates a desire of the United States to reach out to our
friends in Kuwait and to help to build a strong commercial
relationship to enhance our trade and investment and economic and
commercial relationship.  We have stood together in times of
threat of war and peril, and stood together in war and peril.  We
believe that it is time now to stand together in times of
commercial enterprise, to improve the lives of people of both of
our nations.  We think to do that there has to be a strong and
effective public private partnership.  And that's why I am so
pleased to be informed tonight that there are senior officials of
the Kuwaiti government, cabinet ministers. There are senior
officials of American companies here, there are leaders of
Kuwaiti companies and there is what I hope you believe is a
distinguished delegation from the United States, those that have
travelled with me over these last several days.  Since everyone
is standing, I can't ask them to stand and be recognized, but I
would like to ask them -- all those that are a member of our
delegation, they can just raise their hands and be recognized by
those of us who are here.  You can give them a round of applause.
<P>
The delegation is really symbolic of our world view.  We believe
that security issues are inextricably tied to economic issues,
that you can't talk about one without the other.   Nations cannot
be as secure as far as their defense and national security is
concerned unless they are economically secure.  And that is why
we have been endeavoring to build a new relationship between the
public and private sector in America, with a clear understanding
that it is the private sector that fuels the engine that pulls
the train of economic growth and job creation, but that we in
government can be stronger and more effective partners.  What I
have endeavored to do as Secretary of Commerce is to be a strong,
and hopefully effective advocate for American business and
industry around the world.  I believe that the united states is
the most productive and competitive nation on the face of this
earth.  I believe that we manufacture the highest quality
products and manufacture them at a cost competitive price. It
means that we not only want to compete effectively but we want to
win that competition around the world.  We are not afraid of
competition.  We are not afraid of open and transparent
processes, predictable processes, that anyone can look at and
feel comfortable with.  We are now endeavoring to expand those
victories to demonstrate to people around the world that we are
willing to go out and compete for business.  For many years as
you know because of the size of the United States and the
strength of our economy we often depended just on our domestic
economy.  We were frankly rather late coming to the notion that
in fact the future lies in international commerce.  That is even
more true now than ever with the globalization of the economy.  I
know many of you Americans who are here in Kuwait and have been
here many years, many of you Kuwaitis who are working for
American companies have known that for many years.   You have
been the true pioneers on whom we have relied.  We have learned
much from you and my conversations with our distinguished
Ambassador, he indicated that he is doing here what I do every
day, and that is to listen to the business community.  There is
no way that he can be an effective Ambassador or I can be an
effective Secretary of Commerce unless I am listening to the
private sector, unless I am listening and paying attention to
people who are out there every day where the rubber meets the
road so to speak, identifying the barriers and barricades and
obstacles to conduct in commerce.  We think we've made
extraordinary strides.  One of those extraordinary strides was
completion of the Uruguay Round of trades negotiations and the
resulting beginning on January 1 of the World Trade Organization.

Anything that we can do to lower tariff and non-tariff barriers
to remove obstacles to trade and commerce not only helps the
economies of our individual nations, but helps the global economy
as well.
<P>
Finally, let me say a word about what is happening in this region
and the great sense of hope and optimism that I feel that has
been reinforced by our travels this week.  Our first stop was
Cairo.  President Clinton asked me to change my itinerary to
visit first with President Mubarak to express our sincere
appreciation to President Mubarak for his personal leadership and
that of Egypt in pursuit of the peace process.  The fact is that
real change cannot come to the region until there is true and
lasting peace.  I expressed that appreciation and had a long
conversation with President Mubarak about his view of the future.

And I must say that that view is one of significant optimism.  We
left Cairo and we went on to Israel where we had the opportunity
to meet with Prime Minister Rabin, with senior officials with the
Israeli government.  And again the same sense of hope and
optimism was exhibited there, notwithstanding the recent
setbacks.  The road to peace is not going to be without
impediments.  It's not going to be without events which serve as
temporary setbacks.  But it seems to me we must be willing to
keep pursuing peace to overcome those setbacks.  We went from
there to Ramallah on the West Bank and met with Palestinian
business leaders, and leaders of PECDAR who are looking to a
future where there is economic opportunity and economic growth
and then later yesterday to Gaza, where I had the opportunity to
meet with Chairman Arafat, where he made the strongest statements
that he has yet made about terrorism and about violence and about
his desire to see it ended.  From there we went to Taba in Egypt,
where we had an historic meeting, where the trade and economics
and commerce ministers of the United States and those
representing the Palestinians of Jordan of Israel and Egypt sat
together for the first time -- a meeting that would not have been
thinkable just a year ago.  But it took place and there was real
dialogue and real interchange and a real effort to deal with
problems that exist.  From there it was on to Jordan, where we
spent part of today in Aqaba meeting with officials of the
Jordanian government.  All talked about how we could pursue the
peace process but most important, how we have to consider
economic development and economic progress in the context of
peace.  As peace comes to a region the expectations of the people
are raised considerably, and we have to determine how we can meet
those expectations.  Tension often comes from depravation and
from poverty and lack of hope from an inability to look beyond
the horizon and think that tomorrow is going to be better than
today.  Peace is pursued when people feel that they have a stake
in their future and the way that we can pursue that stake in a
positive sense is to try to secure that economic future.  We left
Aqaba and flew here to Kuwait, and we are honored to be here. 
Tomorrow morning early I'm going to have an opportunity to meet
with some of the American troops who are still here, trying to
help protect the security of Kuwait, and tonight we had a
wonderful meeting with His Highness the Crown Prince, where we
discussed a number of bilateral issues.  We also discussed the
need to continue to reach out to American companies for
expertise, for the products and goods and services that we have
to offer.  And my clear impression was that the Crown Prince was
open to that idea as have been the various ministers with whom we
have talked.  We make no secret about the purpose of our mission.
The purpose of our mission is to advocate the interests of
American business and industry.  We know that the economies of
all of our nations are more and more dependent upon exports, upon
competing in a very tough and difficult global economic
environment.  We know for example in the United States every
billion dollar increase in exports means twenty thousand new jobs
for the American people.  And that is why it is very important
for us to be successful in our pursuit of commercial
opportunities here in Kuwait.  We hope and trust that all of you
here will help us pursue those goals, goals that will bring us
closer together, goals that will enhance our relationship, goals
that will turn friendships that were forged during times of war
into friendships that will be built upon during times of peace. 
So I speak for our entire delegation and for the President of the
United States when I express my appreciation for your warmth and
for your hospitality.  We look forward to seeing you often in the
future.  Thank you very much.
<P>
<HR>
