<HEAD>
<TITLE>2nd meeting Commercial Ties</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">
<H2>U.S., SOUTH AFRICA SIGN AGREEMENTS RENEWING COMMERCIAL TIES</H2>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States and South Africa signed four
agreements July 23 aimed at improving relations and reinstating
commercial ties that were sundered more than nine years ago
during the apartheid era. 
</P>
<P>
Vice President Al Gore, who signed the agreements for the United
States during a ceremony at the White House, said the new era of
U.S.-South African cooperation was based on one fundamental idea:
 &quot;that our nations can grow stronger, wiser, more free and
prosperous when our citizens join together in common cause to
confront common challenges and take advantage of shared
opportunities.&quot; 
</P>
<P>
The four agreements included two dealing with air transport
issues, a &quot;declaration of intent&quot; regarding the GLOBE
environmental program and a &quot;declaration of mutual
anti-crime cooperation.&quot;  Deputy President Thabo Mbeki
signed on behalf of the South African government.
</P>
<P>
 The agreement signing took place against the backdrop of the
two-day U.S.-South Africa Binational Commission (BNC) meeting. 
The BNC was established more than a year ago to smooth commercial
relations between the two trading partners.  Gore and Mbeki head
the body, whose six special committees, led by Cabinet-level
energy, transport, and trade officials from both countries, meet
semiannually in alternating capitals. 
</P>
<P>
Gore noted that when Presidents Clinton and Mandela formed the
BNC &quot;it was really a statement by the two of them and by our
two peoples that each nation regards its relationship with the
other as being sufficiently important to warrant a very heavy
investment of time, thought, and energy&quot; on both sides. 
</P>
<P>
The result, he explained, was a commission meant &quot;to engage
at a high level in an effort to remove all the obstacles to
further improvement&quot; in U.S.-South African relations and &quot;seek
out opportunities to work together.&quot; 
</P>
<P>
Deputy President Mbeki and his party, which included Minister for
Trade and Industry Alec Erwin, took advantage of the BNC meeting
to have discussions with top U.S. government officials,
legislators, and business representatives.  In addition, the
South Africans were honored at receptions hosted by the State
Department, the U.S. Information Agency, and the U.S.-South
Africa Business Council.  The delegation also visited the Olympic
Games in Atlanta, where they witnessed the winning of a gold
medal by a South African swimmer. 
</P>
<P>
Referring to the commission's deliberations in Pretoria six
months ago, Gore said:  &quot;We have accomplished a great deal
since our last meeting.  Together, we have explored ways to
reduce pollution, conserve water, manage wastes, educate young
people, empower our citizens, improve agricultural practices,
build free markets and free minds, and help open the door to real
economic opportunity for all of our citizens.&quot; 
</P>
<P>
The vice president mentioned a number of initiatives undertaken
by the U.S. government to help the new South Africa, including
professional exchanges in which more than 100 South African
leaders have traveled to America to interact with their American
counterparts, and the Mandela Scholars Program, launched to
provide graduate-level training in economics to historically
disadvantaged South Africans. 
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said that in the past few days the commission's
efforts have resulted in further U.S. initiatives, including the
signing by the Overseas Private Investment Corporation (OPIC) of
an investment fund protocol to support a $120 million private
equity fund that will invest in businesses in South Africa owned
by blacks. 
</P>
<P>
Gore pointed out that the OPIC fund &quot;represents a major step
towards spurring investment, trade, job creation, and growth in a
new, robust, and prosperous South Africa -- it is a major step
forward.&quot; 
</P>
<P>
The civil aviation agreements that were signed, said Gore, &quot;will
restore formal aviation relations between the United States and
South Africa for the first time since they were broken in protest
over apartheid more than nine years ago.&quot; 
</P>
<P>
Such an agreement is timely, the vice president pointed out,
considering that &quot;the flow of trade, tourism, and investment
between our two countries has grown enormously during the past
two years.  By recent count, one new U.S. business per week has
set up shop in South Africa.  And American tourism to South
Africa has doubled during that period,&quot; he added. 
</P>
<P>
In addition, Gore noted that the United States has agreed to do
the following:  help South Africa improve its law enforcement
techniques, especially in the area of criminal intelligence
gathering; proceed with a partnership to establish a Fulbright
commission, &quot;which will improve and expand the ways
Americans and South Africans study and conduct research together&quot;;
and send Peace Corps volunteers who &quot;will work with South
Africans where they live to help improve education and foster
good will.&quot; 
</P>
<P>
The vice president emphasized that it is through such initiatives
of the BNC that the United States and South Africa &quot;are
building a matrix of mutually beneficial connections, programs,
exchanges, and business ventures...to establish a healthy and
equal give-and-take across all aspects of our two societies and
to nurture the possibilities of peace, justice, and prosperity
for all our citizens.&quot; 
</P>
<P>
Turning to Gore, Deputy President Mbeki said, &quot;I wish to
reiterate our appreciation for the warmth with which you have
received us and join you in noting the extraordinary amount of
work that has been done, during this session, in the great growth
and scope of cooperation&quot; between South Africa and the
United States. 
</P>
<P>
During a press conference following the signing ceremony, Gore
added that &quot;Deputy President Mbeki and I have an ongoing
dialogue on what we call 'off-line' issues.  And they encompass
virtually every issue in the [U.S.-South African] relationship. 
We can't solve all of them [problems], but we try.&quot; 
</P>
<P>
One of those problems -- the U.S. federal court case against the
South African parastatal Armscor corporation charging its
involvement in the illegal transference of arms to countries the
United States regards as terrorist/aggressor nations -- is
something that Gore said &quot;Deputy President Mbeki and I have
worked on for quite some time now.&quot;
</P>
<P>
 &quot;We've had some very good, substantive discussion over the
past two days&quot; on the Armscor issue, Gore added.  And &quot;our
representatives have had very good, substantive discussions over
the past 10 days.  Both sides very much want this matter
resolved.  We are cautiously optimistic.  But beyond that we have
decided not to comment lest we complicate the productive
discussions at this very delicate stage.&quot;
</P></BODY></HTML>
