<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>USIA: U.S. Policy in the Gulf -- Pelletreau
Remarks at
the Middle East Policy Council, Washington, D.C., October 12,
1995.</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff><IMG SRC="usis2.jpg"><CENTER>
<B><H2>Remarks by Robert H. Pelletreau,<br>
Assistant Secretary of State for Near Eastern Affairs<br>
At the Middle East Policy Council, Washington, D.C.,<br> 
October 12, 1995.</H2></B><P>
<IMG SRC="footer.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
Good morning Senator McGovern, distinguished guests, colleagues,
and friends. I'd like to
congratulate Senator McGovern and the Middle East Policy Council
for organizing this
conference on Oman. I am honored to be your kick-off speaker. It
is a pleasure to be here
and to participate in honoring the twenty-fifth accession to the
throne of His Majesty Sultan
Qaboos. Today, Oman has become a leader on the Arabian Peninsula
in areas as diverse as
enhancing regional security and free trade, support for the
Middle East peace process,
delinking terrorism and Islamic fundamentalism, the education and
political empowerment of
women, protecting the environment, and the effort to develop a
post-oil economy. Under His
Majesty's leadership, Oman has made great strides in its
development during the past
twenty-five years, both domestically and internationally. The
evolution of the close and
cooperative relationship between the U.S. and Oman during this
time is a result of His
Majesty's interest and guidance. His Majesty Sultan Qaboos
visited Washington in 1983.
Vice President Bush twice visited Oman, in 1983 and in 1986, and
Vice President Gore
recently traveled to Oman this past March. We are proud to count
Oman and His Majesty as
close partners and friends.
<P>
The U.S. and Oman have a long tradition of commercial relations
dating back to the early
days of American independence. Others will no doubt talk to you
about our early contacts:
early American merchantmen's contacts with Zanzibar; the famous
voyage of the Sultana to
New York; our trade negotiations in the 1830s. Our current
political relationship, however,
can be traced to His Majesty Sultan Qaboos' accession to the
throne in 1970. One of His
Majesty's first priorities was to end his country's earlier
isolatction designed to increase
Oman's regional and international profile and to expand Oman's
relations with its regional
neighbors and the rest of the world.
<P>
Our relationship began to evolve in the 1970s. In 1972, the first
U.S. ambassador was
accredited to Oman. Several events promoted the growth of the
strong and cooperative
relationship between Oman and the U.S., as we both sought to
promote our mutual interests
in security, prosperity, and stability in the region. The rise of
Soviet influence in Yemen and
later in Afghanistan, the Iranian revolution, the U.S.
initiatives for peace in the Middle East,
and Oman's geographic location on the Strait of Hormuz combined
to establish the
foundation of a close relationship between our two countries.
<P>
The traditional American route to the Arab world has been
eastward across the Atlantic
Ocean, through the Gates of Hercules and along the Mediterranean
to the Levant, or Holy
Land. It was only more recently, with the emerging importance of
the Gulf to American
interests, that our strategic planners began approaching the Arab
world from the south,
around the Cape of Good Hope or coming out of the Pacific. On
this axis, the importance of
Oman becomes self-evident. Oman's strategic location, wrapped
around the southeastern
corner of the Arabian Peninsula and guarding the southern
approaches to the Strait of
Hormuz across from Iran, makes it an essential partner in
preserving freedom of navigation
in the Gulf and a key participant in regional strategic planning.
Following the fall of the Shah
and the Soviet occupation of Afghanistan, Oman was the first
country in the Gulf with which
we negotiated a security cooperation agreement. This accord,
signed in 1980, was renewed
and expanded in 1990 and remains in effect today. During the Gulf
War, Oman contributed
forces to liberating Kuwait and aircraft of the international
coalition operated from Omani
airfields. Oman continues to work closely with the U.S. in
providing crucial logistics and
prepositioning support, and in participating in joint exercises
in the region. Oman is also a
strong supporter of collective security within the Gulf
Cooperation Council.
<P>
Oman has been a member of the Gulf Cooperation Council since its
formation in 1981. It has
contributed to and benefited from GCC efforts to maintain
regional security, as well on other
issues of interest to the Gulf states. In September 1994, Oman
joined with the other five
GCC members to announce their decision to no longer enforce the
secondary and tertiary
aspects of theael. Oman will take over the chair of the GCC in
December.
<P>
At the same time, in keeping with Oman's tradition as a seafaring
nation, Sultan Qaboos has
pursued an independent foreign policy. One example has been
Oman's unhesitating support
for peace efforts in the Middle East. Resisting pressure to
isolate Egypt in the wake of its
peace treaty with Israel in 1979, Oman maintained its ties to
Cairo. In April 1994, Oman
was the first Gulf state to host an Israeli delegation to a
multilateral peace process meeting.
In December 1994, Oman welcomed Prime Minister Rabin on his first
visit to a Gulf state.
The two countries' foreign ministers have met several times. At
the beginning of October,
Oman and Israel announced an agreement to open trade
representation in each other's
country. Oman has been active in all aspects of the multilateral
peace process working
groups. Oman has taken the lead in promoting the establishment of
a regional desalination
research center in Muscat under the auspices of the Multilateral
Working Group on Water,
working with Israel and other regional states, as part of the
peace process.
<P>
Sultan Qaboos has publicly stood with the U.S. in condemning
terrorism and violence. He
has spoken out against those who would use terror or manipulate
Islam in support of violent
opposition to the peace process or stable governments. Following
an unsuccessful attempt in
1994 to destabilize the Sultan's government, by plotters
allegedly under the influence of
Islamist extremists, His Majesty Sultan Qaboos publicly condemned
extremism.
<P>
As a member of the United Nations Security Council since January
1994, Oman has worked
closely and successfully with the U.S. on a variety of issues.
These have included containing
the effects of the Yemeni civil war and maintaining the Iraq
sanctions regime until Iraq
complies with all its obligations to the Security Council. We
both share a deep concern for
the humanitarian hardship of the Iraqi people. Our two countries
worked closely together to
draft UNSCR 986, which allows for the provision of humanitarian
aid to the Iraqi people
through the controlled sale of Iraqi oil, while maintaining the
integrity of the sanctions
regime. In its two years on the Security Council, Oman has been a
serious, responsible and
contributing member of that important body.
<P>
The politics of economics also is an important factor in our
relationship with Oman. On a
bilateral level, our commercial relationship dates back over two
centuries. In 1908, we were
Oman's second largest export market. Then California began
producing dates and trade
tapered off. Today we are coming back. The U.S. is Oman's fourth
largest trading partner.
U.S. companies are working in Oman across various sectors from
oil and natural gas to
manufacturing. We will work with Oman to share knowledge and
experience and to provide
training and opportunities for younr economic opportunities and
cooperation. We recognize
and support Oman's own economic priorities aimed at diversifying
its economy and
developing the interior of the country.
<P>
On a multilateral level, the upcoming Amman Summit at the end of
October will enhance
economic cooperation in the region. Following on last year's
Casablanca Summit, the
Amman Summit represents an opportunity to expand business and
trade among all the
countries in the region and to take advantage of new
opportunities opened by the peace
agreements. We have encouraged Oman to take advantage of the
summit as an opportunity to
promote Omani projects. We understand that an important
delegation representing both the
government and the private sector will attend.
<P>
Domestically, Sultan Qaboos has taken important political and
social steps to ensure Oman's
place as a stable, modern country. He has been a leader on the
Arabian Peninsula in
promoting the education and political empowerment of women and in
articulating a vision of
gradually expanding popular participation in government. In 1991
the Sultan established a
59-seat Consultative Council, or Majlis Ash-Shura, which replaced
an older advisory body.
Council members are selected from lists of nominees proposed by
each of the nation's
regions, become educated and immersed in issues affecting the
nation, question government
ministers and recommend changes to new laws on economic and
social policy. In 1994 Oman
became the first Gulf Cooperative Council state to welcome women
to serve in its
Consultative Council, and there are now two new women members.
Oman is working to
improve worker rights. Oman joined the International Labor
Organization in 1994, and the
Government is drafting a new labor law that addresses worker
rights.
<P>
The future of the U.S.-Oman relationship will continue to be
based on mutual respect and
our common concern for regional security and stability. Last
week, we spend a full morning
with Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Yusef bin Alawi
reviewing conditions in the region
and our bilateral relations, which are sold and healthy. We will
continue to cooperate on
economic, political and security issues and to seek new and
creative ways to enhance our
broad bilateral relationship. We will also work together on
multilateral issues, including the
peace process, Iraq sanctions, and expanded economic
opportunities in the region. Sultan
Qaboos has played an important role in the development of our
strong, cooperative
relationship through his commitment to pursuing an active role in
international policy for
Oman. We appreciate the importance of this relationship and of
His Majesty's interest and
guidance. We look forward to another twenty-five years of His
Majesty's leadership.
<P>
<HR>
<center>This Web site was produced and is maintained by the
United States Information Agency.<P><A HREF="gulfmain.htm">
