</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>USIA: U.S. Policy in the Gulf -- Deputy
Secretary of Defense John P. White Press Conference in Abu
Dhabi</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff><IMG SRC="usis2.jpg">
<CENTER><B><H2>Deputy Secretary of Defense John P. White<BR>
Press Conference in Abu Dhabi<BR>
March 29, 1996</H2></B><P>
<IMG SRC="footer.gif"></CENTER> 
<P> 
 (Stresses U.S. commitment to Gulf security, stability) (2450)

Abu Dhabi -- "The United States has a long enduring, interesting
commitment to security and stability in the Gulf.  We have a
commitment to work closely with our friends in this region for
those ends ...," says a Defense Department official.
<P>
During a March 28 press conference at the conclusion of his visit
to the United Arab Emirates, John P. White, Deputy Secretary of
Defense, said the United States counts the UAE "as one of our
best
friends in the region." He said he had a "very productive set of
discussions on a range of topics" of mutual interest.
<P>
In response to questions from the press, White said the U.S. is
concerned about instability in the Gulf but most of the concern
is
about terrorism. Terrorism of the sort that has occurred in
Bahrain
and Saudi Arabia, he said,  "clearly leads to instability. 
Therefore we are continuing to talk here and elsewhere with our
friends about ways that we can reduce terrorism."
<P>
"We are particularly concerned about Iran with respect to
terrorism
and the fact that they've exported terrorism around the world,"
he
stated.  "We continue to be very clear here and elsewhere about
how
reprehensible all that is, and that their terrorist activities
ought to be terminated."
<P>
Regarding the sanctions against Iraq, White stressed that "the
problem here is the Iraqi leadership.  It's Saddam Hussein, it's
not the question of the sanctions."  The U.S. is concerned about
the plight of the Iraqi people, he said, but the problem that has
to be resolved is "the brutality of the leadership."
<P>
Following is a transcript of the press conference: (Begin
transcript) AMBASSADOR LITT:  Ladies and Gentlemen, as the
American
Ambassador to the United Arab Emirates, I am proud to present to
you the Deputy Secretary of Defense Dr. John White.
<P>
DR. WHITE:  Thank you Mr. Ambassador.  I will begin if I may with
a couple of brief comments.  My colleagues and I have just
concluded a really excellent, although too short a visit to the
UAE.  I came as an emissary from President Clinton and delivered
a
letter to His Highness President Sheikh Zayed.  We had excellent
meetings with the Crown Prince, and with the Chief of Staff,
Sheikh
Mohamed.  As you know we have a long and enduring interesting
commitment to stability and security in the Gulf.  We have a
commitment to work closely with our friends in this region for
those ends and of course we count the UAE as one of our best
friends in the region.  And we were able to have some very
friendly
common discussions about areas of interest to both countries.  So
I am pleased to say that I will be able to return to the United
States with a word to the President and to Secretary Perry that
we
have had a very productive set of discussions on a range of
topics. 
Thank you.  I'd be happy to answer any questions.
<P>
Q:  We hear that there is an increase in the deployment of troops
in the area.
<P>
A:  I wouldn't be in a position today to discuss any details of
any
deployments in the area.  We do not, as a rule, ever discuss
future
deployments.  We did discuss the exercise Iron Falcon which will
be
coming up soon, which will be a joint exercise with the UAE and
the
U.S.  In fact we had a very informative airplane tour this
morning
in the general region where that's going to be and it's a great
interest to both of us.  So we're looking forward to that, and
that
will happen shortly.
<P>
Q:  Regarding the security arrangements in the area, have you
discussed with the UAE officials here the case of the  Emirates'
Islands occupied by Iran?
<P>
A:  Of course.  As I think you know, we have been concerned about
those islands, we continue to be concerned.  We did discuss the
general issue of security in the region, and particularly with
respect to Iran.
<P>
Q:  There's been a lot of talk about threats from Iran and Iraq. 
Do you think that there is a new kind of threat in the Gulf from
internal instability, home-grown instability in Bahrain, the bomb
explosion in Saudi Arabia!  Are you concerned about this?
<P>
A:  We're concerned about instability but most of our concern in
that regard has to do with terrorism.  As you know we are
strongly
opposed to terrorism in the region and the world at large and we
think any terrorism of the sort that's been experienced clearly
leads to instability.  Therefore we are continuing to talk here
and
elsewhere with our friends about ways that we can reduce
terrorism. 
That was the point of the President's visit to the region
recently
and I think he clearly underlined that commitment.
<P>
Q:  The United States has big deals with United Arab Emirates and
other Gulf countries and they also signed many deals through
offset
programs.  Can you tell us about steps made by the American side
and the Emirates during the past three years?
<P>
A:  I can't recount Mr. Ambassador all the details.  Can you?
AMBASSADOR LITT:  You're speaking specifically in terms of
military
and defense.  Over the last three years, of course we have had an
ongoing program with the United Arab Emirates in terms of Apache
helicopters and Hawk Missile program.  And we are engaged with
them
and have been for quite a long time to see if there are other
defense systems that they would like to acquire from the United
States.  Over the last three years I don't know off hand of any
major systems that they have purchased.
<P>
Q:  -- talked with Sheikh Mohamed Bin Zayed about defense. 
Jurisdiction of American personnel (inaudible).
<P>
A:  We as you know have a cooperative defense agreement that's
very
important.  It's been in place since 1994.  It provides a
framework
for a whole range of inter-relationships and we obviously talked
about the agreement and the inter-relationships but beyond that
we
didn't get into any specifics.
<P>
Q:  (inaudible) A:  We have a relationship, both sides think the
relationship continues to work well.  It's an evolving
relationship
between friends, and it will evolve over time.
<P>
Q:  The UAE defense minister has voiced concern about the
sanctions
against Iraq and the UAE has sent relief aid to the Iraqis.  Did
you discuss the sanctions and the need to maintain the sanctions?
<P>
A:  Yes we did.  We did discuss Iraq and we did discuss the
sanctions.  From our point of view, we also are concerned about
the
plight of the Iraqi people.  But I think we have a common
understanding that the problem here is the Iraqi leadership. 
It's
Saddam Hussein, it's not the question of the sanctions.  The
sanctions are a result of the brutality of the leadership and if
we
can solve that that's the problem that has to be solved not the
issue of sanctions so we are supportive of the concerns that were
expressed during our visit with respect to the Iraqi people.
<P>
Q:  Did the UAE reiterate its position on sanctions, that there
should be some kind of reconciliation with Iraq during the talks?
<P>
A:  Well, I am not going to go into the details of the talks. 
Let
me just say that we talked about sanctions, we talked about a
whole
set of security issues in the region, and it was a very mutually
satisfactory conversation.
<P>
Q:  How do you look at Iran as a military threat? A:  Well, we
think that Iran is a military threat.  We watch them closely in
terms of their military activities.  But as I said earlier we are
particularly concerned about Iran with respect to terrorism and
the
fact that they've exported terrorism around the world.  We've
been
very clear about that over time and we continue to be very clear
here and elsewhere about how reprehensible all that is, and that
their terrorist activities ought to be terminated.
<P>
Q:  Let's take the economic sanctions ... have the economic
sanctions against Iran been effective?  Or do you think that
other
measures are needed?  I mean, when you say you're going to fight
terrorism, how are you going to do it?
<P>
A:  I'm not going to go into speculation about hypothetical
situations, or what we might do in the future.  We think that
we've
been realistically and generally supportive and positive, but
nevertheless, we are continually concerned about terrorism.
<P>
Q:  Dr. White, you believe that Iran is a very important player
in
the Gulf as far as security and peace are concerned.  Why has not
the United States tried to bring Iran into the fold instead of a
constant policy of confrontation with it?
<P>
A:  We would be happy to see a better relationship with Iran if
they would terminate the practices that we object to.  But as
long
as they conduct themselves as they have been, we are not in a
situation where we can accommodate them.  There's an easy
solution
to that.
<P>
Q:  What do you mean by that? A:  Well I mentioned terrorism in
particular, which is something that is of particular concern to
us.
<P>
Q:  Why did the United States not ask the Israeli Government to
remove the economic sanctions against the Palestinians, and at
the
same time, the United States increased its support for Israel
(inaudible) and finally it is altogether against the peace
process
and the Middle East at the same time.
<P>
A:  Well let me just say in general first of all, that my focus
here obviously has been on this specific region.  Secondly, that
we
continue to support the peace process, and support it in the
broad
sense as we have over time now.  Thirdly that we are acting based
on the President' recent visit to provide a series of support,
conditional support, to that peace process, and we're  hoping
that
we can continue to have some progress on that regard.
<P>
Q:  (inaudible) relationship with Iran.  Is the U.S. prepared to
sit with Iran without any condition and discuss the relationship?
<P>
A:  Well, I think I would only be repeating what I said before. 
We
have a basic concern with respect to the way the Iranian regime
conducts itself, and as long as that's the case, we are going to
have a problem.  We would like to see that changed.  If that
changed then, obviously, that would open up other issues.
<P>
Q:  Are you aware of some talk about (inaudible) A:  The AEF? Q: 
Yes. A:  Yes.  That's been announced here.  We do have an air
expeditionary force which we have deployed in the region before,
and which we do anticipate deploying again, and we anticipate
that
in the future to be in Jordan.  The King was in the United States
a couple of weeks ago.   We talked with him about that.  He's
supportive of that.  The King, as you know, is a friend of ours,
and so we do anticipate having that happen, and I think next
month,
or the month after April.
<P>
Q:  We got some idea regarding Idex 97 in Abu Dhabi.  We heard
that
a lot of American companies will participate.  Did you discuss
that
with Sheikh Mohamed?
<P>
A:  No.  We did not. Q:  Going now to the Syrian track, one of
the
issues has to do with the surveillance forces ... (inaudible). 
What sort of solution do you see that would be satisfactory to
both
sides, and what military role ... that the U.S. could play?
<P>
A:  Again I don't think it is for me to get into these kinds of
details here.  That's not why I'm here.
<P>
Q:  Are you prepared to militarily come to the aid of the UAE if
Iran boosts its activities on islands?
<P>
A:  Again, I wouldn't speculate about hypothetical situations. 
These people are friends here.  We've had a good visit.  We
continue to work very closely together.
<P>
Q:  You have a defense agreement with the UAE.  Does the
agreement
provide for military protection in case Iran attacks the UAE?
<P>
AMBASSADOR LITT:  I wouldn't go into details about our defense
cooperation agreement.
<P>
Q:  There is (inaudible) between the United States, the United
Kingdom, and France.  (inaudible) armaments marketing.  Did you
discuss with the United Arab Emirates officials, or are you going
to discuss in Kuwait, aircraft sales?
<P>
A:  We did discuss here with Sheikh Mohamed, issues around
aircraft
sales, fighter aircraft sales, but that is a discussion we have
been having for quite some time.  We have offered, in the spirit
of
the cooperation that we have, and in the context of the DCA, to
make those sales.  We think we clearly make the best fighter
aircraft in the world.  We would like to see a situation in which
the UAE would acquire some of our aircraft.  That would improve
our
cooperation with the UAE.  It would enhance training, enhance
(inaudible) and therefore we did discuss that, and we had a very
useful conversation.
<P>
Q:  it seems there is a special relationship between Qatar and
Iran.  How do you view that relationship?
<P>
A:  I can't comment on that, I'm sorry. Q:  Dr. White, you'd have
thought that once Iraq started actively to support terrorist
activity, that it would be better to ...
<P>
A:  I didn't affirm that.  What I simply said was, that as long
as
we have the situation that we have, we have a problem with the
regime in Iran.
<P>
Q:  What is the situation now in Taiwan, now after the Chinese
(inaudible) A:  Again I'm not going to go into the Chinese
situation.  That's a very complicated situation.  As you know, we
have been talking actively with the Chinese with respect to that
situation over the recent period.  We took certain actions that
we
thought were important at that time.  We now see those exercises
winding down, and we think that's good.  We would hope that they
reduce the exercises and that everything gets back to normal.
<P>
Q:  The recent defections from Iraq raised apparently false hopes
or false perceptions that Saddam was losing a grip on power.  How
long do you think these sanctions are going to affect his grip on
power, any time soon, or do you think he's in as strong a
position
as ever?
<P>
A:  We think the sanctions have been very effective, and as long
as Saddam continues to conduct himself the way he has, and to be
there, we will be in favor of these sanctions, and as I say, I
think the evidence is clear that they've been successful.  Thank
you very much.
<P>
<HR>
