<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>USIA: U.S. Policy in the Gulf -- Remarks by
Assistant Secretary Pelletreau to Center for Arab Studies Seminar
December 12, 1996</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff><IMG SRC="usis2.jpg"><CENTER>
<B><H2>Remarks by Assistant Secretary Pelletreau<br>
at the Center for Arab Studies Seminar<br>
Commemorating the 25th Anniversary of the UAE<br>
December 12, 1996</H2></B><P>
<IMG SRC="footer.gif"></CENTER> 
<p>
Thank you, Dr. Hudson.  Ambassador Shaali, my U.S. ambassadorial
colleagues, I am delighted to join with you today in
commemorating the United Arab Emirates' first 25 years of
independence.  As some of you will recall,  there were voices in
1971 who doubted the federation would survive infancy, let alone
be standing proudly among the community of nations to celebrate
its Silver Jubilee.  Today, we can say that nation-building in
the UAE has been a resounding success.  Despite surrounding
turmoil in the form of the Iraq-Iran war of the 1980s, and then
the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait and its subsequent liberation by an
international coalition of nations, the UAE steadily knit
together the sinews of nationhood and is today practicing a
vigorous prosperity.  In a world too often governed by petty
jealousies, this remarkable accomplishment is a tribute to the
far-sighted leadership of His Highness Shaykh Zayid, to the
commitment of his fellow rulers, and to the abilities of the
people of the UAE.  
<P>
In guiding the federation's development, Shaykh Zayid showed his
commitment to unity by generously sharing the wealth of Abu Dhabi
with less well-endowed northern emirates, and by funding the
federal government while respecting the right of each emirate to
run its own internal affairs.
<P>
No figure in the Arab world is more universally respected than
Shaykh Zayid.  He has remained true to his traditional values
while presiding over the rapid modernization of his country.  And
what extraordinary changes he has brought his people in their 25
years of independence!  Life expectancy has increased by more
than ten years.  The population has quadrupled, as has the
overall literacy rate.  Petroleum exports now account for only
one-third of GDP.  In downtown Abu Dhabi, you can stroll through
lush park land and watch a wild falcon hunting for its next meal,
while across the street stands a gleaming high-rise office tower
with a fast-food restaurant on the ground floor.  On his
instructions, local institutions pioneered in developing
hydroponic agriculture and other modern techniques to lessen
reliance on food imports.
<P>
When I had the pleasure of revisiting the UAE in October, I was
delighted to see how much new development had taken place since
my previous visit, and how much additional construction is taking
place.  Dubai has become the hub of commerce and shipping for the
entire region.  The late Shaykh Rashid Al Maktoum and his sons
have shown remarkable vision by investing ambitiously in
infrastructure and opening their emirate to international
business.  The impressive port facility at Jebel Ali is not only
the only one in the region large enough to host U.S. aircraft
carriers, but its booming free port area now includes offices or
warehouses of some sixty-five American companies which use it as
a hub for their business activities up and down the Gulf.  The
vision of Shaikh Rashid, may he rest in peace, on that day over
twenty years ago when he went out with his advisors and put his
walking stick firmly into the desert sand and said "here," has
been confirmed a hundred times over.
<P>
More and more, the United States and the UAE are discovering the
benefits of doing business together. Our bilateral trade has
grown by some 37% in the past two years alone. This year, it is
projected to exceed $2.3 billion.  I believe this trend will
continue.  American business has a great deal to contribute to
the continued development of the UAE.  And thanks to the silver
anniversary celebrations, many more Americans are hearing about
the UAE's remarkable transformation.  Our embassy estimates there
are now 14,000 Americans in the UAE, and projects that the number
will continue to grow by 10-20% each year.  
<P>
While the United States has enjoyed good relations with the UAE
since it was founded, we have grown closer in this decade, when
we stood together to defend the independence of Kuwait.   
<P>
Iraq's invasion, and the support Baghdad received in some
quarters, constituted a wake-up call for all the GCC states.  The
dangers of relying on Iraqi strength to balance Iranian threats
was brought home.  Their very prosperity and success made them
targets of aggression, and they found out who were the friends
they could count on and who were not.  The United States'
response to that aggression demonstrated more clearly than words
how genuinely we are committed to the security of the Gulf.  We
showed that we can and will defend our friends as well as our
interests -- preferably by deterring potential threats, but with
overwhelming military force, if necessary.  Perhaps more
importantly, we showed that American power could serve the cause
of stability in the region.  And we showed we could do so in a
way that did not impinge on the sovereignty of our friends or
their values.  When the hundreds of thousands of troops we had
massed in the region had accomplished their mission, they came
home, ready to return in case of need.
<P>
Although we seek no bases or permanent presence on the sovereign
territory of our friends, let there be no mistake:  the security
and stability of the Gulf remains a vital national interest of
the United States.  
<P>
Our economy, indeed that of the entire modernizing world, depends
on the unimpeded flow of oil and gas from the Gulf, which has 65%
of the world's proven reserves of oil.  The UAE alone accounts
for nearly 10% of world oil reserves and 4% of gas reserves, and
its reserves will last well over a hundred years at current rates
of production.  
<P>
The Gulf War stimulated the UAE's interest in building a security
relationship with the United States.  We cooperate in many ways
already, and I am confident our partnership will grow in the
months and years ahead.  Our two countries concluded a Defense
Cooperation Agreement in 1994.  Today, U.S. Air Force aerial
refueling tankers fly out of al-Dhafra air base in support of
Operation Southern Watch, the "no-fly" zone in southern Iraq. 
Our Navy calls regularly at ports of the Emirates, both for
necessary maintenance and for R and R for our sailors and Marines
on duty in the Gulf region, and our forces exercise together
regularly, often with those of other GCC states. 
<P>
As we seek to build a lasting security relationship, our two
governments are consulting closely to devise mutually acceptable
arrangements to complete implementation of the 1994 agreement. 
We also welcome the establishment two years ago of the Emirates
Center for Strategic Studies and Research and appreciate the work
of the Center under its energetic and capable director, Dr. Jamal
al-Suweidi.
<P>
Clearly, the UAE is a valued partner for us in this strategic
region.  Among other things, it has a crucial role to play in
enforcing United Nations sanctions against the Iraqi regime.  As
Security Council Resolution 986 is implemented, sanctions
enforcement will become even more important.  The sheer volume of
shipping in the Gulf will make the Multinational Interdiction
Force's job even more difficult than it already is.  And Baghdad
is falsely portraying 986 as the beginning of the end of
sanctions.  Nothing could be further from the truth.  The
"oil-for-food" formula was always part of the framework of
Security Council resolutions because the Security Council did not
want the Iraqi people to suffer undue hardship for the sins of
its government.  Until this year, however, Baghdad refused to
accept this resolution even though its own people would be the
beneficiaries.  There should be no doubt in anyone's mind that
the sanctions must and will remain in effect until Iraq has
complied fully with all the Security Council resolutions.  
<P>
When I visited the UAE in October, I stressed the importance of
cracking down on sanctions-busters, some of whom unfortunately
operate out of the UAE, principally Dubai and the northern
Emirates.  I want to note here that the UAE has cooperated in the
handling of these violators.  It has readily accepted vessels
diverted for sanctions violations, and this summer the UAE
government warned its shipping community that it would deflag
vessels that are caught violating sanctions repeatedly.
<P>
Moving eastward in the Gulf, the United States and the UAE share
concerns about Iran's policies and behavior in the region: its
support for terrorism; its drive to acquire weapons of mass
destruction; its efforts to destabilize other governments; its
hegemonic behavior in the Gulf; and its opposition to the peace
process.  The United States supports the UAE's call for peaceful
resolution of its dispute with Iran over the islands of Abu Musa
and Greater and Lesser Tunb.
<P>
The United States has no more important goal in the Middle East
than to secure a just, lasting and comprehensive peace between
Israel and all its neighbors.  The UAE shares the realization
that peace is in the interest of all peoples of the region.  Just
the other day, Ambassador Shaali remarked to me that the success
of the peace process is vital to his country's future security
and development.  We appreciate that the UAE has demonstrated its
support for the peace process by its participation in the
multilateral track of the process.  We were gratified that
Foreign Minister Rashid Abdullah personally headed his country's
delegation to the recent Middle East North Africa Economic
Conference in Cairo.  We also encourage the UAE to continue
contributing generously to the development needs of the
Palestinian people.  
<P>
The UAE has played a constructive role in international affairs
beyond the Middle East.  It contributed troops to the UN peace
keeping mission in Somalia.  Right now, it is a key participant
with us and other donors in the program to strengthen the Bosnian
Federation militarily, so that it will be able to deter future
attack--or defend itself if deterrence fails.
<P>
Let me close by stressing again how much my government values its
growing ties with the UAE.  Emiris are getting to know the United
States better too, as many attend university here or come on
business or tourism.  The growing interaction between Americans
and Emiris is good for both sides.  I look forward to the day
when U.S. airlines stop regularly in the Emirates and when
Emirates Airline also flies to the States.  Incidentally, it's a
wonderful airline.  I took it recently and had a great flight.  I
also stopped in the Dubai free shops -- bought this necktie in
fact.  Now you may not agree with my taste in ties (I have that
problem in the family, too), but there can be no disagreement
that a visit to the Dubai free shop is a memorable experience.  I
believe that increasing day-to-day contact between our peoples is
one of the most effective ways to foster mutual understanding and
awareness of each other's concerns, and can lead us to appreciate
how much we share common values and interests.  Arabs and Muslims
are all too often misunderstood in this country, just as
Americans sometimes are misunderstood in the Middle East.
<P>
We extend our warmest congratulations to all citizens of the
United Arab Emirates on this important anniversary.  Given all
that the UAE has accomplished during this first quarter century,
the people of the Emirates can look forward to the future with
confidence.  And Americans and Emiris can look forward to the
continuing expansion of productive relations between our
governments and peoples in greater understanding, closer
communication, and mutual respect.
<P>
<HR>
