<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>USIA: U.S. Policy in the Gulf -- Ambassador
Theros' nomination statement before the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff><IMG SRC="usis2.jpg">
<CENTER><B><H2>Ambassador Theros' nomination statement<br>
before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee<br>
June 20, 1995</H2></B><P>
<IMG SRC="footer.gif"></CENTER> 
<P>
Mr. Chairman and members of the Committee, it is an honor and
privilege to appear before you today as you consider my
nomination
to be the Ambassador of the United States to the State of Qatar. 
I am very grateful to the President and Secretary of State for
the
confidence and trust they have shown in me by this nomination.
<P>
Mr. Chairman, although America's formal relations with the State
of
Qatar date less than three decades, they are characterized by a
depth of mutual support and understanding that could be the envy
of
many countries whose intercourse with us is centuries older. 
Qatar's soldiers, sailors and airmen, though few in number,
distinguished themselves as fighting allies during Desert Storm. 
A Qatari battalion halted and held the Iraqi thrust at Khafji,
permitting American air power to destroy the attackers.  Qatar
has
been at the forefront of states in the region offering military
cooperation, support in kind and facilities to US forces in
defense
of our mutual interests.  American companies have been welcomed
to
participate prominently and profitably in the development of
Qatar's enormous gas reserves.  Finally, Qatar has been out in
front in working to integrate Israel economically and politically
with the Arab World; "warm peace" has real meaning in Doha.
<P>
I believe the information provided to the Committee documents my
thirty-two years of experience in the Foreign Service.  I will
not
elaborate on them in this statement but would be happy to answer
any questions that you might have.
<P>
I will state for the record, however, that I view my nomination
as
an opportunity to advance the strategic and economic interests of
the United States, and of its citizens, through deepening the
relationship with a small, but brave and valuable partner.  If
confirmed, I plan to work closely with this committee, with the
Congress as a whole and with American business.
<HR>
