<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>USIA: U.S. Policy in the Gulf -- 50 Years of
U.S.- Saudi Friendship Commemorated in Washington</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff><IMG SRC="usis2.jpg">
<CENTER><B><H2>50 Years of U.S.- Saudi Friendship<BR>
Commemorated in Washington<br>
February 16, 1995</H2></B><P>

<IMG SRC="footer.gif">
<p>
by Joanne L. Nix<BR>
USIA Staff Writer</CENTER> 
<P>
Washington -- This week in Washington, ceremonies were held to
commemorate a brief but remarkable chapter of naval history --
the meeting in 1945 of President Franklin Delano Roosevelt of the
United States and King Abdul Aziz (Ibn Saud), the founder of
modern-day Saudi Arabia.  What began as a warm, personal
friendship fifty years ago is now a strong, mutually advantageous
partnership between two great countries.
<P>
On February 15, U.S. sailors who served during World War II
aboard
the U.S. destroyers the USS Murphy, the ship that carried King
Ibn
Saud to the top-secret meeting, and crew members of the USS
Quincy,
the ship where the meeting with Roosevelt took place, traveled
with
their families from cities and towns throughout the U.S. to
Washington.  They were the special guests of the United States
Navy
and the Embassy of Saudi Arabia at an event commemorating the
formal beginning of strategic, economic and cultural relations
between the United States and Saudi Arabia.
<P>
The crewmen were honored at a Navy Memorial Foundation-sponsored
ceremony and reception attended by high-ranking diplomatic
representatives of Saudi Arabia, including Saleh Al-Rajhy,
Counselor of the Royal Embassy, Captain Mogbel Al-Mogbel, Naval
Attache of the Saudi Embassy and Dr. Mohsin Helal.
<P>
The hour-long ceremony was opened by the President's Own, the
U.S.
Marine Corps band, which played the Saudi and American national
anthems. Dignitaries and special guests arrived and were escorted
down to the first two rows of the Arleigh and Roberta Burke
Theater.
<P>
February 15 marked the actual day the two leaders met 50 years
ago. 
Among the U.S. officials present at the commemoration were the
widow and two sons of the late Captain John S. Keating, who
commanded the Murphy's destroyer squadron and Secretary of the
Navy
John Dalton who described the bond that was formed when "the men
of
the desert met the men of the sea as friends and allies."
<P>
"This ceremony," said the Secretary, "is both a reunion and a
remembrance. It is a reunion for the officers and sailors of the
USS Murphy and USS Quincy ... shipmates who served their nation
in
a time of grave peril.  It is a remembrance of their deeds.  But
it
is also a ... celebration ... of the relationship of two nations
who have been allies in war, and friends in peace:  the United
States and the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia."
<P>
"The Great Bitter Lake Summit," so named because King Ibn Saud
and
President Roosevelt held their secret meeting in the Great Bitter
Lake that forms part of the Suez Canal, was not the first time
the
United States and the Kingdom of  Saudi Arabia pledged mutual
cooperation.
<P>
Secretary Dalton explained that in 1933, America and Saudi Arabia
signed a treaty of friendship, commerce and navigation.  In
February of 1943, President Roosevelt -- who had once served as
Assistant Secretary of the Navy -- "declared that the defense of
Saudi Arabia was a vital interest of the United States."  Later,
during World War II, the United States and the Kingdom of Saudi
Arabia became allies against the Axis powers.
<P>
Dalton emphasized that the ties that were forged during that
summit
are still strong.  "In 1991," he said, "the Armed Forces of Saudi
Arabia met again with the United States Navy and United States
Marine Corps ... and all the American Armed Forces ... to help
liberate (Kuwait)."
<P>
Saleh Al-Rajhy, Counselor of the Saudi Embassy, acting on behalf
of
the Saudi Ambassador to the United States, Prince Bandar bin
Sultan
bin Abdulaziz, accepted a framed photograph of the historic
meeting.  The 1945 Summit, he said, "was a landmark in the
history
of our friendship and set the stage for cordial relationships ..
(between) our two countries."
<P>
"In Saudi Arabia, even today," the Counselor said, "pictures of
President 1oosevelt hang in our offices and homes.... (Although)
times have changed, our feelings of friendship and gratitude have
only grown stronger."
<P>
Following the remarks by officials, the crewmen of the two
vessels
were presented with certificates of appreciation from the Saudi
Arabian Embassy and the Navy Memorial Foundation.
<P>
As part of the ceremony, original film footage of the voyage of
the
Murphy and the meeting aboard the Quincy was shown to the guests.

Included in the film was an interview with Commander Bernard
Smith,
Captain of the USS Murphy.
<P>
In the film, Smith described the meeting between two very
different
groups of people -- the Saudi contingent and American sailors,
who
developed mutual  understanding and admiration while taking part
in
the history-making journey.
<P>
The voyage marked the first time the Saudi king had left his
homeland.  His staff was anxious that the 63-year-old ruler would
be comfortable aboard the American warship so they brought aboard
the trappings of his own country.
<P>
According to Smith, the King had at the departure point in Jidda
100 live sheep to be loaded on the destroyer Murphy to feed not
only his party, but the ship's crew and President Roosevelt as
well.
<P>
The commander of the Murphy was shocked at the prospect of
loading
live animals aboard his ship so a compromise was finally reached
and only seven sheep were loaded on board.
<P>
Once on board, the King spurned the offer of the Captain's cabin
and slept under a specially constructed tent on deck.  According
to
other historical sources, Ibn Saud's servants lit fires for
coffee
despite live ammunition racks and guns nearby.  Both Saudi and
ship
staff shared cooking duties in the galley in relative harmony.
<P>
Five times each day, the navigator provided the Saudis with a
compass heading pointing toward Mecca so that the King and his
party could say their customary prayers.
<P>
Ambassador Bandar, Ibn Saud's grandson, recalled the historic
meeting in a 50th anniversary article written for "Middle East
Insight" magazine.  The prince revealed that King Ibn Saud posed
only two questions about Roosevelt and his country:  Do Americans
believe in God, and do they have colonies? Assured that the
Americans believed in God and had no colonies, the king embarked
on
the relationship that even today represents the heart of Saudi
Arabia's diplomatic and security policy.
<P>
According to Prince Bandar, at no time did Ibn Saud even hint at
financial aid for Saudi Arabia.  He traveled to the meeting
seeking
friends and not funds in spite of the fact that at that time, his
land was cut off by war from foreign import markets.
<P>
Although President Roosevelt died less than two months after the
historic meeting, he lived long enough to make in person one
address to Congress in the course of which he said, "I learned
more
(about the Near East) by talking with Ibn Saud for five minutes
than I could have learned in exchange of two or three dozen
letters."
<P>
Ever since that day fifty years ago, every American president has
attested to Saudi Arabia's vital importance to the United States.

On the occasion of the Murphy/Quincy commemoration, President
Clinton wrote: "It gives me great pleasure to reflect on the warm
personal relationship that King Fahd and I have developed, which
mirrors the Saudi Arabia over the past half-century.  I believe
King Abdul Aziz and President Roosevelt would be very pleased
with
the results of their meeting fifty years ago.  And I am 1onfident
that the foundations they laid will continue to ensure a vibrant
U.S.-Saudi partnership for many decades to come."
<P>
<HR>
<center>This Web site was produced and is maintained by the
United States Information Agency.<P><A HREF="gulfmain.htm">
Return</A> to the Gulf Security Homepage <IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE
SRC="usisflag.gif"> <A HREF="http://www.usia.gov/usis.html">
Return</A> to the USIS homepage 
</CENTER></body></html>
</DOC>
