<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>USIA: U.S. Policy in the Gulf -- Joint Chief
of
Staff Shalikashvili Press Conference in Kuwait,
5/27</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff><IMG SRC="usis2.jpg">
<CENTER><B><H2>Joint Chief of Staff Shalikashvili<br>
Press Conference in Kuwait<br>
May 27, 1996</H2></B><P>
<IMG SRC="footer.gif"></CENTER> 
<P>
TRANSCRIPT:(General expresses U.S. solidarity with Kuwait) (910)
<P>
Kuwait City -- The relationship between the United States and
Kuwait "is on very solid footing and ... we will continue working
together every bit as well as we have done in the past," General
John M. Shalikashvili, Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
said
May 27.
<p>
At a press conference at Kuwait Airport following his earlier
meeting with Kuwaiti defense officials, Shalikashvili said that
in
addition to discussions about the bilateral defense relationship,
they also commented on United Nations Security Council Resolution
986, the Iraq oil-for-food agreement.
<p>
Shalikashvili said the U.S. is "absolutely committed to ensure
that
986 is not used to circumvent the intent of it, which is to
provide
humanitarian assistance to the people of Iraq who have suffered
so
much under Saddam Hussein."  He also emphasized that the
sanctions
regime will remain in place until Iraq complies with the relevant
UNSC resolutions that deal with sanctions.
<p>
Following is the official transcript of the press conference, as
provided by USIS Kuwait:
<p>
(Begin transcript)
<p>
General:  Thank you very much for coming and I appreciate the
opportunity in this public way to thank General Ali for his
gracious invitation to come here to share an opportunity to
discuss
the United States' commitment to the peace and stability of this
region and to express our solidarity with Kuwait.  It also gave
me
the opportunity to visit some of our men and women who are
serving
here and to see how very, very well they are hosted by their
Kuwaiti counterparts.  So, I leave here very much assured that
our
relationship is on very solid footing and that we will continue
working together every bit as well as we have done in the past. 
With that, ladies and gentlemen, I am prepared to answer any of
your questions.
<p>
Q:  What issues did you address in your meetings?
<p>
General:  We discussed principally the relationship between us,
if
there were any issues that we needed to work on.  I am very happy
to report to you that everything is working well.  We did comment
in our discussions on such issues as United Nations Security
Council Resolution 986, and our firm commitment that 986 in no
way
lessens the requirements on the part of Iraq to fulfill all
relevant United Nations Security Council resolutions, and
certainly
that resolution dealing with Kuwaiti POWs and those missing.
Those
kinds of resolutions must be fully complied with.
<p>
Q:  Did you discuss the resolution results which involved the
imports into Iraq from the rest of the world dealing with food
and
humanitarian aid? Are you going to monitor the shipments going to
Um Qasr and are you going to use any Kuwaiti ports?
<p>
General:  I don't think I am the one to talk about the specifics
of
the monitoring regime that is being set up, other than to tell
you
that we are absolutely committed to ensure that 986 is not used
to
circumvent the intent of it, which is to provide humanitarian
assistance to the people of Iraq who have suffered so much under
Saddam Hussein.  We will make sure that none of that money from
the
sale of oil is diverted to such things as improving his military
capability.
<p>
Q:  Don't you think the implementation of this resolution will
give
Iraq the opportunity to forestall implementing the other U.N.
resolutions?
<p>
General:  I think it is up to the community of nations to be sure
that that does not happen.  It's absolutely important that
everyone
understands our continued commitment to hold Saddam Hussein
accountable for the full compliance of all relevant United
Nations
Security Council resolutions.
<p>
Q:  Would you like to comment about the Iran exercise?
<p>
General:  I think it is too early to tell about the specifics of
the exercises that just finished the other day.  I must tell you
that I, for one, as the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
watch very carefully what is happening in Iran and certainly that
we are committed to ensure that no one in this region threatens
or
intimidates any of our friends or our allies.
<p>
Q:  Will the role of the U.S. Navy change in the Gulf?
<p>
General:  I think that to talk about specifics it's a little too
early.  But remember that the operation that's being run in the
Gulf is one essentially of ensuring that the sanctions regime is
complied with, the sanction regime remains in place and so the
task
of ensuring that Iraq abides by the relevant sanctions is still a
requirement, that we will ensure that we do our part to insist
that
it is complied with.
<p>
Q:  (Inaudible)
<p>
General:  It's too early to tell, but the function will not
change,
that is the compliance on the part of Iraq with the relevant
United
Nations Security Council resolutions that deal with sanctions.
<p>
Q:  Did you discuss any increase in the American presence in
Kuwait?
<p>
General:  No, we did not discuss any specific increases.  What we
discussed is the presence that we have here now, and we both
expressed our satisfaction with the way our relationship is
moving
along.  I took the opportunity to express my deep appreciation
for
the way our troops here are being hosted.  It's being done in an
excellent way.  Thank you very much.
<p>
<HR>
