<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE></TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">
<H2>AGRICULTURE COMMITTEE OF THE U.S.-SOUTH AFRICA BINATIONAL
COMMISSION    JUNE 1996</H2>
<P> The U.S.-South Africa Binational Commission was established
in March 1995 to facilitate bilateral cooperation between the
United States and South Africa to ensure that key issues of
mutual concern are discussed at the highest levels of government.
 Agriculture was the sixth committee formed under the auspices of
the Binational Commission.  The Agriculture committee is
co-chaired by U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) Secretary Dan
Glickman and the new South African Minister of Agriculture and
Land Affairs Derek Andre Hanekom, who assumed his ministerial
portfolio in May 2996 after the resignation of then South African
Minister of Agriculture Andre Isak van Niekerk. 
</P>
<P>The Agriculture Committee's goal is to strengthen bilateral
relations between the United States and South Africa on
agricultural and rural development issues of mutual interest. 
The committee provides a high-level, government-to-government
framework to facilitate discussion and cooperation on
agricultural programs, projects, and linkages between the two
countries in the following areas: agricultural trade, investment,
and development; rural economic and community development;
agricultural marketing, regulation, and safety of food products;
food and nutrition; sustainable use and management of natural
resources; and agricultural economics, extension, and research. 
</P>
<P>At the first meeting of the Agriculture Committee on March
26, 1996, organizational and membership issues were the focus of
discussion.  The co-chairs -- U.S. Agriculture Secretary Glickman
and the former South African Agriculture Minister van Niekerk --
agreed to sign a Terms of Reference (TOR) by the next meeting of
the Agriculture Committee on July 22, 1996.  The meeting precedes
the third full meeting of the Binational Commission on July 23,
1996.  The TOR describes the functions and organizational
structure of the committee.  The committee has formed four
working groups to address agricultural issues: Market Access,
Institutional Development, Sustainability and Agriculture in the
Rural Context, and Agricultural Technology Development for Income
Generation. 
</P>
<P>The Agriculture Committee held a U.S.-South Africa
Agribusiness Trade Opportunities Forum in Washington, D.C., on
March 27, 1996, for South African agribusinesses.  Participants
exchanged ideas and information about doing business in South
Africa.  Topics included public and private financing, food
safety requirements for export and import, transportation of food
products, and opportunities for U.S. high-value, intermediate,
and bulk products.  Additionally, the committee is funding
numerous agricultural and rural development training and
technical assistance programs in South Africa. 
</P>
<P>Other committees of the Binational Commission are the
sustainable Minerals and Energy Committee; the Human Resources
Development and Education Committee; the Conservation, Water, and
the Environment Committee; the Trade and Investment Committee,
and the Science and Technology Committee. 
</P>
<P>For more information about the Agriculture Committee and the
U.S.-South Africa Binational Commission, contact: 
</P>
<P>Frankie King Foreign Agricultural Service International
Cooperation and Development U.S. Department of Agriculture Room
3008-South Building AgBox 1081 Washington, DC  20250-1081 Tel:
(202) 690-0598 Fax: (202) 270-6l03 Internet: fking@usda.gov
</P></BODY></HTML>
