<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Science and Technology Committee</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY
BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#993300" VLINK="#666600" ALINK="#CCCCCC">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="ussafg.gif"><BR>
<I><FONT SIZE="6">Science and Technology Committee</FONT></I>
</CENTER><IMG SRC="spacer.gif" WIDTH="10" HEIGHT="35">
<P>U.S., S. AFRICA SIGN JOINT ENVIRONMENT AGREEMENT,<BR>
Excerpts from the December 5, 1995 statement on accord 
</P>
<P>
PRETORIA -- At the conclusion of the U.S.-South Africa Binational
Commission meetings December 5, U.S. Vice President Al Gore and
South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki signed an umbrella
Environment, Science and Technology Agreement.
</P>
<P>The agreement provides a framework for governmental science
and technology (S&amp;T) cooperation between the U.S. and South
Africa, including protection for intellectual property.
</P>
<P>Following are excerpts of a statement released by Vice
President Gore's office, marking the occasion:
</P>
<P>(BEGIN EXCERPTS)
</P>
<P>The Agreement will pave the way for cooperation in areas
ranging from energy research to climate prediction to biomedical
research.  The signing was witnessed by Science and Technology
Committee Co-chairs John H. Gibbons, U.S. Assistant to the
President for Science and Technology, and Ben Ngubane, South
African Minister for Arts, Culture, Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>Among the top priorities of the S&amp;T Committee are
education and capacity building in science and technology.  At
the December 4 meeting, the Committee members discussed proposals
to advance S&amp;T education and training in South Africa, with
the long-term goal of creating a new generation of scientific
leaders.  Proposals under the committee include a Faculty
Enrichment Program at South African historically black colleges
and universities (HBCUs), in which the U.S. Department of Energy
will support advanced training in science and engineering for
faculty at historically disadvantaged institutions.
</P>
<P>In addition, the U.S. National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration, the Southeast Fisheries Science Center, and the
University of Maryland Eastern Shore will sponsor a cooperative
educational program in the marine and environmental sciences. 
The S&amp;T;Committee will also launch a program to encourage
young South Africans to study math and science by holding a video
dialogue between NASA astronaut Winston Scott and South African
students during Scott's January 1995 space shuttle mission.
</P>
<P>Also under the auspices of the S&amp;T Committee, the U.S.
Department of Agriculture and the South African Agricultural
Research Council signed a Cooperative Agreement on Agricultural
Science and Technology.  A prime goal is to support small-scale
farmers and to create small business enterprises in rural areas
through joint technology development.
</P>
<P>The S&amp;T Committee also held discussion on cooperation in
health and the biomedical sciences.  The sides discussed a
proposal to cooperate on the use of telecommunications for
medical diagnosis, which would expand access to health care to
millions of South Africans in rural areas.  The Committee also
made a commitment to promote cooperation between the U.S. and
South Africa in the surveillance of emerging infectious diseases,
such as tuberculosis and HIV/AIDS, which have reached epidemic
proportions worldwide.
</P>
<P>(END EXCERPTS) NNNN
</P>
<P>12/06/95
<A NAME="agpact">U.S., SOUTH AFRICA SIGN AGRICULTURAL SCIENCE
AND TECHNOLOGY PACT</A> (Text:  12/5 announcement) (310)
</P>
<P>PRETORIA -- Vice President Gore and South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki on December 5 announced the completion of a
Cooperative Agreement between the U.S. Department of Agriculture
(USDA) and the South African Agricultural Research Council (ARC)
on Agricultural Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>The agreement, signed by Floyd Horn, administrator of the
Agricultural Research Service, USDA, and Jons Terblanche, ARC
president, under the auspices of the U.S.-South Africa Binational
Commission Science and Technology Committee, will support
small-scale farmers and help create small business enterprises in
rural areas through joint technology development.
</P>
<P>Following is the text of a statement on the agreement
released by Gore's office:
</P>
<P>(BEGIN TEXT)
</P>
<P>THE WHITE HOUSE OFFICE OF THE VICE PRESIDENT
</P>
<P>For Immediate Release                                  
December 5, 1995
</P>
<P>U.S.-SOUTH AFRICA BINATIONAL COMMISSION SCIENCE AND
TECHNOLOGY COMMITTEE
</P>
<P>Cooperative Agreement on Agricultural Science and Technology
</P>
<P>At today's meeting of the U.S.-South Africa Binational
Commission, U.S. Vice President Al Gore and South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki announced the completion of a Cooperative
Agreement between the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) and
the South African Agricultural Research Council (ARC) on
Agricultural Science and Technology.  The Cooperative Agreement
was signed on Friday, December 1, by Floyd Horn, Administrator of
the Agricultural Research Service, USDA, and Jons Terblanche, ARC
President, under the auspices of the Science and Technology
Committee.
</P>
<P>A prime goal is to support small-scale farmers and to create
small business enterprises in rural areas through joint
technology development.  Cooperative projects under this
agreement include production of goat meat, hides, and ornamental
plants; small-scale dairying; development of technology for
improving shelf-life for fruit and vegetables; and enhanced
production of arid-zone plants used in high-value products.
</P>
<P>(END TEXT)</P>
<P>12/06/95
<A NAME="umbrella">U.S., S. AFRICA SIGN JOINT ENVIRONMENT
AGREEMENT</A> (Excerpts:  12/5 statement on accord) (450)
</P>
<P>PRETORIA -- At the conclusion of the U.S.-South Africa
Binational Commission meetings December 5, U.S. Vice President Al
Gore and South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki signed an
umbrella Environment, Science and Technology Agreement.
</P>
<P>The agreement provides a framework for governmental science
and technology (S&amp;T) cooperation between the U.S. and South
Africa, including protection for intellectual property.
</P>
<P>Following are excerpts of a statement released by Vice
President Gore's office, marking the occasion:
</P>
<P>(BEGIN EXCERPTS)
</P>
<P>The Agreement will pave the way for cooperation in areas
ranging from energy research to climate prediction to biomedical
research.  The signing was witnessed by Science and Technology
Committee Co-chairs John H. Gibbons, U.S. Assistant to the
President for Science and Technology, and Ben Ngubane, South
African Minister for Arts, Culture, Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>Among the top priorities of the S&amp;T Committee are
education and capacity building in science and technology.  At
the December 4 meeting, the Committee members discussed proposals
to advance S&amp;T education and training in South Africa, with
the long-term goal of creating a new generation of scientific
leaders.  Proposals under the committee include a Faculty
Enrichment Program at South African historically black colleges
and universities (HBCUs), in which the U.S. Department of Energy
will support advanced training in science and engineering for
faculty at historically disadvantaged institutions.
</P>
<P>In addition, the U.S. National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration, the Southeast Fisheries Science Center, and the
University of Maryland Eastern Shore will sponsor a cooperative
educational program in the marine and environmental sciences. 
The S&amp;T;Committee will also launch a program to encourage
young South Africans to study math and science by holding a video
dialogue between NASA astronaut Winston Scott and South African
students during Scott's January 1995 space shuttle mission.
</P>
<P>Also under the auspices of the S&amp;T Committee, the U.S.
Department of Agriculture and the South African Agricultural
Research Council signed a Cooperative Agreement on Agricultural
Science and Technology.  A prime goal is to support small-scale
farmers and to create small business enterprises in rural areas
through joint technology development.
</P>
<P>The S&amp;T Committee also held discussion on cooperation in
health and the biomedical sciences.  The sides discussed a
proposal to cooperate on the use of telecommunications for
medical diagnosis, which would expand access to health care to
millions of South Africans in rural areas.  The Committee also
made a commitment to promote cooperation between the U.S. and
South Africa in the surveillance of emerging infectious diseases,
such as tuberculosis and HIV/AIDS, which have reached epidemic
proportions worldwide.
</P>
<P>(END EXCERPTS) NNNN
</P>
