<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>2nd meeting  - Gore remarks</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">
<H2>U.S. AND SOUTH AFRICA GROW STRONGER THROUGH BNC, GORE SAYS</H2>
<P>
Good afternoon.  I would like to begin by thanking all the
dedicated men and women who have worked so hard these past months
to make this meeting of the U.S.-South Africa Binational
Commission a true success.  My special thanks, though, go to
South Africa's Deputy President Thabo Mbeki for the commitment
and leadership he has shown throughout the BNC process which we
began here in Washington in March of 1995 and continued in
Pretoria late last year. 
</P>
<P>
Created by the clear vision and very good sense of Presidents
Mandela and Clinton, our Binational Commission exists to support
one very simple, but fundamental idea:  that our nations can grow
stronger, wiser, more free and prosperous when our citizens join
together in common cause to confront common challenges, and to
take advantage of shared opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
We have accomplished a great deal since our last meeting. 
Together, we have explored ways to reduce pollution, conserve
water, manage waste, empower and educate our young people,
protect our environment, improve agricultural practices, build
free markets and free minds, and help open the door to real
economic opportunity for all our citizens. 
</P>
<P>
By sharing experience and know-how, we also have been enriching
both our nations.  Since our Commission's first meeting, over 100
South African leaders have participated in professional exchanges
with their American counterparts.  We also have launched the
Mandela scholars program, which is providing graduate-level
economics training for historically disadvantaged South Africans.

</P>
<P>
These young people truly are the best hope for our future.  I
would like to ask those Mandela scholars who are here today to
stand up and be recognized.... 
</P>
<P>
Each of you should know we are all very, very proud of you. 
</P>
<P>
If I may, I would like briefly to review some of the important
new steps we've taken in the past few days across the full range
of our Commission's efforts, from promoting trade and investment,
to cooperation on agriculture, sustainable energy, science and
technology, human resources development and education, and our
environment. 
</P>
<P>
-- First, I am pleased to announce that earlier today, Ruth
Harkin, the President of the U.S. Overseas Private Investment
Corporation, signed an Investment Fund Protocol to support a 120
million dollar private equity fund that will invest in businesses
in South Africa owned by the country's majority population.  This
new fund represents a major step towards spurring investment,
trade, job creation, and growth in a new, robust, and prosperous
South Africa. 
</P>
<P>
I am proud that our Commission has played an important role in
making this new fund a reality. 
</P>
<P>
-- The civil aviation agreement we just signed also is emblematic
of the many other accomplishments of the BNC.  This agreement
will restore formal aviation relations between the U.S. and South
Africa for the first time since they were broken in protest over
apartheid more than nine years ago.  The agreement is born of
mutual need and will serve our mutual self-interest.  The flow of
trade, investment, and tourism between our two countries has
grown enormously in the last two years.  By recent count, one new
American business per week has set up shop in South Africa. 
American tourism to South Africa has doubled in that same period.

</P>
<P>
This new agreement will meet the existing need for more passenger
and cargo flights between our countries and provides for
increasing scheduled and charter flights to meet the further
growth that is sure to come. 
</P>
<P>
-- We also have agreed during this session to expand our
cooperative efforts to combat crime.  The U.S. will contribute
substantially to South Africa's request for assistance to help
realize the full potential of its law enforcement forces. 
</P>
<P>
Working together, sharing ideas and expertise, I know we can
improve the quality of law enforcement in both countries and can
help each other ensure the safety and security our citizens
deserve. 
</P>
<P>
-- We also signed a Declaration of Intent to help bring South
Africa into the growing community of schoolchildren, teachers,
and scientists around the world that participate in a program
which we call &quot;GLOBE&quot;; or &quot;Global Learning and
Observation to Benefit the Environment.&quot;  This is a hands-on
science and education program we formed at the beginning of the
Administration that links students, educators, and scientists
around the world through the Internet to study our environment,
and share data about our planet with scientists and each other. 
</P>
<P>
Already, some 37 nations and tens of thousands of students
participate in this important effort.  I am glad that South
Africa soon will become a GLOBE partner as well. 
</P>
<P>
-- We also pledged today to proceed with a partnership to create
a Fulbright Commission which will improve and expand the ways in
which Americans and South Africans study and conduct research
together. 
</P>
<P>
-- We are working with our partners in South Africa to build
energy-efficient housing, and to promote the use of renewable and
clean fuels, both by industry and in homes. 
</P>
<P>
-- Our Peace Corps also will soon provide talented young
Americans with the chance to work with South Africans where they
live to help improve education and foster good-will. 
</P>
<P>
Through these, and many other initiatives of our Binational
Commission, the U.S. and South Africa are building a matrix of
mutually beneficial connections, programs, exchanges, and
business ventures. 
</P>
<P>
Some of those, like the civil aviation agreement, are bearing
fruit today.  Others, like the Mandela Scholars program and the
Fulbright Commission, will pay dividends in the future.  But
these are all part of the same critical effort -- to establish a
healthy give-and-take across all aspects of our societies, and to
nurture the possibilities of peace, justice, and prosperity for
all our citizens.  I am deeply proud of our work together.  And
Mr.  Deputy President, may I say that I look forward to our next
meeting in South Africa. 
</P></BODY></HTML>
