<HEAD>
<TITLE>Role of NGOs</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">
<H2>ROLE OF NGOs IN THE WORK OF THE AGRICULTURE COMMITTEE</H2>
<P> Introduction
</P>
<P> At the first meeting of the Agriculture Committee held on
March 26 here in Washington, a joint U.S.-South African position
was put forth to include NGOs and CBOs in the work of the
committee at the working group level.  It was suggested, however,
that they will not have full-fledged membership on the committee.
 This first Committee meeting was focused heavily on resolving
several organization and membership issues as outlined in its
draft Terms of Reference that will impact the final outcome of
involvement by any non-public sector organizations in the work of
the committee.  It is our position that a final report should
reflect the views of the full membership of the committee which
is a work in progress.  It is our goal to have a final report on
or before the next full commission meeting.
</P>
<P> Background
</P>
<P> USDA's pre-Committee work in South Africa, which began in
the fall of 1994, heavily utilized the experiences of NGOs,
academia, and the private agribusiness sectors in the
implementation and consultation processes of its programs and
projects in South Africa.  Collaboration with U.S. organizations
such as 21st Century Africa, U.S. Wheat Associates, Africare, and
Land O'Lakes, and South African organizations such as Wesgro, the
Rural Foundation, and the Peninsula Technician was important to
projects such as the Cochran Fellowship Program and discussions
of our food aid programs.  Expanding and continuing these
relationships is strongly desired. 
</P>
<P>The issue of the role of NGOs was an agenda item during the
pre-Committee meeting in Pretoria this past December.  However,
it was decided to table discussion on the matter until the first
full meeting of the Committee. 
</P>
<P>Role of NGOs in the Context of the First Agriculture
Committee Meeting 
</P>
<P>Secretary Dan Glickman and Minister Andre van Nickerk
convened the first meeting of the Agriculture Committee this past
March 26 here in Washington.  This meeting was heavily focused on
first order membership and organizational issues that are
important to the Terms of Reference. 
</P>
<P>First order membership issues highlighted both sides'
progress made to date on determining the membership of other USG
departments and agencies and other South African ministries and
departments.  Discussion was had concerning the potential
membership to the committee of both sides' private agribusiness
sectors, Congress/Parliament, academia, and NGOs and CBO's.  It
was put forth that none of these entities be full-fledged members
of the committee.  
</P>
<P> Initial progress was made organizationally by identifying
four broad working groups that, for starters, would serve as the
technical operating mechanisms for integrating, facilitating,
resolving, developing, and planning joint programs and
activities.  These four working groups are: 1) Agricultural
Market Access, 2) Institutional Development, 3) Sustainability of
Agriculture in the Rural Context, and 4) Agricultural Technology
Development for Rural Income Generation.  It was suggested that
NGOs would best serve the committee at this working group level. 
It was determined that further discussion would be needed to
reach a common understanding and working definition of NGOs. 
Several teleconferences will be scheduled between now and the
next commission meeting to address the details of this and other
issues.
</P>
<P> It is the goal of the Co-chairs of the Agriculture Committee
to have a completed Terms of Reference ready for signature by
both the Vice President and Executive Deputy President Mbeki by
the next full commission meeting.  A final report on the role of
NGOs will be forwarded to the OVP on or before that time.
</P></BODY></HTML>
