<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>State of Conclusion</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">
<H3 ALIGN="center">THE WHITE HOUSE<BR>  Office of the Vice
President<BR> 
_____________________________________________________</H3>
<P>
<BR> For Immediate Release	July 23, 1996 
</P>
<P>
United States-South Africa Binational Commission  
</P>
<P>
Human Resources Development and Education Committee  
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Gore noted today that the Human Resources
Development and Education (HRDE) Committee of the Binational
Commission met on Monday, July 22, 1996 to discuss progress since
the last meeting in December 1995 and to determine next steps. 
The Committee reported on activities in its three program areas: 
	</P>
<P>
The Joint Working Group on a Fulbright Commission, a committee of
four Americans and four South Africans, met frequently from
February through May 1996 to consider the feasibility of
establishing a U.S.-South Africa Fulbright Commission.  The final
report, which  strongly recommends the establishment of a
commission,  has been received by the HRDE Committee.  The two
governments were favorably impressed with the report and are
considering the establishment of a Fulbright Commission.    	</P>
<P>
The Committee reported on activities of the Youth Development
program which is recognizing and addressing the needs of  the
disadvantaged youth of South Africa.  The potential for
collaboration on youth development issues between the United
States and South Africa holds great promise.  The National Youth
Commission was established in June 1996 in South Africa.  The
national coordinator of youth development activities, Sheila
Sisulu, and several youth commissioners exchanged information
with their American counterparts during a three-week study tour. 
  Next steps include working with the National Youth Commission
to develop a national framework and to implement, monitor and
evaluate development activities.  
</P>
<P>
  	The Post-Graduate Economics Training Program also has seen
progress.   In  December 1995 a Memorandum of Understanding was
signed for the program, which promotes post-graduate studies in
economics by members of the disadvantaged communities across
South Africa.  The first six Mandela Economic Scholars are now
beginning their training program.  Further scholars will
eventually form a cadre of 50 highly trained economists.    
</P></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
