<HEAD>
<TITLE>USIA, Introduction to Human Rights - The U.S. Commitment
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<br>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="thinblue.gif"><P>
<P>
<H3>THE U.S. COMMITMENT</H3>
<p><i>An Interview With John
Shattuck,
U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, <br>Human
Rights,
and Labor</i>
</CENTER>
<P>
<BR>
<P>
<blockquote><blockquote><blockquote>
<hr>
<p>
<b><i>...we are at a new moment. Our agenda for freedom must
embrace 
every prisoner of conscience, every victim of torture, 
every individual denied basic human rights. 
It must also encompass the democratic movements that have changed
the political map of our globe.</i>
<P><center>
Warren Christopher, U.S. Secretary of State, from his remarks at
the World Conference on Human Rights, Vienna, Austria,
1993</b>
<hr>
</center>
</blockquote></blockquote></blockquote><p><br>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<b><i><font size=5>Q.</font></i></b><i>
One of the most important
conferences on human rights in
recent history took place in Vienna in 1993. What was the
significance of what happened there?</i>
<P>
<b><i><font size=5>A.</font></i></b>
In 1993, the World Conference on
Human Rights re-emphasized
that there are no cultural, religious, or other barriers that
should stand in the way of the universal enjoyment of basic human
rights. No one, no matter what country he or she lives in, should
be subjected to torture simply because of the cultural or
religious traditions of that country. No one should be subjected
to arbitrary execution. No one should be subjected to mass rape
as a tool of so-called ethnic cleansing, just because of
religious differences in a country. This is what universality is
all about.
<P>
Probably no situation better illustrates this issue than the
crisis in Bosnia, where the fundamental rights of the person were
massively violated in a setting in which cultural, ethnic, and
religious differences became excuses for human rights violations.
This is why universality is so important.
<P>
Those governments that claim that they can be exempt from basic
principles of human rights because they have different cultures
or different historical traditions simply fly in the face of
basic human experience at the end of the 20th century, when there
is so much global interconnectedness. Obviously, we should
celebrate differences -- different countries, different cultures,
different religions  -- and we should protect those differences.
But those differences can never be an excuse for torturing,
killing, raping, or otherwise fundamentally violating a person's
rights and freedoms, for putting them in prison for long periods
of time without a trial or without finding some guilt in due
process, or for preventing them from speaking or engaging in
basic freedoms of expression.
<P>
The Vienna Declaration made clear by its very language that human
rights are not only universal but are a legitimate subject for
international organizations and institutions. This is why any
effort to prevent the United Nations Human Rights Commission --
which meets annually to review the human rights records of
countries around the world -- from scrutinizing the record of a
country is a violation of the principle of legitimate inquiry
into human rights, which is what the Vienna Declaration is all
about. This is why it was so important in 1995 that the
commission rejected the effort of a large country -- China -- to
block consideration of its human rights record. This is also why
it is so important to build new institutions to improve human
rights in Bosnia or Rwanda or any other place where universal
values have been fundamentally shattered.
<P>
What Vienna did, I think, was show that adherence to human rights
must be more than rhetoric. It involves implementation as well,
whether through international institutions or through domestic
institutions. This is why the Human Rights Commission is so
important; this is why the human rights ombudsman is so important
in Bosnia; this is why the War Crimes Tribunal and many other
institutions that are built to advance human rights protections
are so important for Rwanda and Bosnia. This is the spirit of
Vienna.
<P>
<b><i><font size=5>Q.</font></i></b><i>
In March of 1995, the
United States submitted its first report
on the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights for
United Nations scrutiny. What was the significance of this?</i>
<P>
<b><i><font size=5>A.</font></i></b>
This was the first time that the
United States, in an
international setting, publicly issued a report about its own
human rights situation. This was done pursuant to U.S.
ratification of the major covenant implementing the Universal
Declaration -- the Covenant on Civil and Political Rights. The
United States will be issuing other reports as well, as do other
countries. I think this emphasizes that the standards of the
Universal Declaration are as absolutely applicable within the
United States as they are around the world.
<P>
The United States is very proud of the fact that its own
Constitution and Bill of Rights in some ways provide even greater
protection to civil and political rights than the Universal
Declaration. For example, in the area of freedom of speech, the
United States is widely regarded as having higher standards than
those found throughout the world. This is one thing that was
emphasized in our report to the United Nations. But the United
States also has had its shortcomings. Certainly among these are
the history of its treatment of African-Americans and, in some
cases, of refugees and of other minority groups -- the terrible
legacy of slavery, the terrible legacy of the way in which
American Indians, Native Americans, were treated. These
shortcomings demonstrate how important it is to have a Universal
Declaration. The United States considers itself, as many other
countries do, a work in progress in terms of trying to constantly
improve its adherence to these basic international standards.
<P>
<b><i><font size=5>Q.</font></i></b><i>
You are known to be a
strong advocate of the role of
nongovernmental organizations in advancing human rights and civil
society. What is the importance of this role?</i>
<P>
<b><i><font size=5>A.</font></i></b>
Ultimately, human rights are not
about government. They are
about people. One of the most dramatic developments of the last
50 years has been the popular movement across the globe for the
advancement of democracy and human rights, for participation in
government. The greatest achievement of this movement probably
came when the Cold War ended, freeing hundreds of millions of
people from living under conditions in which there were virtually
no civil and political rights.
<P>
Nongovernmental organizations form the backbone of the protection
of human rights in any society. This is certainly true in
American society, and it is true in other societies as well. That
is why the work we do in support of the massive international
grass-roots movement to protect human rights has even greater
importance than any particular relationship we have with other
governments.
<P>
Nongovernmental organizations can do many practical things. They
can lobby on behalf of people whose rights are being violated.
They can gather information. They can provide technical expertise
in building new institutions of justice and in supporting court
systems working on reconciliation in societies torn apart by
civil war or human rights abuse. Nongovernmental organizations
are absolutely vital to the advancement of human rights the world
over. Their work is hard and sometimes dangerous. We are
constantly saluting and showing support for those human rights
workers around the world who live under dangerous conditions,
many of whom are injured or killed in the process of their work.
<P>
A new element of U.S. human rights policy in the last several
years has been to support, both financially and diplomatically,
nongovernmental organizations that are active in emerging
democracies -- in South Africa, in Russia, in the countries of
Eastern Europe, in parts of Asia. A civil society that protects
human rights and recognizes their importance can come into being
only through the work of countless small organizations that are
dedicated to their own specific work -- whether in the
environment of refugees or the administration of justice or in
political parties. Groups that are working on elections or
organizations that provide assistance to other citizens, that
provide charity -- these are basic elements of civil society.
<P>
Nongovernmental organizations clearly are central players in the
effort to develop a system that allows greater participation by
people in their own governments and, ultimately, in democracy.
That has been a major focus of U.S. foreign policy in recent
years; that is why the State Department's Bureau of Human Rights
has been renamed and expanded to become the Bureau of Democracy,
Human Rights, and Labor.
<P>
<b><i><font size=5>Q.</font></i></b><i>
The State Department has
been issuing its annual Human Rights
Reports since 1977. How has the process evolved since then?</i>
<P>
<b><i><font size=5>A.</font></i></b>
The Human Rights Reports, I think,
reflect the importance of
human rights in American foreign policy. They also reflect the
universality of human rights. All countries are covered, and the
United States now is also issuing reports on itself in response
to treaties it has signed. In 1995, a very important event
occurred when the United States appeared for the first time
before the UN Human Rights Committee  in New York and publicly
discussed its own report on civil and political rights in the
United States.
<P>
The Human Rights Reports are issued for 194 countries -- 195 if
you include the United States. They reflect the central values of
the Universal Declaration [on Human Rights], which also reflects
the basic values of America's Constitution and Bill of Rights.
The reports are issued annually and have been since 1977. They
have grown in number from approximately 50 reports to the present
195. They cover a range of political and civil rights issues, and
they are expanding into other areas, such as the rights of women,
workers' rights, the rights of disabled persons.  I'm sure
additional areas will come into focus in the future.  
<P>
It is obviously an enormous task to objectively pull together the
information that goes into these reports. The information
included is received from U.S. embassies around the world and
from other governments, as well as from nongovernmental
organizations. Each report is a measure of the state of human
rights in any country, and also a way of showing trends in the
progress in human rights around the world.
<P>
The reports can be controversial. Clearly, governments are not
very receptive to reading criticisms or statements about human
rights failures and shortcomings in their own countries. But the
reports are tremendously important to the millions of people
around the world who are struggling to improve their own
situations with regard to human rights and to engage in dialogue
with their own governments. This is true also in the United
States, which is constantly under scrutiny by its citizens in
terms of freedom of speech and freedom of religion. These are
central issues in our election campaigns, and the same should be
true throughout the world.
<P>
<b><i><font size=5>Q.</font></i></b><i>
The United States has a
very complex relationship with the
People's Republic of China. How would you describe U.S. efforts
to induce China to improve its human rights practices?</i>
<P>
<b><i><font size=5>A.</font></i></b>
The United States has made clear
from the very beginning of
its work in the human rights area that all countries, including
our own, should adhere to international standards of human
rights. At the end of the 20th century, this should be the
hallmark of enlightened government around the world. No
government should be exempt from that -- certainly not the United
States, and certainly not the People's Republic of China, if only
because China is the largest country in the world in terms of
population. So we have not hesitated to analyze and report on
human rights abuses in China and to publicly criticize those
abuses. Issues involving significant repression of the freedoms
of speech and religion frequently have been raised by the United
States both in bilateral discussions with Chinese government
officials and in the international setting, in such places as the
United Nations Human Rights Commission, where we regularly
co-sponsor resolutions on the human rights situation in China
critical of the government's handling of freedom of speech,
freedom of religion, and other basic freedoms.
<P>
<b><i><font size=5>Q.</font></i></b><i>
How do such policy
formulations fit in with the other demands
of our foreign policy relationship with China?</i>
<P>
<b><i><font size=5>A.</font></i></b>
Foreign affairs in an open,
democratic society such as our own
is a subject that is publicly debated. There is great interest in
the U.S. Congress, and there are frequent congressional hearings
on subjects such as the human rights situation in China. Our
press and nongovernmental organizations take a great interest in
these subjects as well. This means that the State Department's
report on the human rights situation in China is looked at very
closely for its accuracy. Also, the way in which the United
States raises human rights issues with China makes it very clear
that it will be impossible for the United States to have a
complete and positive relationship without improvements on the
human rights front.  
<P>
The U.S. policy toward China is one of engagement, dialogue,
discussion -- and that includes human rights very centrally.
<P>
<b><i><font size=5>Q.</font></i></b><i>
How do you see the events
in Bosnia and the creation of the
International War Crimes Tribunal in the context of the
historical evolution of human rights?</i>
<P>
<b><i><font size=5>A.</font></i></b>
Clearly, the situation in Bosnia
calls upon all the
imagination of diplomats, military specialists, and economic
specialists. The challenge of rebuilding a fundamentally
shattered society that has, in essence, been destroyed by massive
violations of human rights -- worse than anything seen in Europe
since the end of the Second World War -- is enormous. It is a
challenge of vision and of practical implementation. The vision
must have at its heart rebuilding the understanding that any
society needs to be able to function, the understanding that
there are certain basic values that hold people together. The
integrity of the person, the right not to be tortured or executed
or raped, the right to stay on your own property and in your own
house without being forced out -- these are among the rights that
have been so fundamentally violated in Bosnia by cynical leaders
who have fanned the flames of ethnic and religious
misunderstanding. The value system at the center of the Bosnia
effort is very important; it is the universal value of human
rights.
<P>
I think it is important to emphasize that all countries in the
United Nations Security Council have seen the Bosnian crisis in
the same way -- ultimately, as a catastrophe of the violation of
fundamental human values. China, Russia, the United States, the
European countries, members of the Security Council from other
states -- all have joined together in seeing this as an attack on
fundamental human values and human rights.
<P>
The implementation side of this calls upon the international
community to create new institutions to rebuild the values that
have been shattered, institutions of justice such as the
International War Crimes Tribunal, which was established by the
Security Council three years ago, not only for Bosnia but for
Rwanda, another country that was devastated in much the same way.
The new institutional structures for rebuilding Bosnia will
provide for the rights of refugees to return to their homes, will
create a framework for resolving human rights disputes as the 
[United Nations] Human Rights Commission does, and will set up
the election process mandated by the Dayton Peace Accords that
were signed by all the parties.
<P>
What has been learned so painfully over the past few years is the
need for a strong international commitment to back up this
institution-building and the reinforcement of human rights. That
is what the NATO Implementation Force is all about, with its
60,000 members. Having pulled the warring factions apart and
assured that the zone of separation is protected, that force is
now turning its attention to assisting in the civilian
implementation of human rights protections, as well as other
aspects of the peace accord.  
<P>
We have in Bosnia both a tremendous challenge and a great example
of what can be done when the world community pulls together to
address the shattering of universally held values.
<P>
I think Bosnia is the test of the late 20th century for human
rights. There are other tests as well, but Bosnia is a very
powerful example. Human rights are not just rhetoric, nor are
they just universally held values. The human rights system has to
be implemented on the ground. To overcome the horror of genocide,
it takes new institutions that we have perhaps never had before
-- human rights enforcement mechanisms that are part of a process
of reconciliation and peace. These human rights institutions will
emphasize justice as much as they will reconciliation. It is
difficult to end the spiral of violence that grips a society like
Bosnia when that violence is unleashed by criminal elements who
are claiming leadership. The only way to end the violence is to
bring to justice those responsible for unleashing it, or at least
to begin the process of bringing them to justice -- isolating
them as the International War Crimes Tribunal is doing, turning
them into pariahs within the international community. They cannot
travel anywhere without fear of being arrested, and ultimately
they must be arrested and brought to justice. Otherwise, the
violence is likely to continue.    o
<P><center>
__________
<P>
This interview was conducted by Rick Marshall, <br>a staff writer
with the United States Information Agency.
<P>
</blockquote>
