<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release July 23, 1996</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">
<H3>THE WHITE HOUSE Office of the Vice President</H3>
<P>
______________________________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
For Immediate Release	July 23, 1996 
</P>
<P>
United States-South Africa Binational Commission 
</P>
<P>
U.S.-SOUTH AFRICA ENERGY PROJECTS EXPAND ACCESS TO POWER AND
INCREASE USE OF RENEWABLE RESOURCES IN SOUTH AFRICA   	</P>
<P>
New energy  policies and programs resulting from U.S.-South
African cooperation promise to make electricity more widely
available to South Africa's citizens and increase the use of
sustainable energy technologies.  The Sustainable Energy
Committee of the U.S.-South Africa Binational Commission will
report achievements in these areas at the commission meetings
headed by Vice President Al Gore and Deputy President Thabo Mbeki
next week.  The energy committee, co-chaired by Secretary of
Energy Hazel R. O'Leary and Minister of Mineral and Energy
Affairs Penuell M. Maduna, met today in Washington, D.C., to
finalize its progress report and discuss new initiatives that
will further increase the economic and environmental benefits to
South Africans.  
</P>
<P>
	Through joint efforts on the Sustainable Energy Committee, the
United States and South Africa have: 
</P>
<P>
o	Drafted electricity legislation for consideration by South
Africa's Parliament, which would ensure the legal and financial
infrastructure needed to distribute the benefits of electricity
equitably among the nation's citizens . o	Built a modular,
energy-efficient house in South Africa with financial support
from the U.S. Agency for International Development, which has
resulted in orders to build a community of 200 such homes and
plans for another 2,000.  o	Established a board of directors,
business plan, and financial incentives program for Renewable
Energy for South Africa (REFSA), a joint organization that
promotes the use of renewable technologies in off-grid
applications. o	Agreed to a natural gas action plan which will
include legislation creating a gas market in South Africa   o	Met
numerous other commitments made during Secretary O'Leary's trade
mission to South Africa in August 1995 and the Binational
Commission meeting in South Africa in December 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	&quot;Already our collaborations are starting to deliver real
benefits to real people in the form of electric power, energy
policies and laws, and energy-efficient, affordable housing,&quot;
said O'Leary.  &quot;We applaud and continue to support the
progress made so far in the energy sector under South Africa's
redevelopment plans.  While we have made a good start, however,
we cannot stop here.  What we have yet to do is to attract the
private investment that will make even more of South Africa's
energy goals a reality and ensure the economic incentives that
will make them self- sustaining.&quot;  	</P>
<P>
DOE sent a two-person team to South Africa's workshop this spring
to help draft electricity legislation that encourages economic
growth and the equitable distribution of electricity.  That team
will continue to provide expert advice throughout the regulatory
restructuring process.  DOE experts will assist in designing and
will participate in a South African  Workshop in October to
create a legislative framework for the initiation of a gas market
in South Africa.  DOE is also supporting the drafting of South
Africa's energy policy and an options paper on energy  strategy. 
	</P>
<P>
Improving access to convenient and affordable sources of energy
is one of South Africa's primary goals for the energy sector. 
The Sustainable Energy Committee is partially addressing this
goal  through Renewable Energy for South Africa, which is
developing a pilot program to install 2,500 photovoltaic systems
in rural areas that do not have access to the electricity grid. 
The solar power systems, half funded by the U.S. Agency for
International Development, will help supply power  for lighting,
television/radio, and productive uses to the estimated 2.5
million homes and 100,000 small businesses currently without it. 
  	</P>
<P>
Another avenue for increasing and conserving energy supplies is
an integrated housing project to develop, design and build an
urban housing pilot project featuring energy-efficient designs. 
A model home in Kimberley already built and exhibited by a
partnership of U.S. and South African companies showed enough
promise to result in industry orders to build 200 such houses.  A
long-term commitment by the private sector to build 2,000 more
houses is anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
	Another joint project that promises to deliver real benefits to
people is a series of workshops for South African industry and
community leaders to explore the benefits of investing in
low-smoke fuels for home heating and cooling.  The meetings and
tours of U.S. facilities, organized by DOE's Pittsburgh Energy
Technology Center, demonstrated the use of coal waste
reclamation, coal briquetting, and biomass and wood combustion
technologies that can provide cleaner, more efficient home energy
supplies than traditional sources.  	  </P>
<P>
	In the transportation sector, the Sustainable Energy Committee
has developed an action plan to study South Africa's
transportation needs and to form a partnership between U.S. and
South African industries to research and develop electric
vehicles and other clean, energy-efficient transportation fuels.

</P>
<P>
	Businesses and communities should find it easier to gain easy
access to statistics and information on energy use and energy
technologies through an energy database project supported by
DOE's Energy Information Administration (EIA).  Under this
effort, the South Africans are exploring the feasibility of
starting a computerized information system modeled after EIA's
service, which provides extensive information to the U.S.
government and general public on domestic and international
energy supply, demand, prices, and use.  	</P>
<P>
In addition to these projects, numerous other U.S.-South African
collaborations in the energy sector,  including  a coal bed
methane study, a power pooling effort, and provincial
initiatives, will be addressed in the Sustainable Energy
Committee's progress report.  Copies of the report will be
available  after the July 23 Binational Commission meeting from
Andrea Lockwood in DOE's Office of Policy and International
Affairs at 202-586-6082.     ###
</P></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
