<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Terms of Reference: Market Access</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">
<P></P>
<H2>U.S.-SOUTH AFRICA BINATIONAL COMMISSION AGRICULTURE
COMMITTEE WORKING GROUP:  MARKET ACCESS <BR>TERMS OF REFERENCE<BR></H2>
<P>PREAMBLE</P>
<BR>
<OL>
<LI> The establishment of the Market Access Working Group under
the Committee on Agriculture of the USA-RSA Binational Commission
is recognized.
</LI>
<LI> It is not the intent nor the authority of the Working Group
to negotiate specific bilateral trade issues, but will provide a
forum to facilitate discussions regarding market access issues.
</LI>
<LI> That the discussions pertaining to the above be in
recognition of the difference in the development status of the
RSA and the USA economies and the different structural character
of the two agricultural sectors.
</LI>
<LI> The Working Group will abide by and respect the commitment
of each country as signatories to the GATT and the agreement on
Sanitary and Phytosanitary issues (SPS-agreement)
</LI>
<LI> And that discussions and cooperation to the above will be
conducted with due recognition  of and in collaboration with our
Working Groups, under the Agriculture Committee and within the
Binational Commission.
</LI></OL>
<P>ARTICLE 1:  PURPOSE</P>
<P>1. To familiarize (improve knowledge of) all affected parties
in government and the private sector, including non-governmental
organizations, with the following marketing related aspects on
both sides such as:</P>
<UL>
<LI> existing tariff structures and arrangements
</LI>
<LI> the implications of regional bilateral and multilateral
arrangements
</LI>
<LI> international trade agreement and commitments (WTO)
</LI>
<LI> national programs/agencies related/affecting international
trade (promotion, subsidization or any government assistance)
</LI>
<LI> the parastatal organizations and their impact on trade
</LI>
<LI> the activities and objectives of NGO's operation
internationally and their operations related to commodity groups
and the promotion of trade
</LI></UL>
<P>2. To identify aspects which impede trading such as:</P>
<UL>
<LI> institutional and general marketing arrangements;
</LI>
<LI> financial arrangements; and
</LI>
<LI> any other non-tariff trade barriers
</LI></UL>
<P>3. To facilitate market research of mutual interest.</P>
<P>4. To investigate and facilitate affiliation between trade
related organizations and institutions  in order to improve
communication, transparency and the flow of information and
market intelligence.</P>
<P>5. To pursue the facilitation of joint ventures of mutual
benefit through which market access can be improved.</P>
<P>6. Identify training needs, requirements, and opportunities.</P>
<P>ARTICLE 2:  MEMBERSHIP</P>
<OL>
<LI> The co-conveners will be nominated by the Agriculture
Committee.
</LI>
<LI> The Working Group will consist of the co-conveners and such
individual as each co-convener may, from time to time,
respectively appoint as members of the Working Group, including
representatives from other departments, government agencies and
NGO's.  Each co-convener will keep the other informed as to the
Working Group membership.
</LI>
<LI> Each co-convener may appoint a co-vice convener to act in
its capacity as co-convener.
</LI>
<LI> Each co-convener will designate a point of contact on its
respective side for all communications and to organize
administrative staff support for the committee.
</LI>
<LI> The co-conveners may establish ad hoc working groups to
address specific issues within the scope of these terms of
reference.  These members may include non-working group
representatives.
</LI></OL>
<P>ARTICLE 3:  MEETINGS OF THE COMMITTEE</P>
<OL>
<LI> The co-conveners will mutually establish the date,
location, time, procedures and agenda of meetings.  The
co-convener resident in the country which is the venue of a
meeting, will conduct that meeting.
</LI>
<LI> For its meetings, the Working Group may use various methods
of communication when practical.  The co-conveners will mutually
decide who will conduct any such meeting.
</LI>
<LI> All recommendations or decisions of the Working Group must
have the concurrence of the co-conveners.
</LI>
<LI> The point of contact in the country which is the venue of a
meting, will be responsible for providing adequate administrative
support for the meeting.
</LI>
<LI> Each country will be responsible for the expenses of its
own officials incurred for the attendance and arrangement of
meetings of the Working Group.
</LI></OL>
<P>ARTICLE 4:  RECORD OF PROCEEDINGS</P>
<OL>
<LI> The records of each Working Group will be in the English
language.
</LI>
<LI> The co-conveners will mutually agree on the frequency and
format of progress reports to be submitted to the Agriculture
Committee.
</LI></OL>
<P>ARTICLE 5:  LIMITATIONS</P>
<OL>
<LI> The functions and activities of the Working Group will be
subject to the availability of funds and personnel.
</LI>
<LI> Nothing in these Terms of Reference is intended to create
communications that are binding under international law.
</LI></OL>
<P>ARTICLE 6:  MODIFICATION AND TERMINATION</P>
<P>1. These Terms of Reference may be modified in writing by the
two parties, and may be terminated at any time by either side
upon written notice to the other and with the approval of the
Agriculture Committee.</P>
<P>Co-convener:</P>
<P>/s/        7/22/96</P>
<P>___________________________  _______________________</P>
<P>Shirley R. Watkins      Date</P>
<P>United States Department of Agriculture</P>
<P>Deputy Assistant Secretary, Marketing and Regulatory Programs</P>
<P>Co-convener:</P>
<P>/s/        96/07/22</P>
<P>__________________________  _______________________</P>
<P>Deon Joubert       Date</P>
<P>National Department of Agriculture</P>
<P>Chief Directorate:  Economics and Marketing</P></BODY></HTML>
