<HEAD>
<TITLE>DOE news</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">
<H2>DOE NEWS FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE December 7, 1995</H2>
<P>
U.S.-SOUTH AFRICA ENERGY COLLABORATION PRODUCES TRAINING AND NEW
JOBS   	
</P>
<P>
Remarkable progress and agressive plans to encourage economic
growth and equitable distribution of electricity were reported to
Vice President Al Gore and Deputy President Thabo Mbeki by the
Sustainable Energy Committee of the U.S.-South africa Binational
Commission.  The report was presented this week in Pretoria by
committee co-chairs U.S. Secretary of Energy Hazel R. O'Leary and
South African Minister of Mineral and Energy Affairs R.W. &quot;Pik&quot;
Botha. 
</P>
<P>
The report cited several first-track projects, including policy
and regulatory framework initiatives and projects that advance
rural electrification, energy efficiency and the peaceful uses of
nuclear energy.  The report also detailed ambitious work the
committee is pursuing to build technical and scientific capacity
in South Africa. 
</P>
<P>
&quot;We were able to bring together Ambassador Andrew Young,
Chair of the Southern African Enterprise Development Fund, and
Suncorp, a majority-owned firm, resulting in the first
disbursement of $500,000 from the fund.  Since its inception
three months ago, Suncorp has demonstrated that it is a winner -
now breaking even and employing eight previously unemployed South
Africans,&quot; O'Leary said. 
</P>
<P>
&quot;Our committee has been able to seize the vision of our two
Presidents, and we are pleased that we have moved forward from
establishment of the committee to reporting on real successes
that already are impacting the lives of South Africans and
creating jobs both in South Africa and in the United States,&quot;
O'Leary added.  &quot;I congratulate my colleague, Minister
Botha, who has been instrumental in the start-up of Renewable
Energy For South Africa, beginning the path of electrification to
those in South Africa who live far from the grid.&quot; 
</P>
<P>
Realizing that capital investment is needed to fund
energy-related projects that can meet South Africa Reconstruction
and Development Program goals, the committee has focused its
efforts on building an investment-friendly regulatory framework.

</P>
<P>
In addition to the first investment by the Southern African
Enterprise Development Fund in Suncorp, a photovoltaic
manufacturing company formed in August with support from the U.S.
Department of Energy, the American company Spire and the South
African firm Renaissance, the committee reported progress on an
industrial development project in Gugulethu Township that will
result in 1,000 new jobs.- 2 - 
</P>
<P>
During its mission to South Africa last August, the Clinton
Administration's Delegaiton on Sustainable Energy and Empowerment
joined with the leaders from Gugulethu Township, which has 70
percent unemployment, to create a common vision for an economic
development project.  Those same leaders and project
representatives have met again to review a feasability study, and
all have agreed to work together toward the successful completion
of the joint effort. 
</P>
<P>
Presently, South Africa is developing a national energy policy
and regulatory framework to support its construction and
reconstruction and development program goals.  The U.S. has
played a major role in this by providing policy guidance and
regulatory expertise. 
</P>
<P>
At a recent national energy policy summit, Minister Botha praised
the expertise provided by U.S. government and private sector
experts, and he requested continued U.S. help in drafting energy
legislation to be introduced next year. 
</P>
<P>
The committee will continue to encourage the use of renewable
energy technologies to electrify 10 million rural homes, and it
will seek to develop technical and financial support for rural
electrifaction.  With that in mind, Secretary O'Leary and
Minister Botha dedicated a mobile demonstration unit that will
travel to rural areas to train majority South Africans to market
and maintain photovoltaic products, thereby allowing these
residents to control their energy future.  A $1.1 million
investment from the U.S. Agency for International Development
made this possible. 
</P>
<P>
Along with a discussion of ongoing projects, the committee set an
ambitious schedule for future collaboration, including the
development of a sustainable energy center, the formation of a
$50 million energy efficiency fund for South Africa and peaceful
uses for nuclear energy. 
</P>
<P>
The delegation led by Secretary O'Leary in August identified
capacity building as a key component for integrating the
previously-disenfranchised population into the economic growth
that is the future of South Africa.  Among results to date, 17
U.S. companies are sponsoring 50 South Africans for technical and
business training.  Additional results include 21 South Africans
trained in areas such as manufacturing and renewable energy
installation and maintenance. 
</P>
<P>
O'Leary also traveled to Secunda to observe a new training
curriculum sponsored by U.S.-based Fluor Daniel that is helping
South Africans learn home construction and pipefiting skills. 
While there, the Secretary broke ground for a new facility that
will further support this training.  In Northern Cape Province,
the Secretary showed her support for a project linking
electrification and home building with the promotion of
efficiency and environmental goals through an energy-efficient
model home with a low-smoke heater.  The home, displayed at the
Made in USA conference in South Africa in October, will be
permanently sited in Kimberley. 
</P>
<P>
Recognizing that provincial governments will play a key role in
achieving electrification and economic development goals. 
O'Leary also traveled to Free State Province following adjornment
of the commission meeting.  There she met with Premier Lekota and
other leaders to examine energy, environmental and economic
empowerment issues and areas for collaboration.
</P></BODY></HTML>
