<html><title>1st BNC Meeting</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">

<center><a name="arrival"><B>VICE PRESIDENT GORE ARRIVES IN
JOHANNESBURG</a></B></center><br>
12/4 Gore arrival statement 
<hr> 
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, South Africa -- Vice President Al Gore arrived
December 4 in
Johannesburg to attend the first full meeting of the U.S. South
Africa Binational Commission.
<P>
Following is the text of Gore's arrival statement, as delivered:
<P>
(BEGIN TEXT)
<P>
Ladies and Gentlemen, I want to thank you all for waiting out
here so late.  Tipper and I are
delighted to be back in South Africa.  I want to say how pleased
we are to return and to
continue the important work of the U.S.-South Africa Binational
Commission.
<P>
Our two nations and our two peoples, of course, have a great deal
in common.  Three decades
ago, when the great U.S. leader Robert Kennedy came to South
Africa, he described the
common threads that bind our past and, ultimately, will shape our
future.  Now on the cusp of
a new century, and some thirty years after Robert Kennedy's
visit, our nations share far more
than a common history, we share at long last common aspirations
for our futures.
<P>
We are sister nations, united by the vision of non-racial
democracy and human rights.  Of
healing and hope.  Of renewal and redemption.
<P>
We in the United States feel that we have a great deal to learn
from the New South Africa
and that is why I very much look forward to the next two days as
Deputy President Thabo
Mbeki and I work together through our Binational Commission to
map out the themes and the
means through which our relationship will grow and flourish well
into the next century.
<P>
The U.S.-South Africa Binational Commission is a pioneering
effort to forge a new
partnership in the areas of greatest mutual interest and benefit
to both peoples:  Education,
Energy, the Environment, Science and Technology, and Business. 
And, to repeat, this is a
partnership, a two-way street.  While Americans have much to
offer South Africans, clearly,
South Africa also has much to offer us.  And so we are hear to
learn from you, to share with
you and to build with you a relationship rich in meaning and
benefit to both our peoples.
<P>
I am told there is a wonderful African concept, which I wish to
invoke here, because I
believe it describes my hopes for our future together.  That
concept is "ubuntu," the notion of
community in its fullest sense.  Ubuntu is what we seek with
South Africa, and I am certain
we will find it during our meetings these next few days.
<P>
Thank you very much and thank you again for coming out this
evening.
<P>
(END TEXT)
<P>

12/05/95
GORE INVOKES PRINCIPLE OF UBUNTU UPON ARRIVAL IN SOUTH AFRICA
(FR) (Vice president signs three major agreements) 
<P>
PRETORIA, South Africa -- Vice President Gore invoked the African
principle of Ubuntu
(community) upon his arrival with Mrs. Tipper Gore at
Johannesburg International Airport
late December 4 for a series of Binational Commission meetings.
<P>
"Ubuntu is what we seek with South Africa and I am certain we
will find it during these next
few days," Gore said.  "This is a partnership, a two-way street."
<P>
Gore met December 5 with his counterpart, South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki, at
one in a series of Binational Commission (BNC) events arranged by
the two vice presidents. 
After weeks of intensive discussions, bilateral agreements have
been reached in six major
areas:  business development; environment; energy; science and
technology; human resource
development and education; and agriculture.
<P>
Within the framework of the BNC, the range of prepared agreements
serves a broad sector of
South African developmental objectives in an effort to secure and
bolster the newly
democratic southern African country.  Only Russia and Egypt enjoy
similar bilateral
agreements with the United States.  The BNC signings mark a new
era in the bilateral
relationship.
<P>
The vice presidents signed three major BNC agreements:  one,
establishing a mechanism of
exchange in science and technology; another, officially launching
a Peace Corps program in
South Africa; and a third, recognizing a wide area of bilateral
programs funded by the U.S.
Agency for International Development (USAID) in Pretoria.
<P>
Gore's visit was preceded by a number of other more specific
agreements, such as a solar
energy development project; a scholars program to bring South
African government officials
to the United States to study economics; and the establishment of
a working group to explore
the feasibility of creating a Fulbright Commission in South
Africa, which would be
sub-Saharan Africa's first.
<P>
A significant cohort of Washington leaders accompanies the vice
president on his historic
mission to the "new South Africa," to assist in the last-minute
negotiations and signing.  The
group includes Commerce Secretary Ron Brown, Energy Secretary
Hazel O'Leary, Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt, Peace Corps Director Mark Gearan, USAID
Deputy Director Carol
Lancaster, Assistant to the President for Science and Technology
John Gibbons, and Deputy
Under Secretary of Agriculture Dallas Smith.  Ambassador Andrew
Young led a business
delegation on the trip.
<P>
The vice president is joined as well by George Moose, assistant
secretary of state for African
affairs; Susan Rice, adviser to the president for African affairs
in the National Security
Council; and Leon Firth, adviser to the vice president on
national security affairs.
<P>
Gore attended a working session December 5 to outline the six
areas of future exchange and
assistance, and was the guest of honor at a lunch given by Deputy
President Mbeki for the
ranking members of the six subcommittees.
<P>
After the signing ceremony at the South African Presidential
Guest House, Gore  hosted a
reception at the residence of Princeton Lyman, the U.S.
ambassador to South Africa.
<P>
On December 6 Gore will visit a site for the training of
construction workers, near Soweto,
which is funded by USAID.  He also will make an official visit to
Gaborone, Botswana,
before stopping for an afternoon in Cape Town en route home.
<P>

12/05/95
<a name="plenary">GORE PRAISES SOUTH AFRICA'S LEADERSHIP ON
NUCLEAR NON-PROLIFERATION</a>
(FR) (Text:  Gore remarks to Binational Commission) 
<P>
PRETORIA, South Africa -- Vice President Al Gore said December 5
that South Africa's
"leadership on the issue of nuclear non-proliferation provides a
model for the rest of the
world."
<P>
In remarks December 5 to the U.S.-South Africa Binational
Commission in Pretoria, Gore
added that South Africa's "work on conflict resolution offers
practical experience of vital
importance to many nations on this planet.  South Africa's vision
of and work toward a
non-racial society offers the people of the Earth remarkable
inspiration and hope for the
future."
<P>
Following is the text of the vice president's remarks:
<P>
(BEGIN TEXT)
<P>
On behalf of all the American members of Binational Commission,
let me say how delighted
we are to be here this morning.  South Africa and the United
States are truly sister nations,
tempered by similar histories of racial intolerance and religion.

We are now bound by
common vision of a future of democracy, social justice and
prosperity for all of our people.
<P>
Our two nations and our two peoples have a great deal in common. 
On the cusp of a new
century, our nations share far more than a common history, we now
share common
aspirations for a shared future.  We are united by the vision of
non-racial democracy and
human rights, of healing and hope, renewal and redemption.
<P>
We in the United States feel that we have a great deal to learn
from the New South Africa. 
That is one reason why I very much look forward to the next two
days as we all work
together through our Binational Commission and map out the themes
and the means through
which our relationship will grow and flourish.
<P>
Our task, therefore, is to work together to develop the
institutional ties that will take our
relationship to the next level.  In order to do so, we might draw
upon the traditional wisdom
of the South African people, and your concept of "masakhane."
<P>
Our reason for being here, and what drives the work today, is to
continue building together, a
broad, deep and balanced U.S.-South African partnership.  The
U.S.-South Africa Binational
Commission is a pioneering effort towards a new partnership in
the areas of greatest mutual
interest and benefit to both peoples:  education, energy, the
environment, science and
technology and trade and investment.  To repeat, this is a
partnership, a two-way street. 
While Americans believe that we have much to offer South Africa,
we also know that South
Africa has much to offer us.
<P>
Clearly South Africa has a tremendous amount to offer the United
States and the entire world. 
Your leadership on the issue of nuclear non-proliferation
provides a model for the rest of the
world.  Your work on conflict resolution offers practical
experience of vital importance to
many nations on this planet.
<P>
South Africa's vision of and work toward a non-racial society
offers the people of the Earth
remarkable inspiration and hope for the future.
<P>
So we are here to learn from you, to share with you and to build
with you a relationship rich
in meaning and benefit to both our peoples.  In this spirit let
us recommit ourselves today to
constructing a true and lasting partnership -- a partnership
which stands before the world, as a
shining example of the ideals and visions uniting our two great
nations.
<P>
There is a wonderful African concept that I was told of which I'm
given to believe describes
the one way of expressing our goals for our future together:  the
concept of "ubuntu," the
notion of community in its fullest sense.  That is what we seek
with South Africa.  In order
to achieve it we must match the expressions of hope and the
shared aspirations which we
celebrate in our partnership with the practical hard work of
completing the details of a
partnership that can be productive in a series of different
areas.
<P>
If we are diligent and if we work together to forge the
partnership in a most productive way,
I am certain now that we will succeed.  On behalf of my
colleagues that have travelled here
from the United States I want to say again how grateful we are
for your hospitality and how
hopeful we are about the work that begins this morning.
<P>
(END TEXT)
<P>

12/06/95
<a name="jointpc">GORE, MBEKI HOLD JOINT PRESS CONFERENCE</a>
(FR) (Transcript:  12/5 discussion of bilateral issues) 
<P>
PRETORIA -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore and South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki
held a joint news conference December 5, touching on a range of
issues of bilateral interest --
from Nigeria to Iran to the need for binational commissions.
<P>
Gore was in South Africa to attend the first full meeting of the
U.S.-South Africa Binational
Commission.
<P>
Following is transcript of that joint news conference:
<P>
(BEGIN TRANSCRIPT)
<P>
Q:  Did you discuss issues of bilateral difference, including
Armscor, Cuba and Iran?
<P>
MBEKI:  We did not discuss Cuba.  We are in a discussion about
the Armscor case.  Those
discussions are continuing between the lawyers on both sides.  We
still proceed on both sides
on the basis that it is necessary to find a solution to this
problem, so those discussions are
continuing and negotiations are taking place in the United
States.  We did not discuss the
question of Iran, except in the instance that the vice president
indicated the general
framework of the United States' policy towards Iran.  This was to
indicate to us what the
positions of the United States government are with regard to this
question.
<P>
GORE:  I would just add briefly that the Armscor case is an issue
on which our two
governments have been working in an effort to find a satisfactory
solution.  It's an important
and complex issue in that it involves matters of both law and
policy.  We are hopeful that we
will be able to reach a mutually acceptable settlement of the
issue soon.  We did discuss Iran,
as the deputy president mentioned, and I also discussed Iran with
President Mandela.
<P>
Q:  Don't you also disagree over policy toward Nigeria?
<P>
GORE:  To the contrary, I do not see any significant difference
between the United States
and South Africa where our policies toward Nigeria are concerned.

Indeed, our two countries
are working hand in hand as the two co-sponsors of the resolution
now pending in the United
Nations to condemn the recent execution of Ken Saro-Wiwa and
other members of the
Ogonis -- and the lack of due process and representation and
self-government in Nigeria.  We
are agreed that an effective response must be multilateral in
order to work.  And we have
agreed to work together in search of the best and most effective
way to follow what President
Mandela has described as a two-track approach by putting pressure
on Nigeria in response to
its unacceptable activities, while at the same time searching for
ways to engage Nigeria in a
dialogue that might pull them back onto a proper path of
democracy and development.  Any
approach, in order to work, must be multilateral, and we are
considering a variety of options. 
We do believe that any option that is effective must be
multilateral, and I don't think that
there is disagreement on that score between our two countries.
<P>
Q:  (inaudible)
<P>
MBEKI:  The vice president explained to us U.S. government policy
towards Iran.  This was
not with a view to discussing this matter that we will reach a
common position.  We must, of
course, report the discussion that we had with the vice president
which he was saying he had
with the president, we must report it to the rest of the
government.  I think any discussion
that will take place within the S.A. government would only take
place at that point.  You
know the actual situation on those relations between South Africa
and Iran.  As I say, we
must take forward to the rest of the government the positions
which the vice president
explained.
<P>
Q:  Isn't there a policy inconsistency in that the United States
wants South Africa to practice
an oil boycott against Iran, a position which South Africa
rejects?  Yet, now South Africa is
asking the United States to boycott Nigerian oil?
<P>
MBEKI:  The U.S. recognizes the fact that, for the bulk of our
crude oil, they know that it
comes from Iran.  It's an old relationship, and as I was saying,
what would happen in terms
of any policy discussion would have to be on the basis of a
report that we still have to give
to the government.  Consistencies or inconsistencies in the
policies of the U.S. government,
that I can't answer for.
<P>
GORE:  Our policy is consistent, in both cases we believe that
the behavior of the
governments in question is unacceptable.  In the case of Iran,
that government has gone far
beyond a disregard for the rights of its own citizens, and the
violation of commonly accepted
principles of due process and human rights and has added the sin
of state-sponsored terrorism. 
There can be no doubt that this activity continues and is
unacceptable in the world
community, and therefore quite strong measures are warranted. 
The experience with respect
to Iran's oil certainly is consistent with our stated view that,
in order to be effective, an
embargo has to be multilateral and other sanctions have to be
multilateral.  And so we are
joining with South Africa in seeking condemnation of these
unacceptable activities in Nigeria
and working with Nigeria to add to that U.N. resolution a
possible coordinated policy with
other nations that will put economic and other pressure on
Nigeria.  At the same time, we feel
an obligation to present to our friends in the world the
unassailable evidence that documents
the sponsoring of terrorism by Iran, an activity, again let me
say, that is unacceptable in the
civilized world.
<P>
Q:  Mr. Vice President, how would you comment on the fact that
three countries, South
Africa, the United States and Russia, have established binational
commissions between each
other?  Is this, in fact, a strategic alliance for a new world?
<P>
GORE:  Let me explain why the United States of America has felt
that it is important to
establish a Binational Commission with South Africa and with
Russia.  What, you might ask,
what do these two nations have in common in our eyes?  Both are
great nations, but beyond
that we feel that the transition under way in Russia, from
communism to a free-market
democracy, is a transition vitally important to the future of
Eurasia and the entire world.  If
Russia can successfully complete that transition the future of
the entire world will look a lot
brighter.  Democracies and free markets everywhere will be
stronger.  Similarly, just as the
world used to face a threat from communism and the Cold War, the
world faced and still
faces a threat from ethnic violence and hatred from Bosnia to
Rwanda to Cambodia, in places
all around the world.  And the entire world has been inspired by
the process of reconciliation
and renewal here in the new South Africa.  Just recently, shortly
before President Clinton's
trip to Northern Ireland and Ireland, Deputy President Mbeki's
colleague in the Government
of National Unity, Second Deputy President de Klerk, was able to
describe to the Irish people
what reconciliation is all about, based on the S.A. experience. 
This is inspiring to peoples
who are attempting to transcend long-standing conflicts.  In the
world of the future, if peoples
all across our planet are able to point to South Africa and say
to those who counsel violence,
'No, that's the wrong way -- just look at the alternative that
has been pioneered successfully
by the new South Africa'; with that kind of inspiration, the
world has a much better chance to
build a bright future.  We in the United States of America want
to be a good partner to South
Africa and a strong friend to all the peoples of South Africa in
doing everything we can to
learn from their experience and to be a part of their successful
transition, just as we do in
Russia.
<P>
MBEKI:  Let me just add to that, that of course you are aware
that the United States, the
people of the United States in particular, played a very
important role in the struggle for
liberation here.  Even as the process of change was taking place
in this country, there was a
general sentiment around the United States that millions of
people that were engaged with us
to end the system of apartheid wanted to continue that
cooperation.  They wanted to see this
victory that they fought for produce the kind of society which
you all want.  So I think it was
quite natural for the United States government, reflecting that
opinion within the United
States, to say let's seek to engage each other in the manner that
we are engaging each other. 
I don't think it's got anything to do with strategic alliances
which seek to dominate the world
or do something like that.  It arises out of a common concern, as
the vice president has just
said, to see in what ways we can continue that cooperation to the
mutual benefit of both
countries.
<P>
GORE AND MBEKI:  Thank you very much.
<P>
(END TRANSCRIPT)

<P>
12/06/95
<a name="ubttp">GORE:  SOUTH AFRICA HAS CHANCE TO BE 'BEACON OF
HOPE'</a>
(FR) (Text:  12/6 Gore excerpts at training center) (700)
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South Africa has an opportunity to become a
"beacon of hope" to
people around the world, Vice President Al Gore told a South
African audience December 6.
<P>
In remarks at the Union Building Trades Training Program, Gore
said such a beacon is
important, "especially in countries where people of different
ethnic backgrounds are tempted
to blame their problems on each other, whether it's in Bosnia or
Rwanda or Chechnya or
Cambodia."
<P>
Gore added that "every day that the new South Africa continues
moving forward and building
its future is a day when the rest of the world has more hope; a
day when people all over this
planet have more reasons to remain determined to build a bright
future."
<P>
Gore was in South Africa to attend the first full meeting of the
U.S.-South African Binational
Commission.
<P>
Following are excerpts of Gore's statement:
<P>
(BEGIN EXCERPTS)
<P>
Thank you very much.  I'd like to begin by saying how impressed I
am with the training
that's going on here and with the approach that's being taken....
<P>
Let me say what's on my heart here.  Nelson Mandela has brought
new hope to South Africa. 
He has also brought a program of building, reconstruction and
development.  In order for that
program to work the people have to have the skills to get the
jobs rebuilding South Africa. 
You talked about people living in shacks; on the way here I saw
with my own eyes what
visitors to this country always see when they venture outside of
the bright, shining cities.  I
saw people living in desperate conditions.  There's a housing
crisis in South Africa, as
everyone knows.  And, as new businesses are springing up, they
too must be built with brick
and mortar and the people who build these houses and businesses
need the skills to do the
job.
<P>
The labor movement in South Africa is surmounting divisions of
the past and joining in
partnership to create this training center.  My country, the
United States of America, is very
proud to be a partner with South Africa in your effort to build a
bright future.  USAID, the
AFL-CIO, the bricklayers' union, which is a very big part of this
exercise, and others, are all
forming a partnership in investing hope in the future of South
Africa.  Your skills will be the
key ingredient to making the dream that you have a reality.
<P>
The United States, and the people of the United States, have
invested a great deal of hope in
South Africa also.  We know something about hope in the world
because the United States of
America is very proud that, for quite a long time, people in
other parts of the world who have
desired freedom have sometimes taken a measure of hope from the
success of the United
States, where people are free.  And now South Africa has an
opportunity to also become a
beacon of hope to people around the world, especially in
countries where people of different
ethnic backgrounds are tempted to blame their problems on each
other, whether it's in Bosnia
or Rwanda or Chechnya or Cambodia.
<P>
Every day that the new South Africa continues moving forward and
building its future is a
day when the rest of the world has more hope; a day when people
all over this planet have
more reasons to remain determined to build a bright future.  So
we want to be a partner to
you in that exercise.  That's why this project is important to
us.  That's why, along with
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki yesterday, I signed a number of
agreements that will make
possible other partnerships like this one.  Why, for example, we
signed a major Peace Corps
agreement that will bring large numbers of Peace Corps volunteers
into South Africa from the
United States.  We're anxious to see you succeed.  Just as you
are putting the bricks one on
top of another, we want to put our partnerships and projects one
on top of another to build
the houses in your future.
<P>
Thank you very much.
<P>
(END EXCERPTS)
NNNN
<P>
12/06/95
<a name="prpeace">SOUTH AFRICA AND PEACE CORPS SIGN HISTORIC
AGREEMENT</a>
(Text:  12/5 White House news release) (310)
<P>
PRETORIA -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore and South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki
signed an agreement December 5 allowing the Peace Corps to work
in South Africa.
<P>
Gore was in South Africa attending the first full meeting of the
U.S.-South Africa Binational
Commission.
<P>
Following is a news release on the signing issued by the White
House:
<P>
(BEGIN TEXT)
<P>
Pretoria, South Africa, Dec. 5 -- Vice President Al Gore and
South African Deputy President
Thabo Mbeki today signed an agreement that will send Peace Corps
volunteers to South
Africa.  The signing was a follow-up to plans announced last
October by President Clinton
and South African President Nelson Mandela during a ceremony at
the White House.
<P>
Peace Corps Director Mark Gearan joined Vice President Gore and
Deputy President Mbeki
for the signing, which took place at the President's Guest House
in Pretoria.  While in South
Africa, Gearan will meet with government officials, volunteer
groups and non-governmental
organizations about possible activities for Peace Corps
volunteers.
<P>
"This is a partnership of historic significance," said Gearan. 
"Sending volunteers to South
Africa is a very important step for the Peace Corps and for the
people of the United States. 
By living and working at the grassroots level, Peace Corps
volunteers can help further
strengthen the personal ties between Americans and South
Africans.
<P>
South Africa represents the 130th country Peace Corps has entered
in its 34-year history. 
Currently more than 2,500 Peace Corps volunteers are working in
33 African countries. 
Since 1961, over 140,000 volunteers have served in all corners of
the world.  Over 7,200
volunteers, a twenty-year high, serve in 95 countries in such
areas as small business
development, environment, education, health and nutrition, and
agriculture.
<P>
(END TEXT)
NNNN
<P>
12/06/95
<a name="gorepc">GORE ANNOUNCES SIXTH COMPONENT OF BINATIONAL
COMMISSION</a>
(FR) (Text:  12/5 Gore press conf. statement) (1150)
<P>
PRETORIA -- A sixth "crucial" committee on agriculture has been
added to the U.S.-South
Africa Binational Commission, Vice President Al Gore announced
December 5.
<P>
Appearing at a joint press conference with South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki,
Gore paid special tribute to the commission, which seeks to
foster and enhance the bilateral
relationship in five other critical areas:
human resources development and education; energy; conservation
and environment; science
and technology; and business development.
<P>
"I am very proud of the work that we have done here today," the
vice president told his
audience in Pretoria, where he attended the first full meeting of
the commission in South
Africa.
<P>
"We have listened and we have learned.  In a very real way this
Binational Commission pays
homage to the concepts of 'ubuntu,' for the special sense of
community which links South
Africa and the United States, 'masakhane' for our resolve to
build together and 'khotla' for our
determination to work through the problems that we may
encounter," he stressed.
<P>
Following is Vice President Gore's opening statement at the press
conference:
<P>
(BEGIN GORE TEXT)
<P>
Thank you very much, Mr. Deputy President, ladies and gentlemen,
members of the Cabinets
of both countries, distinguished officials.  My wife Tipper and I
are very pleased to be back
here in South Africa and today, because of Deputy President Mbeki
and his colleagues on the
South African side, and the work of the Commission, today has
been a wonderful moment of
hope and progress for the people of South Africa and the United
States.
<P>
We have worked hard today and a remarkable volume of work has
been accomplished since
my friend Deputy President Mbeki and I first discussed the
U.S.-South Africa Binational
Commission in Washington just last March.  We have engaged the
talents of our very best
people in both countries to work together in five critical areas
of our relationship:  human
resources development and education; energy; conservation and
environment; science and
technology; and business development.
<P>
Today I am pleased to join Deputy President Mbeki in announcing
that we have added a sixth
crucial component to that list:  an agriculture committee.  The
Deputy President and I have
charged each of these six committees, which are led by Cabinet
secretaries, ministers and
specialists of equivalent stature, to develop practical, concrete
programs through which both
of our peoples will benefit.  After today, we can safely say that
the work is well under way. 
We have learned here today that both countries have enormous
pools of talent, expertise and
experience to share with one another.  This is a two-way
relationship in which both sides
stand to learn and to gain.
<P>
Let me cite a few of the many examples.  First of all, Ron Brown
led another successful
meeting of the U.S.-South Africa Business Development Committee. 
Under the auspices of
the BDC, a joint statement on tourism was signed to foster
bilateral cooperation in this
important area.  The government-to-government portion of the
bilateral business relationship,
the Trade and Investment Committee, agreed on a joint communique
to advance the bilateral
commercial agenda.
<P>
The Energy Development Committee, under the leadership on our
side of Secretary Hazel
O'Leary, signed a memorandum of understanding on the reduction of
greenhouse gases and
emissions, and an energy implementing agreement under the
Environment, Science and
Technology agreement which the Deputy President and I signed. 
The committee has made
tremendous progress in the three months since Secretary O'Leary
last visited.
<P>
The Science and Technology Committee co-chaired on the U.S. side
by Dr. Jack Gibbons
signed a cooperative program on Agricultural Science and
Technology.  One of the
committee's pilot projects has to do with science education and,
for example, provides a
communications link to South African schoolchildren with an
African-American astronaut,
Winston Scott.
<P>
The Human Resources Development and Education Committee,
co-chaired on our side by
Brian Atwood, represented today by Carol Lancaster, concluded
several cooperative
agreements, including the establishment of a Fulbright Commission
[and] a memorandum of
understanding to support fifty South Africans on the Nelson
Mandela Economic Scholarships
to conduct graduate study in economics in the United States.
<P>
The Conservation, Environment and Water Committee has initiated a
variety of exchanges as
well as joint research and management programs in
desertification, water conservation,
climate change, environmental management and numerous other
areas.
<P>
These are but a sample of the score of achievements that we are
to realize through this
process.  Besides producing real results in practical terms, this
Binational Commission will
also accelerate the growth and strength of our overall bilateral
relationship.  We are working
together to build together a stable, long-term partnership that
will benefit both countries while
accommodating the remarkable political and economic changes afoot
in the world.
<P>
Already, I am happy to say, America's private sector has become
an active participant in
South Africa's economic development.  As was announced today,
Ford's South Africa plant
will soon begin exporting automobile engines to Europe, while
creating jobs for South
Africans and strengthening both our economies.  South African
Airways' purchase of Boeing
aircraft will ensure its continued ability to offer the most
modern and efficient air service
available anywhere.
<P>
I am very proud of the work that we have done here today.  We
have listened and we have
learned.  In a very real way this Binational Commission pays
homage to the concepts of
"ubuntu," for the special sense of community which links South
Africa and the United States,
"masakhane" for our resolve to build together and "khotla" for
our determination to work
through the problems that we may encounter.
<P>
I was also very pleased to have the opportunity to meet and talk
with President Mandela this
morning.  I've passed on to him President Clinton's best wishes. 
We've had an extensive
discussion of matters of common concern.  I will also have a
meeting with Deputy President
De Klerk immediately after this press conference and tomorrow I
am looking forward to
visiting Lenasia township and Cape Town.  I just wish that I
could spend more time in this
beautiful country, but as the deputy president indicated I will
have to return very quickly for
our discussions on Bosnia in the United States Senate, and our
discussion with the Congress
on the budget.
<P>
I have told the deputy president that South Africa's warm welcome
and gracious hospitality
will be difficult to match, but my colleagues and I are going to
try, and thus have invited our
colleagues on the Binational Commission to meet again in
Washington, again in summer, but
this time our summer.  I'd like to close by thanking you again,
Mr. Deputy President and all
of your colleagues, for the hospitality and friendship and for
the wonderful practical start that
we have made with our Binational Commission.  Thank you very
much.
<P>
(END GORE TEXT)

<P>
12/06/95
<a name="tijoint">U.S., SOUTH AFRICA ADVANCE COMMERCIAL
AGENDA</a>
(FR) (Text: 12/5 joint communique) (500)
<P>
PRETORIA -- Vice President Al Gore and South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki on
December 5 approved a joint communique by the U.S.-South Africa
Binational Commission
Trade and Investment Committee, noting that the committee "was
able to significantly
advance" the two nations' commercial agenda.
<P>
The communique underscored "both sides' view that continued
forthright and constructive
government-to-government discussions are the key to resolving
bilateral impediments to the
expansion of the commercial relationship."  U.S. Secretary of
Commerce Ron Brown and
South African Minister of Trade Trevor Manuel chaired the
committee.
<P>
Gore was in South Africa to attend the first full meeting of the
Binational Commission.
<P>
Following is the text of the joint communique:
<P>
(BEGIN TEXT)
<P>
The Trade and Investment Committee of the Binational Commission
was able to significantly
advance the bilateral commercial agenda during its two days of
discussions in Pretoria,
underscoring both sides' view that continued forthright and
constructive government to
government discussions are the key to resolving bilateral
impediments to the expansion of the
commercial relationship.
<P>
The two sides proposed to advance the date for the meeting of the
code share working group
so that the negotiation of the bilateral air services agreement
negotiations can be resumed;
complete the information exchange regarding the bilateral
investment treaty; and expressed a
desire for the final round of the tax treaty negotiations to be
scheduled as rapidly as
practicable.
<P>
The governments of the United States and South Africa recommit to
full and early
implementation of the agreement on trade-related aspects of
intellectual property rights (trips)
and to all other international obligations relating to
intellectual property protection to which
they are signatories, including but not limited to the Paris
Convention for the protection of
industrial property (Paris convention).  In addition, we mutually
agree that the definition of
"special circumstance" will be clarified so as not to be
inconsistent with companies'
compliance with anti-apartheid laws.
<P>
Both sides are encouraged by the ambitious and creative
initiatives launched by the private
sector U.S.-S.A. Business Development Committee (BDC).  The
insights and dynamism of
these 40-some corporate executives testify to the uniqueness of
the U.S.-S.A. relationship.
<P>
The S.A. and U.S. governments are committed to their respective
BDC private sectors'
establishing a Technical Assistance Center in South Africa to
promote linkages between U.S.
and S.A. companies with specific emphasis on South African
companies....  Also, the two
governments committed to the private sectors' exploring the
establishing of a similar center in
the United States dedicated to promoting South African trade and
investment in the United
States.
<P>
The BDC will also undertake a Law in Diversity Program to open up
opportunities in the
commercial law field for historically disadvantaged attorneys in
South Africa.
<P>
Under the auspices of the BDC, a joint statement on tourism was
signed to foster bilateral
cooperation on this sector, which offers significant opportunity
for economic growth and job
creation.
<P>
(END TEXT)

<P>
12/06/95
<a name="hrdestate">BILATERAL COMMISSION FOCUSES ON HUMAN
RESOURCES</a>
(Text:  12/5 statement from Human Resources Committee) (350)
<P>
PRETORIA -- The Human Resources Development and Education
Committee of the
U.S.-South Africa Binational Commission issued the following
statement following meetings
December 5:
<P>
(BEGIN TEXT)
<P>
The Human Resources Development and Education Committee of the
U.S.-South Africa
Binational Commission headed by Vice President Al Gore and South
African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki met December 5 to consider bilateral
initiatives in areas including
government cooperation and academic and professional development
changes.
<P>
The Human Resources Development and Education Committee is
co-chaired by the South
African Minister of Education, Professor Sibusiso Bengu, and J.
Brian Atwood, Administrator
of the U.S. Agency for International Development. Dr. Joseph
Duffey, Director of the U.S.
Information Agency and Mr. Tito Mboweni, South African Minister
of Labor, serve as deputy
co-chairpersons. U.S. membership also includes the Corporation
for National Service and the
Departments of Agriculture, Labor, Education and State. The South
African section includes
participation from ten other ministries.
<P>
The Committee established a $3 million Youth Development Program
to increase the skills,
employability and civic participation of marginalized young South
Africans. The initiative
will fund provision of job skills training, internships and
business-oriented training through a
combination of public and private sector support.
<P>
The Committee signed a Declaration of Intent to pursue the
establishment of a bilateral
academic and professional exchange programs funded by the South
African Ministry of
Education, the U.S. Information Agency and private monies.
<P>
The Committee also signed a Memorandum of Understanding to
initiate the Mandela
Economic Scholars Program to provide post-graduate economic
training up to the doctoral
level for up to 50 promising disadvantaged South Africans at
selected U.S. universities.
Training recipients will, in return, agree to work in the South
African public sector in policy
formulation and analysis positions.
<P>
The December 5 meeting reviewed progress made under the Cochran
Fellowship Program.
Conducted by the U.S. Foreign Agricultural Service, the program
provides short-term
agricultural training in the United States.
<P>
(END TEXT)


<P>
