<TITLE>Partial inventory </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">
<H2>Partial Inventory of U.S. Government-sponsored Fellowship
and Training Opportunities in Science and Technology Prepared by
the Human Resources Development Working Group of the U.S.-South
Africa Binational Commission Science and Technology Committee
July 11, 1996</H2>
<P>National Science Foundation  (NSF)
</P>
<P>
NSF considers proposals submitted by individuals or groups for
support in most fields of science and engineering.  A major
exception is bioscience research with disease-related goals. 
Technical assistance projects also are not supported.  NSF funds
research and education through grants and contracts to university
and other research institutions in the United States.  Although
the principal investigator on an NSF award must be a US citizen
or permanent resident, foreign scientists may participate in the
grant activities through collaborative arrangements with US
investigators. 
</P>
<P>The international activities of the National Science
Foundation extend throughout the world, from the advanced
technological nations to the developing countries.  With South
Africa during the past two years, NSF has supported collaborative
projects in the fields of biology, environmental sciences, polar
science, earth sciences, physics, engineering, and the social
sciences.  The Division of International Programs (INT) has the
responsibility within NSF for catalyzing international research
partnerships, especially those that involve investigators in the
early stages of their careers.  Several NSF officials have
visited South Africa recently, among them a group from the
Engineering Directorate, which visited major university and
training centers, including some historically disadvantaged
institutions, to discuss areas and opportunities for future
collaboration in engineering.  Areas of specific interest were
manufacturing, environmental technology, materials, and civil
infrastructure. 
</P>
<P>Scientists and engineers in South Africa wishing to organize
workshops or enter into cooperative research arrangments with US
investigators should contact their counterparts in the United
States, who may then submit proposals to NSF.  For the most part,
NSF grants for cooperative research with South African scientists
would cover the costs of the travel of the US researchers to
South Africa and their living expenses there.  The costs for the
South African researchers in the United States must be provided
by an organization in that country.  </P>
<P>U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID)
</P>
<P> Participant training in the United States is a major
activity in the portfolio of USAID/South Africa in support of the
Mission's Strategic Objectives.  The vast majority of participant
are here for short-term programs -- short courses, workshops, or
study tours.  Of the academic participants, most are trained at
the master's degree level, with a small number of bachelor's and
Ph.D.s.   
</P>
<P>According to information in the Human Capacity Development
Center's database, as of March 1 approximately 417 participants
were in programs in the U.S. during FY 1995.  Of these, about 126
were in various science and technology fields, since as
engineering (chemical, mechanical, civil, petroleum), computer
science, chemistry, botany, plant pathology, entomology,
forestry, psychology, mathematics, and statistics, among others. 
 
</P>
<P>Selection of participants for training is done by the USAID
Mission and its NGO and government partners.  They set the
criteria to insure that all training serves the Mission's
programmatic objectives.   
</P>
<P>For more information: contact the Mission's Human Resources
Development Officer.      
</P>
<P>National Institutes of Health (NIH) 
</P>
<P>The International Research Fellowship (IRF) Program  	</P>
<P> This program provides opportunities for developing country
postdoctoral biomedical or behavioral scientists, in the
formative stages of their careers (less than ten years beyond the
doctorate), to extend their research experience to a laboratory
in the United States.  These fellowships help forge relationships
between U.S. and foreign scientists to study health problems of
mutual interest.  Fellowships are awarded for twelve to
twenty-four months, and stipends are dependent upon experience.  

</P>
<P>Applicants must have a U.S. sponsor and submit a proposal to
the chairman of the Nominating Committee, the President of the
South Africa Medical Research Council.  Up to six nominees may be
submitted to the FIC by each Nominating Committee each year for
consideration.  Awards are made on the basis of scientific merit,
with no quota established for specific countries or regions. 
Information and application materials are available through the
IRF Nominating Committee Chairman listed below.  	</P>
<P>Professor O.W. Prozesky 	President, South Africa Medical
Research Council 	 	P.O. Box 19070 	70 Tygerberg 7505 	Fax:
021-938-0201	 	Telephone: 921-938-0911  
</P>
<P>The Fogarty International Research Collaboration Award
(FIRCA)  
</P>
<P>This award provides U.S. biomedical scientists with active
NIH cancer-related grants the opportunity to compete for small
grants to establish research cooperation with colleagues in
African countries.  These small grants will provide funds to the
foreign collaborator, through the U.S. grantee institution, for
equipment and supplies at his/ her home institution, and for
travel expenses for both the U.S. Principal Investigator and the
foreign collaborator.  Applicants must request support to conduct
research not already being supported by the U.S. investigator's
parent grant; however, the research proposal must be an extension
of, or related to the currently funded research project.  The
minimum grant project period will be for one year; the maximum
will be for three, dependent on the number of years remaining on
the U.S. Principal Investigator's parent grant.   Requests may be
made up to a limit of  $20,000 per year for up to three years in
direct costs.  For further information contact: 
</P>
<P>	Division of International Training and Research  	Fogarty
International Center, NIH 	Building 31, Room B2C39 	31 Center
Drive, MSC 2220 	Bethesda, MD  20892-2220 	Telephone:  (301)
496-1653 	Facsimile:  (301) 402-0779   
</P>
<P>The AIDS International Training and Research Programs  
</P>
<P>These programs were created to increase the expertise of both
U.S. and foreign scientists in epidemiology related to AIDS and
the use of epidemiology in clinical trials and prevention
research.  These training programs can lead to the M.S. or Ph.D.
degree for foreign scientists.  Short term comprehensive courses
and training in laboratory research techniques related to AIDS
are available to foreign health professionals.  Additionally,
practical training related to AIDS can be conducted in the
participating foreign countries.
</P>
<P> 	I. International Training Grants in Epidemiology Related to
AIDS  are awarded to U.S. institutions with strong AIDS research
programs and international experience.  Five types of training
for foreign scientists from participating developing countries
are available through this program:   	1) training in
epidemiological concepts, methods, field studies, and research
related to 	AIDS that will lead to the M.S. or Ph.D. degree for
individuals with previous field research experience. 	2) training
in epidemiological field studies and research related to AIDS
that will  lead to the M.S. degree for individuals without prior
field research experience. 	3) short-term comprehensive courses
in epidemiology with an emphasis on AIDS,  for health
professionals. 	4) training in laboratory procedures and research
techniques related to AIDS for  individuals with the M.S. or
Ph.D. degree. 	5) practical and applied short-term training
related to AIDS conducted in the foreign  country for
professionals, technicians and allied health professionals.   
</P>
<P>	II. International Postdoctoral Research and Training in
AIDS.   This FIC program is available to U.S. and foreign
scientists to expand epidemiological skills in AIDS diagnosis,
prevention, and treatment.  Priority is given to AIDS researchers
from developing countries, and research is conducted both in the
U.S. and other countries.  For more information, scientists in
South Africa should contact the program director listed below:  
</P>
<P>	Dr. Zena Stein 		Professor Emeritus Public Health 		Columbia
University 		600 West 168th Street 		New York, NY  10032  	</P>
<P>III.  HIV, AIDS and Related Illnesses Collaboration Awards 
provides U.S. biomedical scientists with active NIH
cancer-related grants the opportunity to compete for small grants
to establish research cooperation in HIV, AIDS and related
illnesses with colleagues in African countries.  These small
grants are modeled upon the FIRCA described above, and for more
information, scientists should contact the FIC Division of
International Training and Research.   
</P>
<P>The NIH Visiting Program      
</P>
<P>This program provides opportunities for biomedical
researchers at all levels of their careers to participate in the
varied research activities of the NIH.  Through this program,
scientists are invited to NIH to conduct collaborative research
in their medical specialties.  
</P>
<P>There are three categories of Visiting Program participants:
Visiting Fellows - scientists with doctoral degrees and three
years or less of relevant experience, Visiting Associates -
scientists with three to six years of postdoctoral research
experience; Visiting Scientists - scientists with six or more
years of postdoctoral research experience. 
</P>
<P>Visiting Fellows are normally appointed for two years,
although one-year awards will be considered, and the fellowship
period may not exceed three years.  All Visiting Program
participants must be proficient in the use and understanding of
both written and spoken English. 
</P>
<P>An award or appointment to the Visiting Program must be
requested by a senior scientist in one of NIH's intramural
laboratories.  The senior scientist serves as the participants'
sponsor during the period of award or appointment. 
</P>
<P>Individuals interested in a Visiting Program fellowship award
or appointment should write to NIH senior scientists working in
their area of expertise, enclosing a resume and brief description
of his/her particular research area.  Information about research
being conducted by NIH scientists and their names may be obtained
from the NIH Scientific Directory and Annual Biography which is
published each year by the NIH and available in may libraries
throughout the world.  Copies may be requested from:  	</P>
<P>Public Inquiries 	Office of Communications 	National
Institutes of Health 	Building 31, Room 2B03 	31 Center Drive
	Bethesda, Maryland  20892    
</P>
<P>Research Grant  The National Institutes of Health will accept
Research Grant applications from South African scientists who
wish to compete with scientists from the U.S. and other
countries, consistent with established NIH peer review
procedures.  South African scientists may also participate in NIH
research grants as foreign components in a domestic grant
submitted to the NIH by an investigator at a U.S. institution. 
Applications for these domestic grants with foreign components
compete on an equal basis with other grant applications received
by the NIH from U.S. and foreign scientists.   </P>
<P>The Senior International Fellowship (SIF) Program 
</P>
<P>This program  provides established U.S. scientists
opportunities to conduct collaborative research abroad.  On
invitation from a foreign institution, U.S. scientists who
compete for this award may participate in research or research
training in the foreign country.  The applicant must: 1) hold a
doctoral degree in one of the biomedical or health sciences,  	2)
have 5 years or more of postdoctoral experience,  	3) have
professional experience in one of the biomedical, behavioral, or
health sciences for at least 2 of the last 4 years, 4) hold a
full time appointment on the staff of the U.S. nominating
institution, which must be a non-Federal, public or private
not-for-profit research, clinical, or educational institution, 
5) be invited by a not- for-profit foreign institution, 6) not
have received more than one Senior International Fellowship
previously, and  	7) not be employed by  the Federal Government.

</P>
<P>The fellowship award period is for a total of 3 to 12 months,
which may be divided into 3 month minimum terms each year for
three years.  The fellowship provides a stipend of $1,250 per
month or a maximum of $15,000 per year, a foreign living
allowance of $1,250 per month or a maximum of $15,000 per year,
economy class round-trip air travel for the fellow only, and host
institutional allowance of up to $6,000 per year or a prorated
allowance for a shorter time.  For further information contact
the FIC Division of International Training and Research.  
</P>
<P>The International Neurosciences Fellowship Program 
</P>
<P>This program provides opportunities for junior or mid- career
health professionals and scientists in the neurosciences to
enhance their skills in a research setting in the United States. 
The objective of the fellowship program is to prepare the
candidates for leadership positions in research, academic, and
public health institutions.  Five fellowships are available each
year.  The Fogarty International Center administers the program
in collaboration with the National Institute of Neurological
Disorders and Stroke, and the World Health Organization. 
</P>
<P>Prospective candidates who meet the eligibility requirements
(earned doctorate degree; a research plan; a sponsor in the
United States; assurance from the home country institution that
there is a position for the applicant after the tenure of the
fellowship; and proficiency in spoken English) are invited to
submit a three-page pre-application which includes:   (1) the
title of the application;  (2) a proposed research plan;   (3) a
statement about how the knowledge will be used upon return to the
home institution.  The home institution must submit a statement
that the applicant will be employed upon completion of the
fellowship.   </P>
<P> The preapplication should be submitted to WHO, Geneva: 
</P>
<P>	Neurosciences Programme 	Division of Mental Health
	Headquarters 	World Health Organization 	1211 Geneva 27
	Switzerland  
</P>
<P>The National Cancer Institute (NCI) Oncology Research Faculty
Development Program
</P>
<P> This program supports cancer researchers who have a minimum
of three years of postdoctoral cancer research experience.  The
program provides advanced research and research training at
laboratories of the NCI or U.S. laboratories of NCI grantees for
a minimum of one year, which can be renewed up to three times for
a period of one year each.  Awardees receive an annual tax- free
subsistence allowance of $22,500 the first year, $23,500 the
second year, $24,500 the third year and $25,500 the fourth year
is provided.  The program also provides for the awardee's and
his/her dependent's health insurance.      
</P>
<P>The NCI Short-Term Scientist Exchange Program   This
exchange, sponsored by the Office of International Affairs (OIA),
National Cancer Institute (NCI) promotes collaborative research
between established U.S. and foreign scientists by supporting, in
part, exchange visits of U.S. cancer researchers to foreign
laboratories, or foreign cancer researchers to U.S. laboratories.
 The visits may be from one week to six months in duration.  For
further information on NCI programs contact: 
</P>
<P>	Dr. Federico Welsch 	Director, Office of International
Affairs  	National Cancer Institute, NIH 	Bethesda, MD  20892   
	Telephone:  (301) 496-4761   	Facsimile:  (301) 480-8208  
</P>
<P>For more information: 
</P>
<P>For information on other organizations which provide research
grants and fellowships in the biomedical and behavioral sciences,
individuals may write to the Fogarty International Center to
receive a copy of the Directory of International Grants and
Fellowships in the Health Sciences:
</P>
<P> 	Division of International Training and Research 	 	Fogarty
International Center, NIH 	Building 31, Room B2-C39, MSC 2220 	31
Center Drive, MSC 2220 	Bethesda, Maryland  20892-2220, U.S.A. 
	Telephone:  (301) 496-1653 	Fax:  (301) 402-0779 
</P>
<P>For internet users with access to a system with a Gopher
client, information about all NIH programs may be obtained by
accessing the NIH Gopher at gopher.nih.gov.  Fogarty
International Center programs are listed under Grants and
Fellowships.  
</P>
<P>United States Information Agency (USIA)  
</P>
<P>The U.S. Information Agency (USIA) is the principal U.S.
government foreign affairs agency whose mission is to promote
information, cultural and educational exchanges between the
United States and other countries.  Working with other public and
private agencies and organizations, USIA plans and administers
educational exchange programs for undergraduate, graduate and
post-graduate students, as well as a flexible array of
professional and citizen exchanges involving Americans and
leaders from many countries, including South Africa. 
</P>
<P>Most USIA programs are funded from direct congressional
appropriations as part of the U.S. government's public diplomacy
efforts, but increasingly -- and particularly with respect to
South Africa -- the exchanges are partnerships between USIA and
USAID or private organizations or companies.  
</P>
<P>The Fulbright Exchange Program 
</P>
<P>This program brings over 1,400 foreign graduate students to
U.S. universities each year and sends over 1,000 U.S. scholars
and professionals to more than 100 countries.  In recent years
this program has annually accepted about 30 South Africans to
study or conduct research in the United States and a similar
number of Americans to conduct research or teach in South Africa.
 Over the years, leading South Africans have received advanced
degrees in a wide variety of fields at American institutions. 
</P>
<P>The Humphrey Fellowship Program  
</P>
<P>The Humphrey Fellowship Program brings 1,000 mid-level
professionals from developing countries, including South Africa,
to the U.S. for year-long university study and work-related
practical experience. 
</P>
<P> The University Affiliations Program 
</P>
<P>The University Affiliations Program provides seed funding
toward the establishment of long-term institutional partnerships
between U.S. and foreign universities and develops exchanges of
faculty and staff.  Several linkages between American and South
African universities have been selected for formal funding over
the years; many others have grown out of other USIA-funded
exchanges. 
</P>
<P>The International Visitor Program 
</P>
<P>The International Visitor Program brings approximately 2,600
first-time visitors from around the world to the U.S. each year
for targeted, short-term professional development programs. 
Among the veterans of this program are former Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher and former German Chancellor Willi Brandt. 
Nearly 1,200 leading South Africans, including Presidential Chief
of Staff Jakes Gerwel, ANC leader Cyril Ramaphosa, Deputy
President F.W. De Klerk and anti-apartheid parliamentarian Helen
Suzman have been International Visitors.  The program's
flexibility has been particularly valuable in the case of South
Africa, as special enhancements both from Congress and in
partnership with USAID, have substantially increased the number
of South Africans visiting the United States since 1990.  As
discussed with Minister Ngubane during his Washington visit for
the U.S. - South African Binational Commission meetings, USIA is
prepared to construct a special group program for a high-level
delegation of South African science policy experts, to be
designated by the Minister, to visit the United States for an
intensive consultations with counterparts throughout the country;
</P>
<P>The Voluntary Visitor Program 
</P>
<P>The Voluntary Visitor Program annually assists over 2,500
professionals during visits to the United States with
supplementary short-term consultations or professional
development programs.  This program has also demonstrated its
flexibility in recent years as South African political and NGO
leaders, travelling to the U.S. on other business have been able
to remain for special consultations with American experts on a
broad range of issues, e.g. conflict resolution, constitutional
and civil rights issues, democratic governance and other priority
concerns. 
</P>
<P>The U.S. Speakers Program, Academic/Cultural Specialist and
Professionals-in-Residence Programs 
</P>
<P>These programs send hundreds of U.S. professionals abroad
each year for shorter-term speaking engagements, training and
consultative activities.  These programs have proven particularly
valuable in the case of South Africa; special enhancements both
from Congress and  partnership with USAID have enabled USIA to
provide a large number of outstanding American experts to work
closely with South African government and nongovernment
organizations doing vital work in a range of issues including
conflict resolution, legal and constitutional reform,
broadcasting regulation, education and arts management; 
</P>
<P>The Office of Private Sector Programs
</P>
<P>The Office of Private Sector Programs in recent years has
facilitated a number of exchange programs in a wide variety of
targeted areas through solicited requests for proposals from
American institutions and organizations creating partnerships
with foreign institutions and organizations.  Open solicitations
for proposals area also periodically published and reviewed. 
This Office also has pioneered USIA's largest public-private
exchange program in cooperation with Warner Music Group and the
New School for Social Research, providing management internships
for South Africans in the United States. 
</P>
<P></P>
<P>For more information:
</P>
<P></P>
<P>South Africans interested in additional information about
USIA exchange programs may contact the Public Affairs Officer,
U.S. Information Service, Embassy of the United States, Pretoria.
Telephone (012) 342-3006.  
</P>
<P>National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) 
</P>
<P>Sea Grant College Program 
</P>
<P>NOAA is the home of the National Sea Grant College Program
which links participating college and university programs across
the United States.  These programs focus on education, advisory
services and research related to the Great Lakes (large
freshwater systems), coastal and marine environments.  Foreign
national graduate students often receive research assistantships
on environmental projects funded by the National Sea Grant
Office. 
</P>
<P>Sea Grant programs are providing training for U.S. teachers
of predominantly minority students and address minority
involvement at all levels of education.  Science education
projects, directly involve middle and secondary students, train
teachers, and generate specialized educational materials for
minority Hispanic populations.  Pre-college education efforts
have been expanded into U.S.-affiliated Pacific island states
through the Pacific Island Network.  Additionally, Puerto Rico
Sea Grant extends its technical advisory assistance and education
programs into the Caribbean Basin. 
</P>
<P>NOAA has initiated the International Marine Debris Project,
coordinated through the National Marine Fisheries Service.  The
Fourth International Conference (Miami, 1994) included South
African researchers as committee chairs.  The proceedings
published through the North Carolina Sea Grant Program and a
subsequent periodical to encourage continued global networking
and exchange of knowledge could easily focus on South African
students for data on beach debris and analysis.  This project
requires technical research and low level volunteer monitoring
for data input. 
</P>
<P>International science education associations, in concert with
the National Association for Research in Science Teaching
(NARST), include university and college faculty from the U.S. and
South Africa.  U.S. membership includes educational specialists
from the Sea Grant programs.  This could provide a mechanism to
exchange/distribute pre-college curricula and strategies on
teaching about the marine and coastal environment and provide an
outlet for research findings to enter the public sector more
quickly. 
</P>
<P>Links with Research Under the Commission 
</P>
<P>NOAA is participating in the Committee on Conservation and
the Environment and the Committee on Science and Technology under
the Gore-Mbeki Commission.  Under these Committees, we chair the
Fisheries Working Group and the Weather and Climate Working
Group.  These groups are developing cooperative projects with
South African counterparts (both government and academic). 
</P>
<P>Based on a similar approach under consideration for research
in Arctic areas, the human resource development aspect could
include three components: (a) information supplied to local,
affected communities both prior to and after the conduct of
research; (b) incorporation, as appropriate, of indigenous
knowledge; and (c) inclusion of students on research or data
collection teams.  
</P>
<P>To encourage diversity in graduate research programs,
mentorship programs, beginning as early as middle grades, could
involve students with professionals, with the objective of
interesting them in future scientific careers. 
</P>
<P>Dr. Bradford E. Brown, a participant in the Fisheries Working
Group, identified several such opportunities in his Trip Report
on his participation in the October 1994 visit of the U.S.
Science and Technology Delegation. 
</P>
<P>Some of the ideas included in his report include: 
</P>
<P>o efforts by the Sea Fisheries Institute to establish links
with Historically Black Colleges to bring students on as interns;
 o increased involvement of the Oceanographic Institution (a NGO)
in Durban with local Black and Indian Communities;  o the
possibility of providing training to Black and Indian students by
the Natal Shark Board;  o supplementing efforts by the FRD to
increase involvement of Historically Black Colleges and
Universities by establishing a marine science area focus;  o
expanding present research linkages between the U.S. National
Marine Fisheries Service (NOAA) and the University of Zululand by
beginning undergraduates in off campus scientific field work. 
</P>
<P>The Globe Program 
</P>
<P>The Globe Program is initiating a global student
environmental monitoring system which could link a diverse group
of South African pre-college students to researchers and students
throughout the world.  
</P>
<P>U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA)  
</P>
<P>The Cochran Fellowship Program
</P>
<P> USDA's Foreign Agriculture Service has initiated a pilot
training program, called the Cochran Fellowship Program, to
provide short-term training in the United States for
agriculturists from middle-income countries.  The program is
intended to develop agricultural systems necessary to meet the
food needs of the domestic population and to strengthen and
enhance the trade linkages between eligible countries and
agricultural interests in the United States.  The Cochran
Fellowship program will include a cross-section of participants
from the public and private sector agriculture community,
including government ministries, agriculture research and
extension centers, farmers unions, and agribusiness. 
Applications were distributed and accepted through the
Agricultural Attache's office in Pretoria.  Interviews of
potential candidates were conducted between March 20-30, 1995.  
</P>
<P>USDA funds were set aside to fund up to 30 Cochran candidates
from South Africa.  A decision was made to fund 15 slots from the
public sector and 15 from the private sector and academia.  Of
the approximately 70 candidates interviewed in March, 20 were
accepted into the training program.  The remaining Cochran funds
will be set aside for FY1996 when further interviews can be
conducted. 
</P>
<P>For more information contact: Frankie King, USDA (202)
690-0598  
</P>
<P>National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) 
</P>
<P>Each year, NIST hosts approximately 600 international guest
scientists and engineers at its Gaithersburg, Maryland and
Boulder, Colorado laboratories.  In the past year, NIST has
hosted three South Africans and hopes o increase this number.  
</P>
<P>For further information, please contact : Dr. B. Stephen
Carpenter, Acting Director, Office of International and Academic
Affairs (301)975-4119
<!-- BEGIN BODY FOOTER SECTION --></P></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
