<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>About Deaconess Hospital</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><H1>Welcome to Deaconess Hospital Online</H1><A HREF="../overview/index.htm">OVIERVIEW</A>|<A HREF="../patient/index.htm">PATIENT INFORMATION</A>|<A HREF="../direct/index.htm">DIRECTORY</A>|<A HREF="../research/index.htm">RESEARCH</A><BR><A HREF="../educate/index.htm">EDUCATION</A>|<A HREF="../news/index.htm">NEWS &amp; CONFERENCES</A>|<A HREF="../employ/index.htm">EMPLOYMENT</A>|<A HREF="../new/index.htm">WHAT'S NEW</A></CENTER><H1>Overview</H1><A HREF="index.htm">[BACK]</A> <A HREF="referral.htm">[NEXT]</A><H2>About Deaconess Hospital</H2>Deaconess Hospital is an adult specialty-referral, tertiary care facility and a major teaching hospital of Harvard Medical School.  The Deaconess is also affiliated with the Joslin Diabetes Center, Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, and the Joint Center for Radiation Therapy.<P>Conveniently located in the Longwood Medical and Academic Area, the Hospital is close to other major health-care institutions with which it shares numerous joint programs, research efforts and staff.<P>Founded in 1896, Deaconess Hospital has long been known for combining "science and kindliness" in the delivery of state-of-the-art health-care and hospital services to the most critically ill patients.  Our reputation for providing quality patient care is internationally recognized as evidenced by the number of patients from around the world who turn to the Deaconess for management of complex illnesses.<P>Since its establishment, the Deaconess has been home to many talented physician-scientists. Clinical highlights -- including the first use of insulin in New England for the treatment of diabetic patients -- abound. The Deaconess Cancer Research Institute was established in 1951 to study causes and potential treatments for cancer. The first of its kind in New England, the Institute remains a leader in the study of chemopreventive agents and their role in the prevention of prostate, colon and breast cancers. Hepatobiliary surgeons at Deaconess Hospital performed New England's first successful liver transplant in 1983.<P>In addition, programs such as the Deaconess Mind/Body Medical Institute and the Institute for Prevention of Cardiovascular Disease have promoted innovative disease prevention modalities in the region and throughout the nation. The institutes examine the roles that life-style factors, including stress, poor nutrition and lack of exercise, play in the development of hypertension, heart disease and other life- threatening conditions.<P>The Hospital provides specialized medical and surgical services and returns patients to their physicians, community hospitals, or other health-care providers for ongoing care and monitoring. This collaboration allows for the most effective use of expertise and provides the highest level of quality patient care in the most appropriate setting.<P>Our extensive experience, research and educational programs have led us to develop multidisciplinary programs in: <P><UL>	<LI>heart and vascular disease/cardiology	<LI>diabetes complications/vascular surgery	<LI>bone &amp; joint	<LI>AIDS/HIV	<LI>gastrointestinal and liver disorders/Hepatobiliary Surgery</UL><P>By establishing these specialized areas of care, the Deaconess can maintain a variety of specialized units within the general Hospital complex.<P>Cluster units for cardiology, oncology, psychiatry, vascular disease and transplantation allow highly trained personnel to address patients' special needs.<P>Intensive and coronary care units are supplemented by stepdown units for patients recovering from vascular, cardiac and thoracic disease or surgery. These units provide greater monitoring of patients who do not require intensive care.<P>Our excellent medical and nursing care are supported by outstanding pathology laboratories and facilities in radiology and radiation therapy.  Dietitians, pharmacists, physical therapists and respiratory therapists all contribute to patient-centered care.<P><H5>Copyright 1996 Deaconess Hospital, All rights reserved.</H5></BODY></HTML>
