<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>Deaconess Hospital Annual Report</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><H1>Welcome to Deaconess Hospital Online</H1><A HREF="../overview/index.htm">OVIERVIEW</A>|<A HREF="../patient/index.htm">PATIENT INFORMATION</A>|<A HREF="../direct/index.htm">DIRECTORY</A>|<A HREF="../research/index.htm">RESEARCH</A><BR><A HREF="../educate/index.htm">EDUCATION</A>|<A HREF="../news/index.htm">NEWS &amp; CONFERENCES</A>|<A HREF="../employ/index.htm">EMPLOYMENT</A>|<A HREF="../new/index.htm">WHAT'S NEW</A></CENTER><H1>Overview</H1><A HREF="centers.htm">[BACK]</A> <A HREF="index.htm">[NEXT]</A><H2>Deaconess Hospital Annual Report</H2><P><B>Highlights: 1996</B><P>For the Deaconess, 1996 marked a turning point -- a period of transition in which the hospital's rich past, vibrant present, and promising future were equally on display.  Preparations for the hospital's 1996 centennial celebration afforded opportunities to reflect on the Deaconess' proud heritage as a place where "science and kindliness unite."  Just as evident, however, were the many far-ranging initiatives that the hospital has undertaken to ensure that its tradition of excellence in patient care, education, research, and community services is carried well into the next century.<P>In 1995 the Deaconess capped a decade of planning and preparation with the successful completion of a $25 million capital campaign that helped ensure timely completion of its new Clinical Center and also make possible a commitment to occupy new research space.  The Clinical Center, which opened in early 1995 to praise from patients and staff alike, is the most visible demonstration of the hospital's commitment to the future.  The building, which has won several awards honoring its design, functionality, and beauty, not only assures patients access to the region's most advanced tertiary-care facilities, but also supports the personalized, compassionate care for which the Deaconess is known.<P>The hospital reinforced its commitment to cutting-edge medical research by joining the Harvard Institutes of Medicine (HIM) project now under construction in the former Boston English High School building.  The facility will provide Deaconess physician-scientists with modern, cost-effective research space that consolidates geographically diverse laboratory activities, fosters the bench-to-bedside application of new research findings, and enhances opportunities for collaboration with colleagues from New England Baptist, Beth Israel, and Brigham and Women's hospital, who also will be located there.  To help ensure the continued growth and vitality of its scientific programs, the hospital established a special fund to support HIM construction and ongoing research activities.<P>At the same time, the hospital took steps to ensure that it remains a leader in today's health-care market.  Changes in the practice of medicine and other clinical initiatives helped reduce average length of stay by nearly a full day in 1995.  This dramatic result reflects Deaconess physicians' active involvement in cost-control and quality-improvement efforts -- working closely with management and employees to streamline procedures, improve communication, and identify and eliminate unnecessary work.  Through the efforts of multidisciplinary teams at all levels and across all departments, the hospital successfully reduced operation costs by $27 million in 1995, and identified and additional $10 million in savings to be realized in the coming fiscal year.  Part of a five-year effort projected to reduce overall expenses by 25 percent from 1992 to 1996, these actions are essential to maintaining the hospital's competitiveness in tomorrow's environment.<P>Teamwork is also at the heart of the hospital's approach to case management, which brings together nursing and social work staff to maintain patient-centered care while improving communication and facilitating cost-effective practices among care givers.  Other key clinical efforts -- including ongoing expansion of the hospital's Transitional Care Unit and further development of Behavioral Health Systems of New England, a Deaconess-initiated, full-service psychiatric network linking complementary mental-health and substance-abuse providers in eastern Massachusetts -- enhance the scope of services offered to patients.  These and other ongoing projects aimed at developing better patient outcome measures and identifying ways to improve patient care exemplify the benefits to be gained from collaboration.<P>Through efforts like these, Deaconess Hospital was able to meet the challenges of the changing market without compromising high-quality, personalized patient care or a positive work climate.  Employee and patient satisfaction surveys undertaken during the year confirmed the hospital's success in these efforts.  Ratings from employees in 10 of 16 categories surveyed, including job satisfaction and working conditions.  Patient satisfaction likewise increased, with results approaching the all-time high recorded in 1983 when the survey was initiated.  The survey provides a constant measure of efforts to ensure that each patient receives care that is warm and compassionate as well as the most advanced that medical science has to offer.  Superior scores from patients treated in the new Clinical Center highlight that facility's positive impact.  This performance was further validated by the Joint Commission on Accreditation of Healthcare Organizations, which gave the Deaconess excellent ratings during its survey last June.<P><B>DPPG: Positioned for the Future</B><P>Formed in 1987 as the first multispecialty physician group practice in the Harvard Medical School system, Deaconess Professional Practice Group (DPPG) works closely with the hospital to further its commitment to quality patient care, education , and research.<P>A separate corporate entity comprising physicians in Deaconess Medicine, Deaconess Surgical Associates, Deaconess Radiology Associates, Deaconess Pathology Associates, and Deaconess Psychiatry, DDPG has been instrumental in aligning hospital and physician initiatives while breaking down the institutional and divisional barriers that can impede communication and optimal coordination or patient care.<P>Efforts to better position DPPG in the evolving managed-care market advanced on several fronts during the past year, overcoming management transitions and challenges.  In September, Deaconess Department of Medicine chairman Robert C. Moellering, Jr., M.D., was named DPPG president and Dorothy Ross DPPG chief operation officer.  Working closely with the hospital to meet ambitious cost-control goals, they an others in the practice group spearheaded several important clinical and contracting initiatives.  DPPG played a critical role in the hospital's successful negotiation of a ground-breaking sub-capitated contract with Brockton-based Goddard Medical Associates, one of the state's largest multispecialty physician group practices.  Under this agreement, the first of its kind in Massachusetts, the Deaconess and New England Medical Center receive a fixed, per-member, per-month fee to provide tertiary care for approximately 20,000 HMO Blue patients.  Through the Goddard Contract, as well as Pathway Health's contract with Fallon Community Health Plan, the Deaconess and DPPG will gain valuable experience in managing capitation and similar kinds of risk-sharing arrangements that are expected to shape the health-care marketplace of the future.<P>Progress continued on the development of "product lines" in several clinical specialties, most notably cardiology and cardiothoracic surgery.  These efforts -- aimed at developing distinct, high-quality, cost-effective algorithms of care that can be priced globally for HMOs and other payers as clinical products -- bring together physicians from different departments, along with other care-team members, to make joint decisions about care plans, resource allocation, contracting, and marketing.<P>Great success also was achieved in academic endeavors that reflect a long-standing commitment to medical education and research.  Exceptional results were attained in the National Residency Matching Program fir 1995-1996, matching a total of 66 medical school graduates with residency training programs in the departments of Medicine, Surgery, Radiological Sciences, Pathology, Psychiatry.<P>Two Deaconess physicians who have pioneered research in the field of organ transplantation, Fritz Bach, M.D., and Anthony Monaco, M.D., were selected as the first recipients of two newly endowed Harvard Medical School professorships made possible by a $5 million gift from the Sandoz Pharmaceutical Corporation and named for two of the most significant scientists in the field.  Bach will occupy the Lewis Thomas chair, while Monaco was awarded the Peter Medawar Professorship.<P>Through cutting-edge research in other areas such as behavioral medicine, diabetes, cancer, nutrition, and AIDS, Deaconess physician-scientists are tackling some of medicine's most challenging puzzles.  In investigation of "designer T cells" and other forays into molecular biology, hospital researchers are working to harness the power of the human immune system to combat cancer and other diseases.  Last fall, Deaconess cardiologists published findings demonstrating a scientific link between anger and heart attacks; the attention and acclaim generated by studies such as this have helped the hospital maintain its national and international reputation as a center of medical knowledge.<P><B>Commitment to Community</B><P>Like Pathway Health Network, the Deaconess works to fulfill a four-part mission that comprises community service as a well as patient care, education, and research.  The commitment to outreach was underscored recently when the hospital's Board of Trustees formed it own Community Benefit Committee to provide strategic guidance for efforts to improve community health.<P>In the past year, activities focused on statewide outreach for patients with HIV and AIDS, as well as on health-promotion and disease-prevention programs geared to older adults and residents of Boston's Roxbury neighborhood.  For example, Deaconess cardiologists help staff the Roxbury Heart Center, which provides much-needed cardiac care for that community's predominantly African-American population.  The Center, a collaborative effort of Deaconess, Beth Israel, and New England Baptist hospitals, along with Roxbury Comprehensive Community Health Center, was selected by the American Hospital Association as a finalist for its NOVA Award, which honors collaborative projects that focus on improving community health status.  Another outreach activity was the Deaconess Department of Nursing's sponsorship of "Health beat on Warren Street," an all-day community health fair attended by hundreds of Roxbury residents.  The event was part of the hospital's year-long centennial celebration.<P><B>A Second Century</B><P>The Deaconess enters its second century supported by a solid financial foundation and guided by a strong, experienced leadership.  During the past year, the hospital's Board of Trustees named former executive vice president and chief operating officer Robert G. Norton as the Deaconess' new president, while Cheryl Hoffman was recruited to serve as chief financial officer.<P>With the successful conclusion of the Deaconess Campaign -- which raised $25 million in philanthropic gifts over four years -- the hospital is well positioned to provide tomorrow's health care today.  As a result of strong support from trustees, corporators, medical staff, and employees, as well as from corporations, foundations, and grateful patients and their families, the new Clinical Center is fully operational and the hospital can turn its attention to research -- renewing its commitment to the creation of new knowledge that will benefit the patients of tomorrow.  This effort will ensure that the Deaconess is able to continue to uncover the cures for diseases while providing patient-centered care -- to be a place where "science and kindliness unite" for a second century.<P><H5>Copyright 1996 Deaconess Hospital, All rights reserved.</H5></BODY></HTML>
