<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>Cardiovascular Disease</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><H1>Welcome to Deaconess Hospital Online</H1><A HREF="../overview/index.htm">OVIERVIEW</A>|<A HREF="../patient/index.htm">PATIENT INFORMATION</A>|<A HREF="../direct/index.htm">DIRECTORY</A>|<A HREF="../research/index.htm">RESEARCH</A><BR><A HREF="../educate/index.htm">EDUCATION</A>|<A HREF="../news/index.htm">NEWS &amp; CONFERENCES</A>|<A HREF="../employ/index.htm">EMPLOYMENT</A>|<A HREF="../new/index.htm">WHAT'S NEW</A></CENTER><H1>Overview of Research Program</H1><A HREF="index.htm">[BACK]</A> <A HREF="infect.htm">[NEXT]</A><H2>Cardiovascular Disease</H2><P><B>Dr. Frank LoGerfo</B><BR>An active vascular surgeon, Dr. LoGerfo's research program includes studies directed toward improved function and lifespan of both natural and artificial blood vessel grafts.  For example, Dr. LoGerfo and his colleagues have prepared various composites wherein either an anticoagulant (to reduce blood clotting) or an antibiotic (to prevent infection) is linked to the graft material.  His group is also interested in the flow dynamics of vessel grafts and the biology of the cells which line blood vessels.  Dr. LoGerfo is Principal Investigator of an NIH Training Grant in Vascular Surgery which combines faculty in several of the teaching hospitals affiliated with Harvard Medical School as well as of an RO1 from the National Institutes of Health.  He also participates as an investigator in a collaboration with a biomedical company which is funded by NIH. <P><B>Dr. Sidney Levitskty</B><BR>Joined by his colleagues Drs. Irvin Krukencamp and James McCully, Dr. Levitsky studies the preservation of heart muscle during surgery and the protection of that tissue from re-perfusion injury.  The group has recently cloned several genes which seem to be involved in intimal hyperplasia.  Both Dr. Levitsky and Dr. Krukencamp are active cardiothoracic surgeons and have investigator initiated grant support from the National Institutes of Health.  Dr. McCully has a grant from the American Heart Association.<P><B>Dr. Richard Verrier</B><BR>A member of the Division of Cardiology, Dr. Verrier joined the Deaconess approximately two years ago.  His research interest is in diagnosis and prognostication of cardiac disease and his approach is combined analysis of parameters such as blood pressure, heart rate variability, and electrical activity of the heart. His research is supported by an RO1 from the National Institutes of Health and grants from several companies.  His work has resulted in several patents, leading to additional support from industry.<P><H5>Copyright 1996 Deaconess Hospital, All rights reserved.</H5></BODY></HTML>
