<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>Infectious Disease</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><H1>Welcome to Deaconess Hospital Online</H1><A HREF="../overview/index.htm">OVIERVIEW</A>|<A HREF="../patient/index.htm">PATIENT INFORMATION</A>|<A HREF="../direct/index.htm">DIRECTORY</A>|<A HREF="../research/index.htm">RESEARCH</A><BR><A HREF="../educate/index.htm">EDUCATION</A>|<A HREF="../news/index.htm">NEWS &amp; CONFERENCES</A>|<A HREF="../employ/index.htm">EMPLOYMENT</A>|<A HREF="../new/index.htm">WHAT'S NEW</A></CENTER><H1>Overview of Research Program</H1><A HREF="cardvasc.htm">[BACK]</A> <A HREF="cancer.htm">[NEXT]</A><H2>Infectious Disease</H2><P>Dr. Jerome Groopman leads a group of investigators which includes Dr. John Ladius, Dr. Randal Byrn and Dr. Ernest Terwilliger studying HIV infection and its treatment.  Dr. Groopman is Principal Investigator on a Program Project Grant from the National Institutes of Health through which the group seeks to improve the understanding of the impairment in pulmonary host defense in the setting of HIV and HIV-associated infections. Dr. Groopman's own project within this large grant is directed towards study of the direct effects of HIV infection on alveolar macrophages - a type of cell central to the immune defense system of the lungs.  He is also the Principal investigator on an RO1 grant to explore the use of a specific growth factor (thrombopoietin) to combat a deficiency of blood platelets in HIV infected patients.  Dr. Ladius is funded by an RO1 from NIH to study the possible role of a class of nuclear receptors which he discovered in the control of HIV replication.  A second RO1 and a grant from the American Heart Association awarded to Dr. Ladius are for the study of the regulation of a lipoprotein gene product by that same family of receptors.  Recently, he has added the technique of x-ray crystallography to provide structure-function correlates.  Dr. Randal Byrn is researching potential new therapies for HIV infection.  His laboratory collaborates with a number of pharmaceutical companies in the development of new drugs.  He has established a set of biological systems which provide important information on drug effects.  The same studies are also informative with regard to our understanding of the life cycle of HIV.  One major current project involves the construction of "designer" T cells genetically engineered to kill HIV.  Dr. Byrn's funding is partially from for-profit companies and partially from non-profit foundations. Dr. Terwilliger is a molecular biologist with two RO1 grants from NIH which support his studies on how an HIV gene designated vpr is involved in the replication of the virus in macrophages/monocytes.  He is also supported by the American Foundation for AIDS Research and Concerned Parents for AIDS Research on projects related to the treatment of HIV infection by gene therapy.  In the first case, the approach is to make cells of the hematopoietic system resistant to infection by HIV and the second is directed at a more direct therapy for cells already infected.<P>Dr. Scott Hammer is lead investigator on a number of clinical studies related to AIDS therapy. At the same time, he maintains a laboratory research effort focused upon specialized assays to type HIV isolates and assays of other viruses causing opportunistic infections in AIDS patients. In both cases, he receives funding from the AIDS Clinical Trial Group (ACTG) at NIH and from pharmaceutical companies.<P>Dr. Christine Wanke's research interest is in infections of the gut in AIDS patients.  Like Drs. Groopman and Hammer, she is an active clinician.  Her current research funding includes five grants from non-profit agencies and pharmaceutical companies.  In the laboratory, a main interest is on infection by E. coli,, a bacterium which is harmless in normal adults but which can cause serious infection in immunocomprimised AIDS patients.<P>A final group including Dr. Robert Moellering and Dr. George Eliopoulos studies bacterial resistance to antibiotics.  The emergence of bacterial strains resistant to antibiotics is a common but serious problem. To counter this problem, pharmaceutical companies are actively developing new antibiotics utilizing techniques such as rational drug design.  Drs. Moellering and Eliopoulos work in collaboration with a number of companies to screen new compounds against a panel of bacterial strains found in the hospital setting and to understand the molecular basis for drug resistance.<P><H5>Copyright 1996 Deaconess Hospital, All rights reserved.</H5></BODY></HTML>
