</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>Cancer/Cell Growth and Differentiation</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><H1>Welcome to Deaconess Hospital Online</H1><A HREF="../overview/index.htm">OVIERVIEW</A>|<A HREF="../patient/index.htm">PATIENT INFORMATION</A>|<A HREF="../direct/index.htm">DIRECTORY</A>|<A HREF="../research/index.htm">RESEARCH</A><BR><A HREF="../educate/index.htm">EDUCATION</A>|<A HREF="../news/index.htm">NEWS &amp; CONFERENCES</A>|<A HREF="../employ/index.htm">EMPLOYMENT</A>|<A HREF="../new/index.htm">WHAT'S NEW</A></CENTER><H1>Overview of Research Program</H1><A HREF="infect.htm">[BACK]</A> <A HREF="inflame.htm">[NEXT]</A><H2>Cancer/Cell Growth and Differentiation</H2><P>The clinical research programs of the Deaconess include studies of all of the major cancers.  Special emphasis is found in studies of colo-rectal cancer where there is a particularly stronglink between clinical and laboratory studies and in the treatment of liver cancer by chemoembolism through a collaboration between the Departments of Medicine and Radiology.  Our laboratory research in this field is more narrowly defined and includes four groups of investigators.<P>The first is led by Dr. J. Milburn Jessup of the Department of Surgery and includes Drs. Harvey Goldman, Max Loda, Arthur Mercurio, Ian Summerhayes and Peter Thomas.  A combination of surgeons (Jessup), pathologists (Goldman and Loda) and basic scientists (Mercurio, Summerhayes and Thomas), this group studies the pathobiology of colo-rectal cancer.  A program project grant from the National Institutes of Health is the cornerstone of funding for the group with additional funding coming from RO1 grants from NIH (Jessup, Mercurio, Summerhayes and Thomas), NASA (Jessup), the American Cancer Society (Mercurio), a training grant from NIH,  and grants from several for-profit companies.  Individual projects include: the role of carcinoembryonic antigen and of integrins in metastasis of colon tumors; the search for new markers specific for types of colo-rectal cancers and description of any correlation which exists between marker levels and disease stage and response to treatment;  and efforts to better understand the role of various oncogenes in the development and progression of tumors.<P>The second group is led by Dr. Jerome Groopman and includes Drs. Hava Avraham, Shalom Avraham, and Jadwiga Grabarek.  This group is interested in the normal development of cells of the blood system (hematopoietic cells) and the nervous system and how such development goes awry in leukemia and lymphoma.  Other studies are directed at the development of supportive therapies for patients with cancer.  For example, chemotherapy and radiation therapy can lead to a significant reduction of blood platelets.  Soluble factors which promote the formation of new platelets including the factor called thrombopoietin and antibodies which can act as growth factor agonists are currently being studied by this group.  Dr. Groopman, Dr. H. Avraham and Dr. Grabarek all have investigator-initiated grants from the National Institutes of Health for their studies.  They also collaborate with biotechnology companies interested in the commercial applications of growth and development factors.<P>Dr. Richard Junghans leads a group studying the potential of creating a strong cell mediated immune response against cancer by genetically engineering a subset of white blood cells (T derived lymphocytes) to carry a more efficient cell surface receptor for recognition of the cancers.  Dr. Junghans' studies are supported by grants from the NIH, the Department of Defense, the FDA and the American Cancer Society.<P>A final group within this category, led by Dr. Arthur Sytkowski, is studying how cells receive signals from their environment and transmit those signals within the cell.  Their more specific interest is with erythropoeitin and its receptor.  The group is supported by grants from the NIH, the Department of the Navy and by several individual postdoctoral fellowships.<P><H5>Copyright 1996 Deaconess Hospital, All rights reserved.</H5></BODY></HTML>
