<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>Nutrition</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><H1>Welcome to Deaconess Hospital Online</H1><A HREF="../overview/index.htm">OVIERVIEW</A>|<A HREF="../patient/index.htm">PATIENT INFORMATION</A>|<A HREF="../direct/index.htm">DIRECTORY</A>|<A HREF="../research/index.htm">RESEARCH</A><BR><A HREF="../educate/index.htm">EDUCATION</A>|<A HREF="../news/index.htm">NEWS &amp; CONFERENCES</A>|<A HREF="../employ/index.htm">EMPLOYMENT</A>|<A HREF="../new/index.htm">WHAT'S NEW</A></CENTER><H1>Overview of Research Program</H1><A HREF="inflame.htm">[BACK]</A> <A HREF="trnsplnt.htm">[NEXT]</A><H2>Nutrition</H2><P>Research in Nutrition has been a long standing area of excellence for the Deaconess.  Since the inception of these programs, there has been on focus on nutritional strategies for the post-surgical patient leading to such innovations as the use of fish oils and structured lipids.  Most recently, a study led by Dr. Timothy Babineau demonstrated the effectiveness of Betafectin (a glucan) in reducing hospital stay in such patients.  The major research groups in this area include:<P>Dr. George Blackburn and colleagues are interested in lasting weight loss as a preventative strategy against several diseases.  Recognizing that failure to maintain weight loss is a major problem, their efforts have included a combination of calorie restriction, exercise, counseling and pharmacolgic intervention.  The later aspect includes clinical studies of the combination of phenteramine resin and dl-fenfluramine.  Other ongoing studies include assessment of leptin levels and attempts to identify additional genes linked to obesity.  Of particular note are the outreach efforts to minority populations in these studies as sociological issues clearly bear upon the effectiveness of some intervention strategies.  This group is supported by grants from the NIH and from industry.<P>A second group, led by Dr. Bruce Bistrian, is engaged in laboratory studies of how specific nutrients affect characteristics of the immune response such as the production of cytokines and an additional study of how hormones such as IGF-1 modulate body composition.  This group is also supported by both NIH and company funding.<P>Dr. R. Armour Forse, an active surgeon, leads a team of investigators working in the new field of "nutraceuticals" in which specific dietary components provide specific medical benefits.  Their studies include compounds such as saponins, sesamins and herbal compounds and their approach includes both the demonstration of clinical benefits and a biochemical exploration of the mechanisms behind such benefits.  A major supporter of their studies is a start-up company formed to commercialize technology developed by this group.<P><H5>Copyright 1996 Deaconess Hospital, All rights reserved.</H5></BODY></HTML>
