<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>Transplantation</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><H1>Welcome to Deaconess Hospital Online</H1><A HREF="../overview/index.htm">OVIERVIEW</A>|<A HREF="../patient/index.htm">PATIENT INFORMATION</A>|<A HREF="../direct/index.htm">DIRECTORY</A>|<A HREF="../research/index.htm">RESEARCH</A><BR><A HREF="../educate/index.htm">EDUCATION</A>|<A HREF="../news/index.htm">NEWS &amp; CONFERENCES</A>|<A HREF="../employ/index.htm">EMPLOYMENT</A>|<A HREF="../new/index.htm">WHAT'S NEW</A></CENTER><H1>Overview of Research Program</H1><A HREF="nutrit.htm">[BACK]</A> <A HREF="mindbody.htm">[NEXT]</A><H2>Transplantation</H2><P>The Deaconess is a major center for transplantation with one of the most active programs of liver transplantation in the country.  Again the patient care program is supported by both clinical and laboratory research.<P>Drs. Anthony Monaco, David Lewis and Roger Jenkins are engaged in clinical studies of  immunosuppressive agents which reduce organ rejection.  Dr. Monaco's laboratory research in conjunction with Dr. Takashi Maki also emphasizes the study of immunosuppression but at the cellular and animal level.  In addition, these investigators have played a major role in the development of an artificial pancreas which is expected to enter clinical trials within the next several months.  support for these investigators comes from the NIH and several pharmaceutical/biotechnology companies.<P>A large program in the Sandoz Center for Immunobiology headed by Dr. Fritz Bach is engaged in studies to make feasible the transplantation of organs from other species into man.  Such xenotransplants are rejected by mechanisms different than those principally operative in man-to-man transplants and the hypothesis is that the barriers to xenotransplantation can be overcome more easily than those to allotransplantation.  Much of their work is directed at defining the various mechanisms involved in rejection and attempts to remove those barriers through a combination of genetic engineering and  drug therapy.<P><H5>Copyright 1996 Deaconess Hospital, All rights reserved.</H5></BODY></HTML>
