<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>News in Review</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><H1>Welcome to Deaconess Hospital Online</H1><A HREF="../overview/index.htm">OVIERVIEW</A>|<A HREF="../patient/index.htm">PATIENT INFORMATION</A>|<A HREF="../direct/index.htm">DIRECTORY</A>|<A HREF="../research/index.htm">RESEARCH</A><BR><A HREF="../educate/index.htm">EDUCATION</A>|<A HREF="../news/index.htm">NEWS &amp; CONFERENCES</A>|<A HREF="../employ/index.htm">EMPLOYMENT</A>|<A HREF="../new/index.htm">WHAT'S NEW</A></CENTER><H1>News &amp; Conferences</H1><A HREF="news.htm">[BACK]</A> <A HREF="bypass.htm">[NEXT]</A><H2>News in Review</H2><B>For Immediate Release:</B><P><BLOCKQUOTE>	Friday, February 23, 1996, 12:00 noon</BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Contact:</B><P><BLOCKQUOTE>	Nicole Gakidis, BIH, (617) 667-4431<BR>	Erin Martin, PHN, (617) 632-8046</BLOCKQUOTE><P><H3>Beth Israel Hospital and Pathway Health Network Begin Discussions For Potential Merger</H3><P>Boston's Beth Israel Hospital and Pathway Health Network, which includes Deaconess Hospital, have agreed to pursue a period of detailed examination to consider the feasibility of a merger between the two organizations and the establishment of a new regional network for healthcare, it was announced today. Members of the Beth Israel and Pathway boards, administrations, and medical staffs have been holding initial exploratory discussions for several weeks.<P>The two organizations envision a new concept of provision of care, from primary to tertiary and quaternary, and from neighborhood practice to the academic medical center. The outcome under consideration would include joining the two hospitals to form a single strengthened Beth Israel/Deaconess Medical Center, affiliated with Harvard Medical School, and located on their present neighboring sites in the heart of the Longwood Medical Area. Consolidation of clinical departments, administrative functions, and governance, along with substantial reduction of certain fixed costs, would create economies of intellectual and fiscal scale while enhancing both quality and efficiency of performance and service.<P>A major potential strength in the new network would be the opportunity to work as colleagues with other hospitals and doctors in their own communities, enhancing their ability to provide technical excellence and high medical competence locally, throughout the region, or, for the most complex illnesses, to serve as a referral source at the Harvard-affiliated academic medical center.<P>The new group, yet to be formally named, "will build upon the strengths of both systems and will constitute a significant restructuring producing a vital new force in healthcare in Massachusetts," according to Stephen B. Kay, Board Chair of Beth Israel. John Hamill, Pathway's Board Chair, hailed the joining of these two major Harvard-affiliated teaching hospitals -- Beth Israel and Deaconess -- as "permitting the vital changes in economics and clinical programs that will provide patients, their physicians, and their health plans with sophisticated medical care, a geographically diverse network of primary care providers, and the exceptional qualities of service and care for which Beth Israel and Deaconess are justifiably renowned."<P>"This cooperative relationship would help community physicians to stay at the leading edge of medical knowledge, diagnosis, and treatment, while in turn keeping the medical-center physicians in touch with and supportive of the needs of both the people in their local communities and their local physicians," said Mitchell T. Rabkin, MD, President of Beth Israel Hospital.<P>"The mission of Pathway Health Network has always been to serve patients, communities, students, and science. By bringing together academic and community-based colleagues and focusing on efficacy, quality and the cost of care, we can also add value to the health system. Collaboration will allow us best to fulfill our mission and to compete effectively in today's rapidly changing market," said J. Richard Gaintner, MD, President of Pathway Health Network.<P>The new hospital would meet the traditional responsibilities of both Beth Israel and Deaconess Hospitals, providing service for their neighboring areas at all levels from primary care on-site, in nearby doctors' offices and affiliated community health centers and hospitals, to highly specialized care for complex referral cases from a wider region, which is the traditionally provided expertise of the Harvard hospitals today.<P>The merged hospitals would provide state-of-the-art care at highly competitive prices in today's demanding economic environment, while also retaining the warmth and personalization widely recognized as particularly attractive characteristics of each institution today.<P>The new network of hospitals, physicians, and other health professionals throughout the region would include the Pathway Health Network institutions in addition to Deaconess Hospital: New England Baptist Hospital, Deaconess-Glover Hospital, Deaconess-Nashoba Hospital, and Deaconess-Waltham Hospital, their affiliated physicians, as well as many of the groups of community physicians related to Beth Israel. It is anticipated that others -- hospitals and physicians -- will join and enlarge the new network further, and that they will focus on the provision of care in their local communities, emphasizing the promotion of health, prevention of illness, and ready local access for most medical problems with the occasionally-needed tertiary support from the academic medical center.<P>This more formal phase of discussions, involving "due diligence" with detailed sharing of information and knowledge about the participants, is expected to last several months.<P><B>Beth Israel Hospital</B><BR>Beth Israel Hospital, Boston, was established in 1916 and moved to its present Longwood site in 1928. It is the cornerstone of Beth Israel HealthCare, a regional system of care promoting lifelong wellbeing. Beth Israel HealthCare includes physicians and medical groups, nurses, and other health professionals associated with Beth Israel Hospital, a major clinical, teaching, and research affiliate of Harvard Medical School.<P><B>Pathway Health Network</B><BR>Established in 1994, Pathway Health Network is an integrated system of community-based physicians, hospitals and health centers serving patients and communities in eastern Massachusetts and throughout the region. Full Network members include Deaconess Hospital and New England Baptist Hospital in Boston, Deaconess-Glover Hospital in Needham, Deaconess-Nashoba Hospital in Ayer, and Deaconess-Waltham Hospital in Waltham.<P><B>Deaconess Hospital</B><BR>Deaconess Hospital is a 385-bed specialty-referral, tertiary care facility and a major teaching hospital of Harvard Medical School. Established in 1896, the Hospital has long been known for uniting "science and kindliness" in rendering health and hospital services. In particular, the Deaconess is recognized internationally for expertise in the treatment of heart and vascular disease, diabetic complications, cancer, infectious diseases including AIDS, transplantation, gastrointestinal and liver disorders, nutrition and behavioral medicine.<P><H5>Copyright 1996 Deaconess Hospital, All rights reserved.</H5></BODY></HTML>
