<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>News in Review</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><H1>Welcome to Deaconess Hospital Online</H1><A HREF="../overview/index.htm">OVIERVIEW</A>|<A HREF="../patient/index.htm">PATIENT INFORMATION</A>|<A HREF="../direct/index.htm">DIRECTORY</A>|<A HREF="../research/index.htm">RESEARCH</A><BR><A HREF="../educate/index.htm">EDUCATION</A>|<A HREF="../news/index.htm">NEWS &amp; CONFERENCES</A>|<A HREF="../employ/index.htm">EMPLOYMENT</A>|<A HREF="../new/index.htm">WHAT'S NEW</A></CENTER><H1>News &amp; Conferences</H1><A HREF="bethpath.htm">[BACK]</A> <A HREF="changes.htm">[NEXT]</A><H2>News in Review</H2><B>For Immediate Release:</B><P><BLOCKQUOTE>	January 4, 1996</BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Contact:</B><P><BLOCKQUOTE>	Erin Martin<BR>	(617) 632-8046</BLOCKQUOTE><P><H3>Deaconess Surgeon Performs Boston'S First Minimally Invasive Coronary Artery Bypass Surgery</H3><P><B>(BOSTON, MA -- December 22, 1995)</B>  Sidney Levitsky, M.D., chief of cardiothoracic surgery at Deaconess Hospital and the David W. and David Cheever professor of surgery at Harvard Medical School, last week performed the region's first minimally invasive coronary artery bypass surgery, operating on a beating heart through a tiny, three-inch incision in the chest wall, without use of the heart-lung machine.<P>The new procedure is the latest advance in cardiac surgery and has been performed on some 250 patients throughout the world. In the minimally invasive coronary artery bypass surgery, a small incision is made near the nipple and extended toward the breast bone. The surgeon, after entering the chest cavity, exposes the left anterior descending artery of the heart. Using a section of the internal mammary artery, which is located beneath the ribs, the surgeon completes the graft, increasing blood flow to the heart muscle and bypassing the problematic arterial blockage. An anesthesiologist manages the heart in a slow, steady beat -- eliminating the need for the heart-lung machine.<P>  	In a standard coronary bypass operation, surgeons make a foot-long incision in the chest, split the breast bone and open the entire chest area. The heart is completely stopped and the patient is connected to a heart-lung machine which temporarily pumps blood through the body. The surgeon harvests a vein from the patient's leg, or an artery from the chest, and grafts it to a coronary artery to restore blood flow.<P>"This procedure is a major advance in cardiac surgery," says Levitsky. "It offers a middle level of treatment in the spectrum from standard angioplasty to formal cardiac bypass surgery utilizing the heart-lung machine. Typical bypass surgery patients recover in hospital post-operatively for seven days. The minimally invasive recovery time is two to three days," he adds.<P>Levitsky has completed two minimally invasive coronary artery bypass procedures at the Deaconess, both on patients who developed recurrent obstruction following arterial angioplasty. In angioplasty, a catheter is inserted through an artery in the patient's groin and directed up toward the blocked artery in the heart. A balloon at the tip of the catheter is inflated to clear the blockage. While extremely successful for some, angioplasty is not effective for every patient, as the coronary artery obstruction may reoccur. The minimally invasive coronary artery bypass technique offers a new treatment option, one that is more cost-effective than traditional bypass surgery, and allows patients a quicker, less painful recovery.<P><H5>Copyright 1996 Deaconess Hospital, All rights reserved.</H5></BODY></HTML>
