ng development. "We will rely on strong management at each Pathway hospital to help us deliver quality care well into the next century," Gaintner says. "Robert Norton's experience and understanding of the Deaconess Hospital's clinical and administrative operations make him an ideal selection for president."<P>Norton received a B.S. degree in Biomedical Engineering from the University of Rhode Island and a Master's degree in Health Care Administration from the University of Minnesota. He is a member of the American College of Healthcare Executives.<P>Deaconess Hospital is a 385-bed tertiary care facility and a major teaching hospital of Harvard Medical School. Established in 1896, the Hospital is internationally recognized for medical expertise in organ transplantation, diabetes, cardiovascular disease, cancer, and AIDS.<P>Pathway Health Network, established in 1994, is a system of physicians, and community and teaching hospitals, providing comprehensive health care services. Hospitals in the network include Deaconess Hospital and New England Baptist Hospital in Boston, Deaconess-Nashoba Hospital in Ayer, Deaconess-Glover Hospital in Needham, and Deaconess-Waltham Hospital in Waltham.<P><H5>Copyright 1996 Deaconess Hospital, All rights reserved.</H5></BODY></HTML>
