<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>News in Review</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><H1>Welcome to Deaconess Hospital Online</H1><A HREF="../overview/index.htm">OVIERVIEW</A>|<A HREF="../patient/index.htm">PATIENT INFORMATION</A>|<A HREF="../direct/index.htm">DIRECTORY</A>|<A HREF="../research/index.htm">RESEARCH</A><BR><A HREF="../educate/index.htm">EDUCATION</A>|<A HREF="../news/index.htm">NEWS &amp; CONFERENCES</A>|<A HREF="../employ/index.htm">EMPLOYMENT</A>|<A HREF="../new/index.htm">WHAT'S NEW</A></CENTER><H1>News &amp; Conferences</H1><A HREF="washko.htm">[BACK]</A> <A HREF="tcells.htm">[NEXT]</A><H2>News in Review</H2><B>Embargoed For Release:</B><P><BLOCKQUOTE>	February 6, 1995</BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Contact:</B><P><BLOCKQUOTE>	Erin Martin<BR>	Maura McLaughlin<BR>	(617) 632-8046</BLOCKQUOTE><P><H3>Study Reports Behavioral Intervention is 100 Percent Effective in Treating Insomnia</H3><P>(Boston, MA) -- Researchers in the Division of Behavioral Medicine at Boston's Deaconess Hospital have developed a highly effective, drug-free treatment for insomnia, a prevalent condition that effects some 60 million American adults and costs society $100 billion annually. According to a study published in the February issue of The American Journal of Medicine, 100% of chronic insomnia patients who were treated with a group multifactor behavioral intervention experienced improved sleep.<P>"The consequences of insomnia include reduced cognitive and intellectual performance, absenteeism, health problems and hospitalizations, traffic accidents, impaired performance and productivity," says study author, Gregg D. Jacobs, Ph.D., director of the Behavioral Medicine Insomnia Program at the Deaconess and instructor in medicine at Harvard Medical School. "Sleeping pills can have serious side-effects and are limited in their effectiveness," adds Jacobs. "Our study proves that behavioral techniques are highly efficacious and safe."<P>Jacobs studied 113 patients with self-defined insomnia who participated in the seven-session Behavioral Medicine Insomnia Program. Patients were taught cognitive restructuring, sleep hygiene, sleep scheduling, gradual reduction of medication, and relaxation response techniques. At the end of treatment, 70% reported significant sleep improvement, and 91% reduced or eliminated the use of sleep medications. These results were maintained at long-term follow-up.<P>"These results suggest that millions of insomniacs can derive significant benefit and improved quality of life from this behavioral treatment," says Jacobs. The results also underscore a recent National Institutes of Health consensus panel recommendation that behavioral techniques be routinely incorporated into medical treatment for insomnia.<P><H5>Copyright 1996 Deaconess Hospital, All rights reserved.</H5></BODY></HTML>
