<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>News in Review</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><H1>Welcome to Deaconess Hospital Online</H1><A HREF="../overview/index.htm">OVIERVIEW</A>|<A HREF="../patient/index.htm">PATIENT INFORMATION</A>|<A HREF="../direct/index.htm">DIRECTORY</A>|<A HREF="../research/index.htm">RESEARCH</A><BR><A HREF="../educate/index.htm">EDUCATION</A>|<A HREF="../news/index.htm">NEWS &amp; CONFERENCES</A>|<A HREF="../employ/index.htm">EMPLOYMENT</A>|<A HREF="../new/index.htm">WHAT'S NEW</A></CENTER><H1>News &amp; Conferences</H1><A HREF="insomnia.htm">[BACK]</A> <A HREF="news.htm">[NEXT]</A><H2>News in Review</H2><B>Embargoed For Release:</B><P><BLOCKQUOTE>	October 31, 1994, 6:00 p.m. EST</BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Contact:</B><P><BLOCKQUOTE>	Erin Martin<BR>	(617) 632-8046</BLOCKQUOTE><P><H3>Genetically Modified Killer T Cells Reported as a Potential Gene Therapy for Viral Diseases and Cancer</H3><P>(Boston, MA) -- Scientists at Deaconess Hospital, a teaching institution of Harvard Medical School, have collaborated with the California-based company Cell Genesys, Inc. to enhance the therapeutic potential of human immune cells. By genetically engineering killer T cells to recognize and destroy specific disease targets and foreign pathogens, scientists may have identified a new form of gene therapy. Reporting in the November 1st issue of the scientific journal Blood, researchers describe the creation of anti-HIV T cells which, in laboratory experiments, specifically target and kill HIV-infected cells.<P>"Active killer T cells have been cited as a critical component in a patient's ability to fight off HIV and other diseases," says Randal Byrn, Ph.D., viral immunologist in the Division of Hematology/Oncology at Deaconess Hospital and assistant professor of medicine at Harvard Medical School. "By genetically engineering killer T cells, we are developing a therapeutic AIDS strategy that works to destroy the HIV-infected cells, not just free virus."  The research began as a NCDDG program project grant awarded to Jerome Groopman, M.D., chief of Hematology/Oncology at Deaconess Hospital. <P>The anti-HIV killer T cells were created by genetically engineering CD8+ lymphocytes with Universal Receptors able to recognize and destroy HIV-infected cells. A principal component of the human immune system, CD8+ cells play an important role in eliminating virus-infected cells and tumor cells in the body. These cells were modified to express two different Universal Receptors, CD4-zeta or single chain antibody-zeta, both of which were found effective in vitro.<P>While immunotherapy with genetically modified killer T cells represents a potentially powerful therapeutic strategy, the scientists caution that extensive human clinical testing must take place to evaluate both its safety and efficacy. The first trial to test the safety and potential antiviral activity of the anti-HIV T cells will be performed at the National Institutes of Health (NIH) and will study approximately 40 sets of identical twins, in which one twin is HIV positive, and the other is HIV negative. Killer T cells from the non-infected twin will be removed and genetically modified with the universal receptors. The re-engineered cells will then be transplanted into the HIV-infected twin in the hope of fighting off the disease. Identical twins are being studied because of their potential for circumventing transplant rejection. Phase I safety results are expected to be available in late 1995.<P><H5>Copyright 1996 Deaconess Hospital, All rights reserved.</H5></BODY></HTML>
