<img src="line.gif">
<center><font size=4><b>The Eighth Annual Corporate Contingency 
Planning Seminar and Exhibition<br></b></font>
<br><font size=4><b>
March 9-12, 1997<br>
San Diego, CA</center><br></font></b>
<br>
Sunday Workshop Sessions<br>
2:00 p.m. - 5:00 p.m.<br>
<img src="line.gif"></center>
<TABLE BORDER=0>
<TR><TD bgcolor="#FFFFFF" width=350>
Workshop 
Features<br><br><br><br>
<br>
These sessions provide an 
opportunity for hands-on learning on a variety of subjects. Each session will feature 
opportunities to apply the 
information to practical case problems.<br>
<Br><br><br><br>
B= Beginner<br>
I = Intermediate<br>
A= Advanced<br>
<br><br><br><br><br>
Pricing 
Information<br>
All workshop fees are included in the conference fee. There is no additional charge to attend the Sunday workshops. <br>
<br><br><br><br><br>
A 30-minute break will 
be held at 3:00 p.m. Refreshments will be provided.<br>
<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br>
</TD><TD>

<STRONG>Session SWS-1<br>
Michael Cannon, CDRP<br>
Boatmens Bancshares, Inc.<br><IMG SRC="photos/mikec.gif" align=right>
Risk Assessment or Business Impact Analysis (BIA), BI&A</STRONG><br>

This is the first phase of the contingency planning program. It consists of several critical steps including obtaining senior management commitment, establishment of a management group to oversee development and implementation of the plan, performing a risk assessment, evaluating critical needs and establishing priorities for recovery. The session will concentrate on performing the risk assessment interviews and evaluating critical needs at the proposed recovery location. Attendees will receive sample data collection forms and will be able to participate in a hands-on case study. An example of a typical Risk Assessment Management Summary Report will be discussed, including business unit priority assignments.<br>
Mr. Cannon is vice president and director of corporate security and contingency planning at Boatmens Bancshares, Inc. with headquarters in St. Louis, Mo. He is responsible for the corporate security and the corporate contingency planning programs.<br>
<br>

<STRONG>Session SWS-2<br>
Regis J. Bates<br>
TC International Consulting, Inc.<br>
What is a LAN?, B&I</STRONG><br><IMG SRC="photos/bud.gif" align=right>
This workshop will discuss the basic makeup of a LAN, so the planner can achieve that necessary awareness to proceed with the recovery planning process. The topics include the concept of the LAN, topologies in operating a LAN, standards and protocols used on the LAN, cabling used, and other pieces attached to a LAN. If you need a tutorial on the composition and operation of a LAN this is the place to be.<br>
Mr. Bates, president of TC International Consulting, has more than 29 years experience in telecommunications and management information systems. Mr. Bates has specific experience in end-user management, systems integration, disaster avoidance and recovery planning, strategic planning and network design. <br>
<br>

<STRONG>Session SWS-3<br>
Tari Schreider<br>
Paranet, Inc.<br>
Using The Internet to Develop an Effective DRP, B&I</STRONG><br><IMG SRC="photos/toris.gif" align=right>
This workshop will present information on how the Internet can be used as an effective tool in developing disaster recovery plans. This workshop will focus on plan development and risk management oriented web sites and products and services which utilize the Internet as enablers for backup and recovery strategies. Those attending this session will walk away with an outline for developing an entirely  Internet-based DRP.<br>
Mr. Schreider is a Division Manager with Paranet, Inc. A former director of consulting services and founding partner of Contingency Planning Research, Inc. and vice president of professional services for Computer Associates International, he is a highly regarded expert in the field of disaster recovery. In 1989, Mr. Schreider was elected to Whos Who in the Computer Industry and has appeared on several television program and written numerous articles.<br>

<br>
<STRONG>Session SWS-4<br>
Ed Devlin, CDRP<br>
Strohl Systems<br>
Presenting the BIA to Upper Management, B&I</STRONG><br><IMG SRC="photos/edd.gif" align=right>
This workshop will focus on the practical aspects of presenting a convincing argument of the results of a Business Impact Analysis to Upper Management. Interactive case studies will be used to evaluate the best approaches by contingency planners in their presentations to management.<br>
   Mr. Devlin is a leading consultant, author, instructor and general speaker in the field of business continuity and business resumption planning. He is a Certified Disaster Recovery Planner (CDRP), a member of the Editorial Advisory Board of the Disaster Recovery Journal and a member of the Advisory Board of the National Association of Contingency Planners. Presently, Mr. Devlin is senior vice president for Strohl Systems, where he consults and develops business continuity planning and disaster recovery seminars.<br>
<br>

<STRONG>Session SWS-5<br>
Barney Pelant, CDRP<br>
Barney Pelant and Associates<br>
Capturing and Maintaining That Management <br>
Commitment to BRP, BI&A</STRONG><br><IMG SRC="photos/barney.gif" align=right>
Do you have all the management commitment you need for BRP?  What can you do to obtain top-down commitment and what can you do to ensure that you dont lose it? Are you really doing all you can do? This will be an interactive workshop to address these and related issues. Such as, what do you do when disaster recovery loses priority? Bring your experiences and be prepared to share, learn and develop your own action item to-do list!<br>
Mr. Pelant is owner and managing director of Barney F. Pelant and Associates, a consulting practice dedicated to business continuity planning. Previously he was a senior manager serving Ernst & Youngs National Business Continuity Program and Director of Contingency Services, SunGard Recovery Services consulting practice. Mr. Pelant serves on the Board of Directors of the Canadian Centre for Emergency Preparedness. He is the past Executive Director, Chair of the Certification Board and member of the Board of Directors of the DRI International.<br>
<br>



