<HEAD><TITLE>San Diego 20 page Brochure</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="marble.jpg"><center>
<img src="line.gif">
<center><font size=4><b>The Eighth Annual Corporate Contingency 
Planning Seminar and Exhibition<br></b></font>
<br><font size=4><b>
March 9-12, 1997<br>
San Diego, CA</center><br></font></b>
<br>General Sessions<br>
<img src="line.gif"></center>
<TABLE BORDER=0>
<TR><TD bgcolor="#FFFFFF" width=350>
A 15-minute break will be held each day between general sessions. Refreshments will be provided.<br>
<br><br><br><br><br><br><br>
Exhibitor Product Demonstrations will be held 12:30 to 1:30 p.m. in the exhibit hall on Monday and 
Tuesday.<br><br><br><br><br><br>
To have a brochure mailed to you just <a href="mailto:drj@drj.com">email us</a> or give us a call at (314) 894-0276. <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br>



</TD><TD>
<STRONG>
General Session 1	--				Monday, 8:15 - 9:15 a.m.<br>
Brigadier General Steve Ritchie<br>
Striving for Excellence</STRONG><br><IMG SRC="photos/stever.gif" align=right>
Turning defeats into victory. Turning disasters into success stories. By using positive discipline and leadership, unexpected crisis problems can be successfully resolved. General Ritchie will demonstrate how a positive attitude can lead to greater efficiency, productivity and problem-solving. Learn how to successfully accomplish your disaster recovery goals and objectives and gain cooperation from corporate executives, management teams and planning groups. This uplifting and stimulating presentation will help guide you through both your personal and business life.<br>
Mr. Ritchie has experienced throughout his career what it takes to become the very best, first as an Air Force officer and pilot, then as a business executive, government official and an inspiring public speaker. A graduate of the Air Force Academy, Mr. Ritchie was one of the most highly decorated individuals in US military history. He is the only American ever to down five MiG-21s, and may be the last Fighter Pilot Ace in the history of aerial combat. Mr. Ritchie has traveled throughout America and overseas speaking to a wide variety of audiences about success, what it takes to achieve it, and how to accomplish your goals.  <br>

<br>
<STRONG>
General Session 2 --				Monday, 9:30 - 10:30 a.m.<br>
Hon. James Lee Witt<br>
FEMA<br>
Building a Public/Private Partnership in Emergency Management</STRONG><br><IMG SRC="photos/jameslee.gif" align=right>
Disasters pose a threat to every segment of our nations communities-- individuals, home owners, utilities, small and large businesses, government services. For too long, our nations emergency management system has relied almost exclusively on government and volunteer groups to assist communities in preparing for, responding to, and recovering from disasters. The time has come for the business community to become a full partner in our nations emergency management system. Mr. Witt will discuss why the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) is actively exploring opportunities to create a Public/Private Partnership for Emergency Management. <br>
  Mr. Witt has been director of the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) since April 6, 1993. As FEMA Director, Mr. Witt coordinates for President Clinton the response and recovery activities of 28 federal agencies and departments. Since taking office, Mr. Witt has led FEMA through more than 125 presidential disaster declarations.<br>
<br>

<STRONG>
General Session 3	--				Tuesday, 8:15 - 9:15 a.m.<br>
John Copenhaver<br>
IBM<br>
Contingency Planning for the Olympic Games - Atlantas Story</STRONG><br><IMG SRC="photos/johnc.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>
The 1996 Centennial Olympic Games held in Atlanta last July represented the largest peacetime event in world history. The planning done for these games was almost certainly the most complex, intricate set of contingency plans ever built! In this presentation we will look at the planning done for the Olympic Games and the end result of all the preparation - the Games themselves!<br>
  Mr. Copenhaver has been active in the d. r. industry for many years. His positions have included the Chairman of the Disaster Recovery Institute (DRI-I) International Certification Board and member of its Board of Directors, as well as President of the Atlanta Association of Contingency Planners. He currently works for IBMs Business Recovery Services (BRS) division, where he serves as a member of the IBM Worldwide Crisis Response Team. <br>
<br>


<STRONG>
General Session 4	--				   Tuesday, 9:30 - 10:30 a.m.<Br>
David Nolan<br>
Comdisco Disaster Recovery Services<br>
Business Continuity: The Standard for Excellence</STRONG><br><IMG SRC="photos/davidno.gif" align=right>
In a dynamic multimedia presentation, Mr. Nolan will describe the elements necessary to achieve enterprise recoverability, the cornerstone of which is high availability of data and technology. Through a case study orientation, Mr. Nolan will present organizations whose business continuity practices emphasize these elements and can be benchmarked as standards for the industry. Management from one of the featured organizations may also be present for audience questions.<br>
Mr. Nolan was promoted to president of Comdiscos Disaster Recovery division in November, 1995. Previously, he held the position of senior vice president of marketing and product management. Mr. Nolan is responsible for North American operations of both Comdisco Disaster Recovery Services and Comdisco Professional Services. Mr. Nolan also serves as corporate senior vice president of Comdisco, Inc. and represents Comdiscos interests on the board of directors of ENET Corporation.<br>
<br>


<STRONG>
General Session 5	--			Wednesday, 8:15 - 9:15 a.m.<br>
Tari Schreider<br>
Paranet, Inc.<br>
Developing a DRP On A Shoestring!</STRONG><br><IMG SRC="photos/toris.gif" align=right>
The vast majority of companies today cannot afford conventional backup and recovery strategies because of the high cost involved. This session will unveil the secrets of developing inexpensive effective disaster recovery plans. You will learn how approaching plan development pragmatically and basing it on real-world recovery scenarios can yield a disaster recovery response plan equally effective as one which cost $100,000 or more.<br>
Mr. Schreider is a Division Manager with Paranet, Inc. A former director of consulting services and founding partner of Contingency Planning Research, Inc. and vice president of professional services for Computer Associates International, he is a highly regarded expert in the field of disaster recovery. Mr. Schreider has been elected to Whos Who in the Computer Industry and has appeared on several television programs and has written numerous articles for DRJ and other publications.<br>
<br>

<STRONG>
General Session 6 --				   Wednesday, 9:30  - 10:30 a.m.<br>
Ken Vander Wal<br>
Ernst & Young LLP<br>
Year 2000: A Disaster in the Making?</STRONG><br><IMG SRC="photos/kennethv.gif" align=right>
This session will address the business impact, and possibly the personal, impact of Year 2000. Is your company prepared? Are you involved? What should companies be doing in the area of business contingency planning as they prepare for the turn of the century? Are there legal implications? Are vendors required to ensure that  their software is compliant for the year 2000? These and other current issues will be addressed in this session.<br>
Mr. Vander Wal is currently the Director of Information Systems Auditing and Security for the East/Great Lakes Region of Ernst & Young. In this position, he is responsible for all information systems auditing and security services. Before joining Ernst & Young, he worked seven years for the US Army in the Pentagon, Washington, DC. <br>

<br>
<STRONG>
General Session 7	--			    Wednesday, 10:45 - 11:45 a.m.<br>
Michael Mulholland<br>
SunGard Recovery Services, Inc.<br>
From Disaster Recovery to Information Recovery: The Dawning of a New Era</STRONG><br><IMG SRC="photos/michaelmu.gif" align=right>
As the year 2000 approaches, the way we process, utilize and depend on information is changing rapidly. More and more, we are becoming a data-driven society, what some have called a data-centric society. This reliance on information is causing disaster recovery professionals to refocus their strategies from protecting hardware and systems to providing continuous availability of mission-critical data.<br>
Mr. Mulholland is president and chief operating officer of SunGard Recovery Services, Inc. and responsible for overseeing the companys operations, product development, financial administration, sales, marketing and communications. Mr. Mulholland joined SunGard in 1987 as vice president for sales. <br>


