<br><font size=5><hr><br>
<CENTER>Monday, 1:30 - 2:30 p.m.</CENTER><br><hr>
<br></font>
<br><br>
<STRONG>SS-1<br>
How to Create Effective Disaster Recovery Teams, BI&A<br>
Ralph Borzyczkowski, CDRP<br>
Borzy Consulting, Inc.<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/ralphb.gif" align=right>
The initial definition and development of disaster recovery teams sets the stage for a successful implementation of your disaster recovery plan. By identifying the proper roles, staffing and mobilization of recovery teams, you can help to insure that your disaster recovery plan has complete team coordination. <br>
Mr. Borzyczkowski is the president of Borzy Consulting, Inc. He has been involved in disaster recovery planning since 1979 and has helped to create and develop more than 100 disaster recovery plans serving companies large and small.<br>
<br>
<STRONG>TS-1<br>
Validation and Testing: A Year 2000 Enterprise Imperative, I&A<br>
Orry DuBois<br>
Comdisco Disaster Recovery Services<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/orridb.gif" align=right>
Testing plays a pivotal role in making certain systems are Year 2000 compliant. Companies need to understand the types of testing that should be done to assure that systems on an enterprise wide basis, not just a unit level, will continue to produce into the next century. This presentation will explore testing options available and when to apply them.<br>
Mr. DuBois, Recovery Center Manager, has overall responsibility for the products and services supported in Comdiscos North Bergen, NJ System Center 2000. <br>
<br>
<STRONG>MS-1<br>
Great Expectations: Managing the Recovery Planning Lifecycle, B&I	<br>
David Johnson<br>
Stelco, Inc.<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/davej.gif" align=right>
Too often, development of a business recovery plan begins with great expectations but ends in disillusionment. Cost overruns, missed deadlines, and staffing problems are just a few pitfalls that can plague the unwary  planner. This session will demonstrate how to manage the recovery planning lifecycle to avoid pitfalls, and to ensure your plan lives up to expectations.<br>
Mr. Johnson is supervisor of security and access services for Stelco, Inc. He has over 29 years experience in the information technology field. <br>

<br>
<STRONG>CS-1<br>
Mid- and Long-Term Psychological After
effects of Large-Scale Disasters, BI&A<br>
Gloria Leon, Ph.D<br>
Victor Koscheyev, MD, Ph.D<br>
University of Minnesota<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/glorial.gif" align=right>
This session will provide a clinical description of posttraumatic stress disorder as manifested after large scale disasters, and how to best deal with this problem to minimize effects. Personal experiences and research findings in the aftermath of the Chernobyl disaster will be described. The Radex North exercise to be conducted in Minnesota simulating a terrorist bombing with radioactive materials taking place in a cold winter climate will be reviewed.<br>
Dr. Leon is Professor of Psychology at the University of Minnesota. Dr. Koscheyev is a Professor and Senior Fellow at the University of Minnesota.<br>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<br>
<STRONG>ES-1<br>
How to Keep Your D.R. Awareness Program Pumped!, I&A<br>
Robbie Atabaigi, CDRP <br>
The Home Depot<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/robbie_a.gif" align=right>
Is your DR awareness program experiencing the ho hums? Are you getting predictable in how you get the disaster recovery message out? Break out your pen and paper and lets get pumped! You will get a glimpse of the awareness programs that are promoted by various companies, large and small,  nationwide. You will see how to spread the disaster recovery word in a new light.<br>
Ms. Atabaigi is a disaster recovery coordinator for The Home Depot. She is responsible for developing, testing and managing disaster recovery plans for various business units, divisions and stores. <br>
<br>

<STRONG>I&A-1<br>
Networks, I&A<br>
Moderator: Nancy Thompson<br>
Comdisco Disaster Recovery Services<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/nancyt.gif" align=right>
This issues-and-answers session will focus on concerns surrounding networks. Both LAN and WAN concerns and issues will be discussed in an open-mike format, allowing attendees to offer solutions and suggestions.<br>
As product manager of Advanced Recovery Services for Comdisco Disaster Recovery Services, Ms. Thompson is dedicated to development and support of advanced recovery solutions and is responsible for continued research and development of A.R. services across all technologies.<br>
<br>
<br><font size=5><hr><br>
<CENTER>
Monday, 2:45-3:45 p.m.
</CENTER><br><hr>
<br></font>



<br>
<STRONG>SS-2<br>
When Silence 
Isnt Golden, BI&A<br>
Michael W. Braham, CDRP<br>
Bell Atlantic Network Services, Inc.<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/mike_bra.gif" align=right>
In todays fast-paced world, communications (voice, data, video, fax, pagers, wireless) have all been bought and implemented to help keep our market edge. As corporations purchase technologies to go faster, smarter, cheaper, what is the effect when these technologies are denied due to outage or disaster? Join in this interactive discussion on how to keep your company communicating no matter what!<br>
Mr. Braham joined Bell Atlantic in 1995 and is currently the Federal Systems Account Manager for Capital Hill. Mr. Braham is the cofounder and president of the Association of Contingency Planners, Capital Area Chapter. <br>

<br>
<STRONG>TS-2<br>
Facilitated Business
Impact Analysis, I&A<br>
Michael Kadar<br>
Detroit Edison Company<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/michaelk.gif" align=right>
Weve heard about them, but how do you actually perform a business impact analysis and complete it in a minimum of time? In this session you will be guided step-by-step through the Facilitated Business Impact Analysis process. You will see how the FBIA gets useful results that guides business continuity planning and determines the relative criticality of computer and business facility resources. You will learn the FBIA methodology and receive worksheets to get you started.<br>
Mr. Kadar is the business continuity planning coordinator for the Detroit Edison data centers. He has 20 years experience in information systems, including eight years in business continuity and information protection.<br>

<br>
<STRONG>MS-2<br>
The Case for Local Alliances , B&I<br>
John Copenhaver, CDRP<br>
IBM<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/johnc.gif" align=right>
With the contingency planning industry saturated with talk of alliances - public/private sector, business-to-business, et., etc. - the spotlight often seems to linger on regional and national partnerships, with little attention being paid to alliances made at the local level. This session will present a case for local partnerships, illustrating the value of these partnerships with examples of initiatives currently reshaping our industry.<br>
<br>
<STRONG>CS-2<br>
Future Trends in Channel <br>
Connectivity, I&A	<br>	
Nancy Bennis, CDRP<br>
TechForce Corporation<br>
Kelly Coticchia<br>
Computerm Corporation<br></STRONG> <IMG SRC="photos/nancy.gif" align=right><IMG SRC="photos/kelly-c.gif" align=right>
This session will forecast the trends in channel connectivity and evaluate how these trends will affect production and DR environments. The session will also address how channel extension can provide backup and recovery for line outages, CPU failure, loss of the data center, and electronic tape vaulting.
Ms. Bennis is a senior product marketing manager for TechForce Corporation, responsible for marketing of internetworking and IBM Mainframe Channel connectivity products.<br>
Ms. Coticchia is Director of Product Strategy and Business Development for Computerm Corporation, handling the strategic development plan for channel extension products.<br>
<br>
<STRONG>ES-2<br>
Current Emergency Management Concepts and E.O.C. Design, BI&A<br>
Terry A. Gitlin<br>
Alameda County Office of Emergency Services<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/terryg.gif" align=right>
Regulations have recently gone into effect in California defining a new Standardized Emergency Management System (SEMS). The principal concepts of SEMS were incorporated into Alameda Countys new $7.5 million emergency operations center. This session will describe these current concepts and demonstrate how they were employed in the new design. The workshop will also address the lessons learned, plus share some of the surprises you can plan to advance or avoid.<br>
Mr. Gitlin, a 15 year employee of Alameda County, has worked in the Sheriffs Office of Emergency Services since 1988. <br>

<br>
<STRONG>I&A-2<br>
Mainframes, BI&A<br>
Moderator: Patti Fitzgerald, CDRP<br>
SIAC Corporation<br></STRONG>
This issues and answers session will be conducted in an open - mike format. During this particular session, the questions will pertain to mainframes. Through audience participation, problems and potential solutions will be discussed.<br>
Ms. Fitzgerald is manager of corporate contingency services for Securities Industry Automation Corporation in Brooklyn, NY.<br>

<br>

<br><font size=5><hr><br>
<CENTER>Monday, 4:15 - 5:15 p.m.</CENTER><br><hr>
<br></font>
<STRONG>
SS-3<br>
Putting the Business <br>
into Your BIA, I&A	<br>
Mark Kemmerer<br>
Deborah Knowles<br>
Deloitte & Touche, CAS Consulting Services<br></STRONG>
Todays business organizations rely on widely varied resources and services to perform their critical business processes, yet many continuity planners continue to focus exclusively on information technology reliances. A truly comprehensive BIA should incorporate an analysis of the organizations business processes. <br>
Mr. Kemmerer, senior consultant for CAS consulting services, is a business operations analyst and strategist. <br>
Ms. Knowles, senior manager, CAS consulting services, is an information technology professional with over 18 years of experience. <br>
<br>

<STRONG>
TS-3<br>
Critical Drills to Ensure Positive Recovery and Restoration, BI&A<br>
Cris Castro, CDRP<br>
Ernst & Young LLP<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/criscstr.gif" align=right>
This interactive session concentrates on the activities required from the time your organization has declared a disaster until it is returned to either a minimal or normal state of operation. A tabletop drill and question-and-answer interaction will be incorporated into the presentation.<br>
Mr. Castro is currently principal of Information Systems Auditing and Security Services for Ernst & Young LLP. <br>
<br>
<br>
<STRONG>
MS-3<br>
Exercising the Company-Wide Business Resumption Plan, BI&A<br>
Ed Devlin, CDRP<br>
Strohl Systems<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/edd.gif" align=right>
What can BR planners do to ensure their company-wide business resumption plan remains viable? In this session, attendees will work together to develop an exercise program to ensure the BRP team leaders know how to perform their responsibilities and that strategies, checklists and procedures will still work. Attendees will discuss different types of exercises and will develop exercise scenarios and measurements criteria.<br>
Mr. Devlin is a leading consultant, author, instructor and general speaker in the field of business continuity and business resumption planning. Presently, Mr. Devlin  is senior vice president for Strohl Systems.<br>
<br><br>

<STRONG>
CS-3<br>
Media Relations in a Disaster, BI&A<br>
John Nevola<br>
IBM Business Recovery Services<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/johnn.gif" align=right>
How important is media relations during and immediately after a catastrophe? It may be the most important task. This session will provide valuable tips in preparing for, and dealing with, the media. After all, other than being put out of business, the only thing worse is the publics perception that you are out of business.<Br>
Mr. Nevola is currently the site manager of the IBM Business Recovery Services Center in Sterling Forest, NY. He was involved in over a 100 actual recoveries in his executive position and has published numerous articles based on these experiences.
 <br>

<br><br>

<STRONG>
ES-3<br>
The First 24 Hours in Disaster Recovery, I&A<br>
Lawrie N. Ackerman<br>
Asset Recovery Technologies, Inc.<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/lawriea.gif" align=right>
Many times steps are taken or not taken in the first 24 to 48 hours of a disaster situation that can make a significant difference in the outcome and successful recovery of a business. This session  highlights some of the issues governing those principles. This discussion will focus on maintaining equipment vital to the company as well as employee safety. Topics will include what to do with damaged equipment and pre-disaster maintenance for vital equipment.<br>
  Ms. Ackerman is president and CEO of Asset Recovery Technologies, a disaster recovery firm; and the Price-Hollingsworth Company, an engineering firm specializing in high tech consultation to the insurance claims industry. <br>

<br><br>
<STRONG>
I&A-3<br>
Disaster Recovery: 
Global Issues, BI&A<br>
Moderator: John Copenhaver, CDRP <br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/johnc.gif" align=right>
This issues-and-answer session will focus on aspects of  the nontechnical disaster recovery industry. Sample questions may include discussion of testing plans, coordination concerns and legal regulations in the contingency field.<br>
   Mr. Copenhaver has been active in the d. r. industry for many years. He currently works for IBMs Business Recovery Services (BRS) division, where he serves as a member of the IBM Worldwide Crisis Response Team.   <br>
<br><hr><br><font size=5>
<CENTER>Tuesday, 1:30 p.m. - 2:30 p.m.</CENTER><br>
<hr><br></font>

<STRONG>
SS-4<br>
Comprehensive Business Continuity Planning, BI&A<br>
William E. Wise			<br>		
AM-RE  Managers, Inc.<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/billw.gif" align=right>
How will your company respond when faced with an unexpected business interruption? This session will help attendees gain a perspective on a Comprehensive Business Continuity Program. If critical business functions of your company or client were impaired, what would be the impact on your financial performance, productivity, customer satisfaction and business opportunity?  This session will inform participants on how to get started and how all critical components fit together.<br>
Mr. Wise is currently an assistant vice president for AM-RE Managers, Inc. and is responsible for the comprehensive business continuity program offered in conjunction with Comdisco Disaster Recovery Services, Inc.<br>
<br>	<br>	

 <STRONG>
TS-4<br>
Coordinated Recovery, I&A<br>
Mike Sneizek	<br>					
BMC Software Consultant<br></STRONG>
Recovery is an inevitable factor in a database administrators life. Ensuring the recovery of a database does not always ensure a satisfactory result.  This presentation covers database methods in recovering databases of dissimilar nature or location. Well cover a manual process of determining a backup and recovery strategy for a heterogeneous database environment.<br>
Mr. Sniezek has been in data processing since 1976 and is currently working with BMC Software as an enterprise software consultant. He has worked with relational technology since 1984, specializing in distributed technology as a consultant and lecturer. <br>
<br>	<br>	

<STRONG>
MS-4<br>
Management Involvement In 
Contingency Planning, BI&A<br>
Mark Avery, CDRP	<br>			
Recovery Management, Inc.<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/marka.gif" align=right>
As contingency planning has evolved, management responsibilities have expanded. This session will begin with getting management support at the start. Management perspective on the goal and scope of the plan as well as the BIA will be discussed. The presentation will describe managements role during the development stage, their suggested recovery procedures and their ongoing commitment. It will conclude with suggestions for keeping recovery plans on managements front burner.<br>
Mr. Avery has over 10 years of direct experience in contingency planning. With Recovery Management, Inc., Mr. Avery has assisted with the development of an  expert system for business recovery planning. <br>
<br>	<br>	

<STRONG>
CS-4<br>
Enough is Enough, I&A	<br>	
Gary Daniels<br>
M&I Data Services<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/garydan.gif" align=right>
This session will include a review of M&Is 11 disaster/business interruptions within an 18 month period. The outages include power outages, cut phone circuits, software, and natural events. Also included is what was learned and what changes have been made to reduce the time to recover. Templates for corporate escalation and individual team procedures will be shared.<br>
Mr. Daniels is the Services Continuity Manager for M&I Data Services, a financial service bureau for over 600 banks nationwide. He has over 20 years of experience in operations, technical support, and data center consolidations. <br>
<br>	<br>	

<STRONG>
ES-4<br>
Reputation Management During A Disaster: Controlling Your Communitys Reaction, BI&A<br>
Jim Gravelle<br>
Jim Gravelle and Associates<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/jimg.gif" align=right>
This session will include information on dealing with the news media during and after a crisis. Topics to be covered include: the objectives and personalities of news reporters; how to control the interview; response techniques; and a ten-point crisis management plan.<br>
Mr. Gravelle has over 30 years of mass communication experience including significant experience both as a news reporter and as a news maker. Since 1982, Mr. Gravelle has served as a public relations consultant, political media director and lecturer. <br>

<br>	<br>	
<STRONG>
PC-4<br>
Certification Programs for Business Continuity Planners, BI&A<br>
Jay Bender, CDRP<br>
William Langendoerfer, CDRP<br>
DRI  International<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/jay.gif" align=right><IMG SRC="photos/bill.gif" align=right>
The contingency planning industry has changed significantly in recent years. In most organizations the business continuity planner role has expanded from a part-time assignment to a full-time profession. This session will address the advantages of certification; personal, organization, and social, the requirements for certification, and the levels of certification available.<br>
Mr. Bender is the Executive Director and Mr. Langendoerfer is the Director of Education of the DRI International. <br>








