<HEAD><TITLE>San Diego 20 page Brochure</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="marble.jpg"><center>
<img src="line.gif">
<center><font size=4><b>The Eighth Annual Corporate Contingency 
Planning Seminar and Exhibition<br></b></font>
<br><font size=4><b>
March 9-12, 1997<br>
San Diego, CA</center><br></font></b>
<br>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Workshop Sessions<br>
Tuesday, 3:00 - 5:30 p.m.<br></B></FONT>
<img src="line.gif"></center>
<TABLE BORDER=0>
<TR><TD bgcolor="#FFFFFF" width=350>
Workshop 
Features<br><br>
<br>


These sessions provide an 
opportunity for hands-on learning on a variety of subjects. Each session will feature plenty of question -and-answer times as 
well as 
opportunities to apply the 
information to your own 
particular cases.<br>
<Br><br>
Refreshments will be 
provided during a  break from
4:00 - 4:30 p.m. 
<br><br>
B= Beginner<br>
I = Intermediate<br>
A= Advanced<br>
<br><br><br><br><br>
<br>
<br><br><br><br><br>
A 30-minute break will 
be held at 3:00 p.m. Refreshments will be provided.<br>
<br><br><br><br><br><br><br>
Also on 
Tuesday<br>
<br>
 Exhibit Hall opens at 10:30 a.m.<br><br>
<br>
  Exhibitor Product Demonstrations will be from 12:30 to 1:30 p.m.<br><br>
<br>
  Lunch is served from 11:00 a.m. - 12:30 p.m.<br><br>
<br>
  Dessert will be served in the exhibit hall.<br><br><br>

  Breakout sessions 4 are from 1:30 to
2:30 p.m.<br><br><br>

  A break will be held from 2:30 - 3:00 p.m.<br><br><br>

 Exhibitor Prize Drawings will be in the exhibit hall from 2:30 - 3:00 p.m.<br><br><br>



<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br>
</TD><TD>
<STRONG>WS-1<br>Disaster Recovery Planning Strategies for the LAN, I&A	<br>		
Regis Bates<br>
TC International Consulting, Inc.	<br>	</STRONG>	<IMG SRC="photos/bud.gif" align=right>			
This workshop will deal with the strategic issues of planning a LAN recovery effort on site. The issues to be discussed include facilities that must be prepared, hardware needs, cabling infrastructure and the data recovery. In addition, discussion will include what areas need to be accounted for when planning these needs. These are the issues that plague the everyday process as well as  recovery efforts. A case study of a network that needs a plan will also be included. <br>
Mr. Bates, president of TC International Consulting, has more than 29 years experience in telecommunications and management information systems, with specific experience in end-user management, systems integration, disaster avoidance and recovery planning, strategic planning and network design. <br>
<br><br>

<STRONG>WS-2<br>Reducing the Recovery Time Line, I&A<br>
Nancy Thompson<br>
Comdisco Disaster Recovery Services<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/nancyt.gif" align=right>
This session will focus on the specific components of the traditional recovery time line. Solutions will be detailed that address the data recovery point and the ability to reduce or virtually eliminate the recovery time. Impacts of networking technologies to the implementations and cost will be addressed. A sample implementation will be profiled and platform specific solutions will be applied to these models. <br>
As product manager of Advanced Recovery Services for Comdisco Disaster Recovery Services, Ms. Thompson is dedicated to development and support of Advanced Recovery solutions and is responsible for continued research and development of AR services across all technologies.<br>
<br><br>

<STRONG>WS-3<br>Realistically Exercising a Business Recovery Plan, BI&A<br>
Steven B. Goldman	<br>
Tech*Plan Associates, Inc.<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/steveg.gif" align=right>
Successful crisis management and disaster recovery take more than a plan: they require realistic testing and validation. How do you do that properly? Are your exercises smoke and mirrors or do they provide as-close-to-real situations as possible? During this hands-on workshop, the attendee will learn how to set up and conduct a successful contingency plan exercise. Students will master the aspects of effective exercise preparation and execution, including the scenario team, objectives, extent of play, scheduling, coordination, as well as creativity and leadership. The class will also teach you how to avoid common pitfalls during the development process and how to anticipate and resolve potential problems that could occur during the exercise.<br>
Mr. Goldman has developed, conducted, and evaluated scores of drills and exercises ranging from two-hour tabletops to massive three-day exercises involving hundreds of responders. He has been involved in all aspects of crisis management since 1978. Mr. Goldman is president of Tech*Plan Associates, a crisis management and crisis communications consulting firm.<br>
<br><br>

<STRONG>WS-4<br>Business Impact Analysis, BI&A<br>
Barney F. Pelant, CDRP<br>
Barney F. Pelant & Associates<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/barney.gif">
The Business Impact Analysis provides the business rationale for developing a business continuity plan. Additionally, it provides the basis for validating the ongoing viability of that plan meeting the organizations needs. However, it is often seen as an impossible task and one that lacks credibility when its completed. This session will explore the purpose of the Business Impact Analysis. Additionally, it will examine the successful methods of achieving timely desired results. This workshop will be interactive and encourage group participation.<br>
Mr. Pelant is owner and managing director of Barney F. Pelant and Associates, a consulting practice dedicated to business continuity planning. Previously he was a senior manager serving Ernst & Youngs National Business Continuity Program and Director of Contingency Services for SunGard Recovery Services consulting practice. Mr. Pelant serves on the Board of Directors of the Canadian Centre for Emergency Preparedness. He is the past Executive Director, Chair of the Certification Board and member of the Board of Directors of the DRI International.<br>
<br><br>

<STRONG>WS-5<br>Developing Disaster Recovery Culture, BI&A	<br>			
Norman L. Harris<br>
Norman Harris Associates, Inc.<br></STRONG><IMG SRC="photos/normh.gif" align=right>
This in-depth workshop combines stimulating lectures with spirited attendee work sessions. Time-proven methods will be presented, along with some new techniques, that will secure the acceptance of the responsibility for disaster recovery by the entire organizational staff. Because only senior management can pave the way for the evolution of the recovery planning culture, responsibility for its success must be recognized at this level rather than solely with the recovery planner. This workshop demonstrates how this process takes place and provides work sessions where these skills can be practiced. To enhance the learning process, Mr. Harris will critique the attendee presentations that conclude the workshop.<br>
Mr. Harris, chairman and CEO of Norman Harris Associates, Inc., the parent company of Harris Disaster Recovery Associates, is recognized as a leader in information technology management and as the founder of the disaster recovery planning industry. He co-founded Crisis Magazine, one of the first disaster recovery publications in the industry. In addition, he founded HSH, Inc., which became the largest disaster recovery planning company in the U.S. and was co-founder of one of the leading advanced technology computer consulting firms in the country.  <br>
<br>





