<HEAD>
<TITLE>1995 Alternate Site Survey </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUND="stone.jpg">
<title>Disaster Recovery Journal</title>
<img src="line.gif"><br>
<center><img src="drjlogo.gif"><font size=6><br>
<font size=4><i><B><STRONG>The Journal Dedicated to Business Continuity</STRONG></B></i><br></center>
<img src="line.gif">

<font size=4><center><strong>ALTERNATE SITE SURVEY<br><br></center></font size></strong><font size=2>
With the growth of the disaster recovery industry, our survey of alternative site vendors has also grown. The comparative matrix on these following pages were compiled directly from responses to a set of surveys sent out to disaster recovery vendors.<br>
The categories address some of the issues pertinent to selecting an alternative site. The survey is not intended to give you all the criteria to select a site, but rather to determine which companies may be best suited to your company's needs.
An alternative site selection process only begins with examining the survey; the most important step is discussing your needs with a representative from those companies that interest you.<br><br>
The survey addresses these questions:<br>
Location: all locations where a hot site, cold site or office work recovery site is located.<br>

Host Mainframe & Midrange Computers/DASD Units/Tape Drives/Frontenal Processors/Dataline/Voice Lines: the equipment listed in these columns are available at some or all hot site locations. This information should be used to determine if a company supports your type of systems. Responses from different companies may not be directly comparable; contact a company representative for complete computer and communications configurations.<br>
Mobile Site: indicates availability of a computer-ready cold-site which can be transported to a desired location. Size and delivery time are also listed.<br>
Cold Site: indicates availability of a data processing site that is not pre-equipped with computer systems. Equipment and resources must be installed in such a facility to duplicate the critical business functions of an organization. Additional information details how well the site is equipped.<br>
Office Work Space: indicates availability of work areas for end-users. Office work space is usually used for critical business operations that are not data processing intensive, such as customer service. Available equipment is also listed.<br><br>
<hr><font  size=4><center>
To View the Survey you will need to<strong> Print all of the files out!</strong><br></center><br>
The survey is in a 2-page spread so the files on the right correspond to the files to the left of them in the table below.  They may be a little difficult to follow so I have added another company column on the right file in an attempt to clear up any confusion.   If you still have difficulties you can call our office at (314) 894-0276 or <a href="mailto:drj@mo.net">e-mail</a> us and we will fax you a copy of this survey.<br><br><br><center><blockquote>
